<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> This Promotion Really Cuts Mustard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bill Veeck would have relished this: a machine  
that shoots bagged hot dogs into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Real ones.  
</P>
<P>
	Fully cooked.  
</P>
<P>
	With mustard, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The frankfurters are sent flying from a 3-foot long plastic  
tube, a hot dog-shaped launcher. They soar 110 feet into the 
stands, and the good news is nobody gets hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	In Philadelphia, the first team to buy into this scheme, the hot  
dogs are shot into the crowd by the Phillies Phanatic. Was that 
cute, green, fuzzy character inhibited about aiming this 
bazooka-looking contraption at the fans? 
</P>
<P>
	``Inhibited?'' says Doug Verb, whose company, Action Sports  
America, sends the hot dogs soaring. ``Are you kidding? He's the 
Phanatic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis Cardinals and Anaheim Angels are also in the  
flying frankfurter business and so are a bunch of minor league 
teams from the Durham Bulls to the Lansing Lugnuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Now this might seem off the chart to some buttoned-down teams,  
and certainly Verb has met pockets of resistance from those who 
disdain gimmickry. 
</P>
<P>
	So did Veeck when he sent a midget to bat and installed showers  
in the bleachers at Comiskey Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``What can be so terrible?'' Verb said. ``What's the worst thing  
that can happen? The hot dog doesn't fire? If nothing happens, it's 
still funny. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people are progressive and want to do new things. Look at  
the Diamondbacks' ballpark in Arizona. It has a pool and hot tub. 
Is that such an outlandish idea? I don't think so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was with this in mind that Verb also began the world's  
largest jersey promotions, inviting fans to sign their favorite 
team shirt. It's sort of an autograph session in reverse. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the 15-foot high creations hung on Yankee Stadium during  
the playoffs a couple of years ago. That's when Verb learned there 
are 80 pinstripes on the classic Yankees jersey and each is 
considerably larger when the jersey measures 22 feet across the 
shoulders. 
</P>
<P>
	This all started innocently enough when Verb, a reformed sports  
writer, was working for the Chicago Sting soccer team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Soccer needed total entertainment,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	He was open to any and all ideas -- piped-in music, halftime  
promotions -- and they worked. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about the fun of the game and fun for the fans,''  
Verb said. ``We wanted to get the crowd involved and make it fun. 
We knew if we did that, they'd come back. And they did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Michael Jordan's first two years in Chicago, the Sting  
averaged larger crowds than the Bulls and the Blackhawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``And this,'' Verb said, ``was with a team that didn't make the  
playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Verb is always shopping for ways to entertain customers.  
</P>
<P>
	``I love anything that's new and different,'' he said. ``I like  
to think I have boundaries, but I can't think of anything I've ever 
said `no,' to.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
