<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lady Boilermakers Make World Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- Katie Douglas and Camille Cooper  
of NCAA champion Purdue were among 12 players chosen Monday for the 
U.S. women's basketball team that will play in the World University 
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas, who made the all-Final Four team, and Cooper were key  
figures in Purdue's 34-1 season that ended with a 62-45 victory 
over Duke in the national championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trying to win a gold medal is going to mean a lot,'' Douglas  
said. ``It's going to mean you're the best team in the world. We 
won the national championship and we were the best team in the 
country this past season, but this is bigger than that. You're 
competing against the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twins Kelly and Coco Miller of Final Four participant Georgia  
also made the team, which was chosen after six days of tryouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Also selected were LaQuanda Barksdale of North Carolina,  
Rasheeda Clark of Pepperdine, Helen Darling of Penn State, Janae 
Hubbard of UCLA, Brandi McCain of Florida, Ruth Riley of Notre 
Dame, Ayana Walker of Louisiana Tech and Brooke Wyckoff of Florida 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State's Rene Portland will coach the U.S. team. The World  
University Games, open to athletes ages 17-28, are July 1-13 in 
Palma de Mallorca, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwina Brown of Texas and Lynn Pride of Kansas also took part in  
the trials and were selected as the first two members of the Pan 
American Games team. The rest of that team will be selected from a 
pool of players available after the WNBA teams finalize their 
rosters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pan American Games basketball competition is July 30-Aug. 8  
in Winnipeg, Manitoba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
