<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Drug Kingpin Found Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- An accused drug kingpin was convicted Monday of  
running a nine-year conspiracy that federal prosecutors say put 
three tons of cocaine on Chicago's streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal sentencing guidelines call for a mandatory life sentence  
for Nate Hill, 32. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Hill was the top supplier of cocaine to both  
the Gangster Disciples and Vice Lords street gangs for many years 
but was never a member of any gang himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, who hid from prosecutors for more than a year in the  
African nation of Guinea, was convicted by a federal court jury 
that had deliberated for more than two days. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill was convicted of conspiracy, masterminding a criminal  
enterprise, plotting to defraud the government out of tax money and 
money laundering. He was acquitted of conspiring to launder money, 
and the jurors could not reach a verdict on a charge of attempting 
to possess drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Two dozen members of Hill's drug ring have been convicted over  
the last three years, according to Randall Samborn, a spokesman for 
the U.S. attorney's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
