<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 35.10 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were falling broadly today amid weakness  
among Internet and bank shares as investors awaited the next 
indication of whether inflation is threatening the vibrant U.S. 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 35.10 at 10,794.18. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 6.70 at 1,323.59, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was down 37.51 at 2,482.63. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks led the Nasdaq's decline as investors shed some  
high-priced stocks in search of bargains among less well-known 
issues. Yahoo fell 8 1/8 to 143 3/16, and DoubleClick tumbled 9 3/4 to 
97 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank stocks, which typically suffer during periods of higher  
interest rates, were hit for a different reason today. Credit 
Suisse First Boston downgraded the group, citing concern about the 
banks' preparation for the Year 2000 computer bug. Citigroup fell 
2 1/2 to 65 5/16, and Chase Manhattan fell 2 11/16 to 76 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline stocks fell after BT Alex Brown downgraded several  
carriers. Analyst Susan Donofrio said weak revenue trends and more 
expensive fuel should hamper results in the second half of 1999. 
AMR Corp., the parent of American Airlines, fell 1 1/16 to 65 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors spent last week on the sidelines, weighing the Federal  
Reserve's decision Tuesday to leave interest rates unchanged. But 
in determining that inflation is not currently enough of a threat 
to justify an increase in rates, Fed policy-makers also said they 
are ready to raise interest rates if inflation is rekindled. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, it appeared that investors are continuing their own  
watch. One bright sign was a weekend report that gasoline prices 
declined in the latest survey after a 2 1/2 month rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will report later this week on initial jobless  
claims, gross domestic product, personal income and spending, and 
traders are content to wait until at least one of those reports 
offers some answers to the lingering questions about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Merger-and-acquisition activity was unusually quiet for a  
Monday. Cendant rose 1/8 to 19 5/16 after Avis Rent A Car agreed to 
buy Cendant's auto fleet leasing and fuel card businesses for about 
$1.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 210.5 million 
shares, well behind Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.26 to 634.61, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was up 3.26 to 798.63. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
