<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court OKs Juries for Land-Use Suits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People who invoke a much-used civil rights law  
and sue in federal court over local governmental land-use 
regulations can get a jury trial -- not just one before a judge, the 
Supreme Court ruled today as it upheld a $1.45 million award 
against the city of Monterey, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, by a 5-4 vote, upheld the legal victory of a  
former owner of 37 oceanfront acres in a case that has been watched 
closely by property-rights advocates nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's splintered decision did not give property owners the  
right to a jury trial in all such cases. But Justice Anthony M. 
Kennedy, writing the court's main opinion, said the Seventh 
Amendment right to a jury trial must win out sometimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not attempt a precise demarcation of the respective  
provinces of judge and jury in determining whether a zoning 
decision substantially advances legitimate governmental 
interests,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and  
Justices John Paul Stevens and Clarence Thomas. Justice Antonin 
Scalia, although he did not join Kennedy's opinion in its entirety, 
voted for the same result. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices David H. Souter, Sandra Day O'Connor, Ruth Bader  
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer dissented. 
</P>
<P>
	The future importance of the ruling is unclear. Such lawsuits  
now routinely are filed in state courts, where jury trials are 
available in land-condemnation cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision appeared to offer little clear guidance for the  
nation's courts on how to handle cases in which the local, state or 
federal government does not take possession of private property but 
restricts its use. 
</P>
<P>
	Government has the power, called eminent domain, to buy private  
property for a public purpose as long as it pays the owner a fair 
price, what the Constitution's Fifth Amendment calls ``just 
compensation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And 19 years ago, the Supreme Court first ruled that some  
regulatory limits on land are severe enough to amount to a 
``taking'' that also requires just compensation. Such ``inverse 
condemnation'' disputes have been an ideological battleground ever 
since, with champions of property rights squared off against 
environmentalists and other opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury ruled that Monterey had violated a landowner's  
equal-protection rights and that its land-use restrictions, which 
for years blocked development of a residential complex on the 
property known as Del Monte Dunes, amounted to a taking. 
</P>
<P>
	The city had disallowed development because the area has natural  
buckwheat plants, the only known habitat of the Smith Blue 
Butterfly, an endangered species. 
</P>
<P>
	Although it was disputed whether any such butterfly actually  
lived on the property, federal Fish and Wildlife Service agents 
said development of the 37 acres would have a devastating effect on 
that species. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the former property owner, however, said city  
officials had engaged in a ``pattern of abuse'' to ``protect a 
butterfly that nobody's ever seen there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city required that about 18 acres of the land be left as  
open public space, and another eight acres be left open as private 
landscaped areas. About seven acres were to be used for public and 
private streets. The city eventually decided that the remaining 
acreage could not be developed because it was home to buckwheat 
plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Over a five-year period, city officials rejected five different  
development plans for the land. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal jury's award against Monterey was upheld by the 9th  
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which ruled that 
inverse-condemnation lawsuits filed under a much-used civil rights 
law are entitled to jury trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court said the appeals court was right.  
</P>
<P>
	Del Monte Dunes at Monterey Ltd. eventually sold its 37 acres  
for more money than it had paid for them. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Monterey vs. Del Monte Dunes at Monterey, 97-1235.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
