<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Commits to Move to NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton says she will definitely  
make her home in New York after leaving the White House, whether or 
not she runs for the Senate here. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady made the commitment during a ``60 Minutes II''  
interview after being asked which New York baseball team she would 
root for. 
</P>
<P>
	``The politic answer, since I do plan to live in New York no  
matter what I end up doing, is I'll root for both,'' she said in 
the interview, which was taped May 20 and will air Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS spokesman Kevin Tedesco said there was no significance to  
her use of the word ``I'' rather than ``we'' since she used ``we,'' 
clearly including the president in her plans, in other parts of the 
interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsha Berry, the first lady's spokeswoman, said Mrs. Clinton  
``and the president have discussed that they would like to live in 
New York, long before she was approached about this race.'' Berry 
said those discussions had been going on ``for over a year now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has not yet announced whether she will seek the  
Senate seat being vacated by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. She 
appeared in New York City on Monday at a fund-raiser for Rep. Nita 
Lowey, D-N.Y., who will run for the Senate if the first lady does 
not. Mrs. Clinton made no reference to her impending decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lowey highlighted her solidarity with Mrs. Clinton,  
betraying no bitterness that her own political future might be hurt 
as she awaits the first lady's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let the governor and the mayor have their petty feuds,'' Mrs.  
Lowey said. ``While the Republicans in this state turn their backs 
on one another, I am proud to march forward shoulder-to-shoulder 
with my friend Hillary Rodham Clinton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Lowey's comments about the Republicans refer to New York  
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has formed an exploratory campaign 
committee for the Senate seat, and Gov. George Pataki. On Monday, 
Pataki said he had no intention of running for the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
