<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets' Isringhausen Back on Roster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jason Isringhausen, who missed all of last  
season because of an elbow injury, will make his first major-league 
start since 1997 when he pitches for the New York Mets at 
Pittsburgh on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen, 26, was considered a top pitching prospect for the  
team and went 9-2 with a 2.81 ERA as a rookie in 1995. He last 
pitched for the Mets September 23, 1997, also against the Pirates 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In eight starts for the Mets Triple-A affiliate at Norfolk of  
the International League this season, Isringhausen is 3-1 with a 
2.53 ERA and has 47 strikeouts in 46 1/3 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen has had his once-promising career slowed by a  
succession of injuries including a broken wrist in 1997, 
arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder and elbow in 1996, and 
reconstructive surgery on his right elbow last season. He also 
battled through a 1997 bout with tuberculosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Isringhausen has been recalled in order to give starters Al  
Leiter and Bobby Jones a few days extra to rest. Jones has 
tightness in his right shoulder and Leiter has been pitching with a 
sprained left knee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
