<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:51:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mail to Some Countries To Cost More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sending packages abroad will cost more  
starting Sunday, although postage for letters will be unchanged for 
most of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Many international postal rates are being increased in the first  
rise since 1995, the Postal Service said. Domestic postal rates 
went up in January, increasing the price of a first-class letter a 
penny to 33 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	The new international rates will boost the price of a letter to  
Canada from 46 cents to 48 cents for the first half-ounce and 55 
cents for a full ounce, up from 52 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Rates for Mexico will remain unchanged at 40 cents for a  
half-ounce and 46 cents for an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Letters to all other countries also will remain at the current  
rate of 60 cents for a half-ounce and $1 for an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	The Postal Service is increasing charges for most other  
categories of international mail. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of sending an international post card will go up a  
nickel to 40 cents for Mexico, 45 cents for Canada and 50 cents for 
all other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	And the popular aerogrammes -- single sheets of paper folded to  
form their own envelope -- will now be 60 cents, up a dime. Their 
rate is the same for all foreign countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Global priority mail, with a 4-pound limit, will increase from  
$3.75 to $4 for a small envelope and from $6.95 to $7 for a large 
one headed for Western Europe, the Middle East, Canada and Mexico. 
For the Pacific rim and South America, the rate will rise from 
$4.95 to $5 for a small envelope and from $8.95 to $9 for a large 
one. 
</P>
<P>
	Express mail will go up about 1.9 percent overall on rates that  
vary by place and size. 
</P>
<P>
	Postal officials said increases will be ordered for the lower  
weights of parcel post, but postage will be decreased for larger 
packages. Those rates also vary considerably by size and 
destination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
