<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mike Tyson Cleared for Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Mike Tyson moved a step closer to freedom  
when an Indiana judge said today she was ending his probation for a 
1992 rape conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	The former heavyweight champion is awaiting release from a jail  
in Rockville, Md., by June 4. 
</P>
<P>
	Jail spokesman Eric Seleznow said Tyson will be free to leave  
once the Maryland Parole Commission authorizes his release. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indiana action was approved Friday by Marion Superior Court  
Judge Patricia Gifford. However, it was not announced until today 
by Becky Wagner, the judge's assistant chief clerk. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was granted parole in Maryland on Friday. Indiana  
authorities needed to approve the decision before Tyson would be 
allowed to go home for the first time since he was sentenced Feb. 
5. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson manager Shelley Finkel said today he'll ``have to sit down  
and talk with Mike about his boxing plans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought Tyson might fight this year, Finkel said,  
``I haven't seen any reason for him not to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson has three fights remaining on a deal with the MGM Grand in  
Las Vegas and at least three more fights with Showtime. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old boxer last fought Jan. 16 and he was behind on  
all three cards before he stopped Francois Botha in the fifth round 
at Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Wagner said Gifford and Tyson's lawyers had agreed that the jail  
time already served by Tyson in Maryland for an assault conviction 
satisfied the penalty he incurred for violating terms of his 
Indiana probation for the rape conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement releasing Tyson from his Indiana probation was  
struck originally in March by Gifford, Tyson's probation officer 
and his Indianapolis lawyer, James Voyles. 
</P>
<P>
	That agreement allowed Tyson to be released from probation after  
he served his 30-day jail sentence in Maryland, Wagner said. No 
additional hearing was needed on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Voyles refused to comment on the probation today, referring  
questions to the document signed in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maryland Parole Commission voted 5-1 Friday to grant Tyson's  
release. Had Tyson served out his term, he would have been placed 
immediately on probation rather than on the stricter terms of 
parole. 
</P>
<P>
	With good behavior, Tyson would have been released from jail in  
September had he not been granted parole. He will now be on parole 
until September, followed by two years' probation that includes 200 
hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson pleaded no contest to misdemeanor assault charges  
following a minor traffic accident in suburban Gaithersburg, Md., 
in August. He was sentenced to one year in the Montgomery County 
jail, and 60 days were later added as punishment for violating 
probation for the 1992 rape conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson was tentatively scheduled to fight again April 24 against  
an undetermined opponent, but his jail sentence prevented that. 
</P>
<P>
	The Botha fight was Tyson's first since his license was restored  
by Nevada boxing authorities on Oct. 19. The license had been 
revoked after he was disqualified for biting Evander Holyfield ears 
June 28, 1997. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
