<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Take Small Steps to Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The turmoil has temporarily subsided for the  
Baltimore Orioles, who are convinced they still can make a run at 
the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore's 15-6 victory over the Texas Rangers Sunday night  
completed a 3-3 homestand that was considered wildly successful by 
Orioles standards, given that the 37-game stretch preceding it was 
disastrous. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Orioles must prove they can win someplace other than at  
Camden Yards. Baltimore, which starts a nine-game West Coast trip 
Tuesday night, is 12-12 at home but owns a major-league 4-15 record 
on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Will Clark will be activated from the disabled  
list Tuesday after a five-week absence with a broken thumb and will 
accompany the team to Anaheim, Oakland and Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played a lot better this homestand,'' Clark said. ``What we  
have to do now is continue to do that on the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to start from somewhere,'' catcher Charles Johnson  
said. ``I hope we can start from here. We're at the point now where 
we have to have a good roll. We keep playing like this, maybe we 
can put five or six wins together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles' last road trip included a six-game losing streak  
that fueled speculation that manager Ray Miller wouldn't be around 
for the duration of the homestand that followed. Miller seems to be 
more secure now, and a successful road trip would go a long way 
toward ending talk of his dismissal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles' mini-surge can be attributed to the revival of the  
starting rotation. Although Mike Mussina (7-1) and Sidney Ponson 
(4-3) are the only starters with more than one win, the unit has a 
3.78 ERA over the past seven games. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore has scored more runs than both the Boston Red Sox and  
New York Yankees. But the Orioles have allowed five or more runs in 
30 of 43 games, which explains why Baltimore (16-27) has been in 
the cellar since April 11. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only people who have written us off are those who don't  
play the game,'' said left fielder B.J. Surhoff, who has a 14-game 
hitting streak and a .352 batting average. ``We feel if our 
pitching comes around and our bats stay hot, we can get right back 
in it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Surhoff, elevated to the No. 3 spot in the batting order after  
Clark went onto the disabled list, will stay there when Clark 
returns. Clark will bat fifth behind Albert Belle, who has done 
little at the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle leads the AL with 43 walks, but is batting .262 and had  
only one RBI during the homestand, on a groundout in his final 
at-bat. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller expects Belle to see better pitches with Clark behind him  
in the lineup. Clark was hitting .370 with three doubles and three 
homers in only 12 games before the injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
