<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Allowed To Regulate Nonprofits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission has the authority  
to regulate at least some nonprofit professional groups, such as 
dental associations, in an effort to protect competition, the 
Supreme Court said today. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the justices ordered lower courts to take a closer look  
to determine whether the FTC properly invalidated the California 
Dental Association's limits on dentist advertising. The FTC said 
the association's rules would bar even truthful ads. 
</P>
<P>
	All nine justices agreed that the FTC's authority to oversee  
for-profit corporations also extends to nonprofit professional 
groups that provide substantial economic benefits to their 
for-profit members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nonprofit entities organized on behalf of for-profit members  
have the same capacity ... to engage in unfair methods of 
competition or unfair and deceptive acts,'' Justice David H. Souter 
wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	But five justices decided that a lower court erred in upholding  
the FTC's decision that invalidated the California dental group's 
rules. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals should have used a 
less abbreviated review standard, the justices said. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's ruling set aside a federal appeals court decision that  
said the FTC properly decided the California dental group's rules 
illegally harmed competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC regulates businesses to prevent unfair competition or  
deceptive practices. Federal law gives it authority over any 
company or association ``organized to carry on business for its own 
profit or that of its members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said that includes the nonprofit dental association  
because its goal is to ensure that its members make money. 
</P>
<P>
	About three-fourths of California's dentists belong to the state  
dental association, which sets ethical rules including limits on 
what members' advertisements can say. Dentists who violate the 
rules can be censured or expelled from the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The association said its rules prohibited false or misleading  
advertising. But the FTC said in 1996 the dental group interpreted 
the rules broadly to bar even truthful advertisements. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said extensive disclosure requirements  
effectively banned dentists from advertising their fees as ``low, 
reasonable or affordable'' and from advertising discounts for 
senior citizens or new patients. Dentists also could not make 
claims about ``quality dentistry'' or say they used the ``latest 
techniques.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said the restrictions harmed competition by keeping  
information from consumers and limiting dentists' ability to 
attract patients. The government ordered the association to narrow 
its rules to prohibit only false and misleading ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the order in 1997.  
</P>
<P>
	Other professional groups, including the American Medical  
Association and the National Society of Professional Engineers, 
supported the California group's appeal to the Supreme Court. They 
said there was no need for FTC regulation because professional 
associations already are subject to antitrust lawsuits filed by the 
Justice Department, state attorneys general and private parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven states backed the federal government, saying they  
needed the FTC's aid in enforcing antitrust and consumer protection 
laws in issues involving professional groups. 
</P>
<P>
	In ordering the lower court to take a new look at the California  
dental group's rules, Souter said, ``the plausibility of competing 
claims about the effects of the professional advertising 
restrictions rules out the indulgently abbreviated review'' used by 
the 9th Circuit court. 
</P>
<P>
	His opinion in that portion of the ruling was joined by Chief  
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, 
Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissenting from that section were Justices Stephen G. Breyer,  
John Paul Stevens, Anthony M. Kennedy and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the four, Breyer said the lower used the proper  
review standard. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is California Dental Association vs. Federal Trade  
Commission, 97-1625. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 03:55:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *James Blades    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- James Blades, a symphonic percussionist whose most  
widely heard work was banging out ``V for victory'' for the BBC's 
wartime broadcasts, died May 19 at his home in Cheam. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Blades also recorded the sound of the gong that was featured in  
the opening credits of films by the J. Arthur Rank studios. 
</P>
<P>
	His recording of the Morse code for ``V'' was played up to 150  
times a day at the start of British Broadcasting Corp. broadcasts 
to occupied Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Blades began drumming with a circus, then in cinemas. In 1982,  
he joined the London Film Society Orchestra. During the war he 
began playing with the London Philharmonic Orchestra, and later 
with the English Opera Group, the Aldeburgh Festival and the 
English Chamber Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote ``Percussion Instruments and Their History,'' published  
in 1970, and two volumes of autobiography. 

</P>
<P>
                          *James Broughton    	
</P>
<P>
	PORT TOWNSEND, Wash. (AP) -- James Broughton, an avant-garde  
filmmaker and poet and a key figure in West Coast independent 
cinema, died May 17. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Broughton considered himself ``first and foremost a poet'' and  
was prominent in San Francisco's art community for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote more than 20 books of verse, including ``True and False  
Unicorn'' -- often considered his strongest and most important long 
poem. 
</P>
<P>
	But his avant garde films such as ``Dreamwood,'' ``The Pleasure  
Garden'' and ``The Golden Positions'' received more attention, 
earning him an American Film Institute lifetime achievement award 
in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	One, ``The Bed,'' focused on an ornate bed in a meadow where  
life's most significant moments -- birth, sex and death -- took 
place. Broughton played a role in the all-nude film. 
</P>
<P>
	Broughton began making films in the mid-1940s and also wrote  
plays for San Francisco's Playhouse Repertory Theater in the late 
1950s and 1960s. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Vanessa Brown    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Vanessa Brown, who made her Broadway debut at  
13 and played ingenue roles in films of the 1940s and '50s before 
becoming a journalist, died of cancer Friday. She was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	She made her first movie at 16, 1944's ``Youth Runs Wild,'' and  
her other films of the 1940s and 1950s included ``Margie,'' ``The 
Ghost and Mrs. Muir'' and ``The Bad and the Beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born Smylla Brind in 1928 in Vienna, her family fled the Nazis  
when she was 9, moving first to France and then America. She heard 
that the producer of the play ``Watch on the Rhine'' was looking 
for a girl with a German accent. She went to the play's author, 
Lillian Hellman, got an understudy part and by the end of the 
Broadway run was a regular cast member. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later, at 14, Ms. Brown joined ``The Quiz Kids'' radio  
show. The popular program had a panel of children answering 
listeners' questions. 
</P>
<P>
	She also did stage work, appearing on Broadway in 1952 in ``The  
Seven Year Itch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She left acting after marrying her second husband, director Mark  
Sandrich Jr., in 1959, but returned to the screen in the 1967 film 
``Rosie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s and 1990s she appeared on such television shows as  
``General Hospital,'' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and ``Homicide: Life on 
the Streets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brown also was a playwright, novelist and a journalist,  
publishing in many newspapers and magazines and freelancing for the 
Voice of America. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Robert Carr Doyle    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Robert Carr Doyle, an Emmy-winning television  
producer who helped launch ``The Huntley-Brinkley Report'' and the 
National Geographic Society's TV nature specials, died Friday of 
pneumonia. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle won an Emmy Award for his work on the NBC-TV show that  
paired anchors David Brinkley in Washington and Chet Huntley and 
later worked for National Geographic from 1962 to 1972, producing 
28 nature documentary specials that won him other Emmy and Peabody 
awards. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked with such figures as Louis Leakey, Jane Goodall and  
Jacques Cousteau on the specials. 
</P>
<P>
	With NBC from 1946 to 1953, Doyle was involved with the first  
broadcasts of national political conventions and had coached four 
presidents, Harry S. Truman, Dwight D. Eisenhower, Lyndon Baines 
Johnson and Richard M. Nixon, on the use of television. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Owen Hart    	
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Owen Hart, the youngest member of a  
prominent Canadian wrestling family, died Sunday following a fall 
at an World Wrestling Federation event. He was 33. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart plunged 50 feet into the ring at a Kansas City arena as he  
was being lowered by cable before a match.. Hart, who wrestled 
under the nickname ``Blue Blazer'' for the federation, was 
pronounced dead at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	At 5-foot-10 and 227 pounds, Hart entered the WWF in 1989, the  
last of Stu Harts' seven sons to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	During his 10-year career, he won several WWF titles, including  
four tag team champions, two intercontinental championships and a 
European championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Hart had recently told a magazine that he was planning to leave  
wrestling when his contract was up. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Robert Rhodes James    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Robert Rhodes James, a prolific historian  
whose books included biographies of kings and prime ministers, died 
Thursday at his home in Great Gransden, Bedfordshire. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes James knew politics from the inside, serving as a clerk  
in the House of Commons for a decade and spending three years as a 
senior aide to U.N. Secretary-General Kurt Waldheim. He was elected 
to the House of Commons as a Conservative Party candidate in 1976, 
representing his Cambridge district until retiring in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes James published his first work in 1959, a biography of  
Lord Randolph Churchill, the father of Winston Churchill. He won 
acclaim with his next book, a life of Lord Rosebery, who became 
prime minister in 1894. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, Rhodes James published ``Gallipoli,'' becoming the  
first historian to use unpublished papers from the official inquiry 
into the disastrous Dardanelles Campaign in 1915. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, Rhodes James published ``Churchill, a Study in Failure:  
1900-1939,'' examined the frustrations and failures of Winston 
Churchill before he became Britain's wartime prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	As a lawmaker, Rhodes James believed in ``one-nation''  
Conservatism, and was not always in sympathy with the more 
combative style of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
