<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Painless Pairing of Black Comedies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One-act plays rarely get major productions, even  
in the nonprofit theater, but the Drama Dept. has resurrected two 
of them off-Broadway with surprisingly good results. 
</P>
<P>
	Surprising, because one of them, ``Imagining Brad,'' didn't make  
much of an impression when it first was done by Circle Rep nearly 
10 years ago. Maybe the decade makes a difference. More likely, it 
is the fine performances of its two actresses, Polly Draper and Amy 
Ryan, that help take the black comedy by Peter Hedges beyond a 
sitcom jokiness that sank the earlier production. 
</P>
<P>
	Draper plays Dana Sue, a good ol' girl of the Nashville variety,  
who tries to welcome a mousy newcomer (Ryan) to church. Dana Sue 
and Brad's wife (she never is identified as anything else) chitchat 
over pink lemonade. The conversation gets around to husbands. At 
first, Dana Sue's helpmate sounds too good to true; Brad does not. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, poor Brad requires constant care. He is blind, has no  
arms or legs and resembles, says one character, a Christmas cookie. 
Yet Brad turns out to be the better husband, a fact that becomes 
apparent as Dana Sue shows up at church with more than just 
bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	Draper and Ryan play off each other perfectly. Draper's  
outrageous Southern-fried mannerisms -- think Minnie Pearl crossed 
with Scarlett O'Hara -- are balanced by Ryan's grave, almost sweet 
earnestness. The two of them help camouflage the obviousness of 
Hedges' plot, a morality tale whose lesson can be discerned without 
thinking too hard. 
</P>
<P>
	The evening opens with ``The Author's Voice,'' Richard  
Greenberg's effective if minor-league musings on the price of 
creativity. Or in other words, how to balance art and commerce and 
what happens when things take a tumble. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd is an up-and-coming author -- young, handsome and prized by  
his predatory female editor, Portia. Unfortunately, he can't write 
without Gene, his alter ego and inspiration. 
</P>
<P>
	Gene is an unhappy romantic; Todd is an opportunist. Together,  
they make for one bickering writer, a man can't quite get it all 
together. Gene desires Portia but wants Todd to woo her in the most 
ardent way possible. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd, dressed fashionable in basic black, while Gene, wearing a  
crumpled jogging outfit, can't even walk. He slithers across Todd's 
oddly surreal writer's garret as if he were a woolly serpent. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Seymour Hoffman overdoes Gene's neurotic ramblings, but  
Christopher Orr, as the hedonistic writer, and a buffed Paige 
Turco, as an editor who wears the season's shortest miniskirt, 
nicely capture the nastier side of New York's competitive cultural 
life. 
</P>
<P>
	Evan Yionoulis directs Greenberg's mortality tale with style. It  
goes down painlessly, maybe too painlessly for a work that seeks to 
teach a sharp lesson about suffering for art. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0039 </DOCNO>
