<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Down at Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Tuesday morning on  
continued profit-taking. Tokyo stocks dropped on renewed concern 
about Japan's debt-ridden banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.99 yen at midday, down 1.05 yen from late  
Monday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 123.21 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 178.12 points,  
or 1.09 percent, to close the morning session at 16,212.37. On 
Monday, the average rose 97.51 points, or 0.60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar remained under continued  
selling pressure from overseas players taking profits on recent 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. Investment banks still have interest to take profits  
following the recent sharp rise of the dollar,'' said a dealer at a 
European bank. ``The market is also undergoing a downward 
correction that will likely take a little while longer,'' he said, 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the dollar climbed to a seven-month high against the  
yen, rising above 124 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.45 yen, down  
from 131.22 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices started lower on concerns  
about the health of Japan's banking sector, a drop in U.S. stock 
prices and the rise of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors are worried that Japanese banks may have  
another difficult fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide newspapers said Tuesday that 16 of Japan's largest  
banks held a total of $171.3 billion in bad loans as of March 31. 
It was the first time that banks have reported the loans under new 
standards which more accurately illustrate the true scale of the 
problem, according to the reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Also dampening sentiment was a decline on Wall Street, where the  
Dow Jones industrial average shed 174.61 points -- or 1.6 percent -- 
to 10,654.67 at Monday's close. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is in a correction or adjustment period, but we  
don't expect any significant adjustment,'' said Yuichi Kohashi, 
chief strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take some time to regain momentum,'' he added.  
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was down 10.51 points, or 0.80 percent, to 
1,307.00. The TOPIX was up 7.84 points, or 0.60 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.3600 percent from Monday's finish of 1.3500 percent, driving 
its price down to 101.23 yen from 101.32 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
