<HEADLINE> MedPartners To Sell Part of Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- MedPartners Inc. signed definitive agreements  
to sell five groups in its California physician management system, 
the first such deals in a plan to sell off its ailing subsidiary in 
the state, the company announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The five units represent about 13 percent of MedPartners  
Provider Network Inc., the subsidiary that manages business affairs 
for 117 clinics and more than 1,000 doctors in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The deals still must be approved by a bankruptcy court judge.  
The names of buyers and financial terms were withheld pending final 
approval of the sales, Mead said. 
</P>
<P>
	The units to be sold were identified as the Inland Empire Group,  
U.S. Family Care Medical, Cassidy Medical Group, Eaton Medical 
Group and High Desert Primary Care. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be no interruption of service for patients of doctors  
in those groups, Mead said. 
</P>
<P>
	MedPartners Inc. agreed to sell its California operations after  
the state seized MedPartners Provider Network and placed it under 
bankruptcy protection in March. 
</P>
<P>
	MedPartners Inc., squeezed by a falling share price and doctor  
discontent, said in November that it was quitting the physician 
management business. The company planned this year to sell or spin 
off 238 physician clinics and more than 13,000 affiliated doctors 
in 42 states. 

</P>
