<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Thefts Let China Build Nuke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China is able to build more advanced, mobile  
nuclear weapons ``on a par with our own'' as a result of two 
decades of stealing the most prized U.S. secrets, and it could 
begin testing one such weapon as early as this year, says a 
congressional report to be released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``These thefts of nuclear secrets from our national weapons  
laboratories enabled (China) to design, develop and successfully 
test modern strategic weapons sooner than would otherwise have been 
possible,'' according to a copy of the report obtained by The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by a select House committee on Chinese espionage  
chaired by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., said the People's 
Republic of China stole U.S. secrets about the seven major warheads 
in the current American nuclear arsenal as well as the neutron 
bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	``China has never stolen any other countries' secrets, including  
from the United States,'' said an official at Defense Ministry's 
office in Beijing that handles inquiries from foreign media. The 
official refused to give her name. 
</P>
<P>
	The thefts date to the late 1970s through the mid-1990s and  
``almost certainly continue to the present,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the stolen nuclear secrets, the PRC has leaped, in a  
handful of years, from 1950s-era strategic nuclear capabilities to 
the more modern nuclear designs,'' the report said. The new Chinese 
weapons are likely to be ``on a par with our own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the weapons China obtained significant information about  
is the miniaturized W-88 warhead, which is launched from 
submarines, and ``is the most sophisticated nuclear weapon the 
United States has ever built,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said the select committee ``judges that the PRC will  
exploit elements of the stolen design information'' on its next 
generation of nuclear weapons, which will be moved from stationary 
silos to mobile locations. 
</P>
<P>
	It said China currently has two land-based and one  
submarine-based mobile nuclear weapon in development that ``will be 
able to strike the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The first of these new People's Liberation Army mobile ICBMs  
may be tested in 1999 and could be deployed as soon as 2002,'' the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has been taking steps since 1998 to counteract  
China's espionage and improve security at the nuclear weapons labs. 
The administration first learned of the extent of China's espionage 
in 1995 when the CIA obtained from a Chinese official a 1988-dated 
document that showed China had obtained sensitive information about 
several U.S. nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said the  
security labs' shortcomings go back through both Republican and 
Democratic administrations, and he defended the administration's 
response to the security problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House ``has moved quickly to try to address it,'' he  
told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The bipartisan report, most of which was unclassified by  
agreement with the Clinton administration so it could be made 
public, details two decades of aggressive Chinese spying that began 
with the theft of neutron bomb secrets in the late 1970s and 
continued into the Clinton administration era. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last known example, the report states that ``in the late  
1990s, the PRC stole or illegally obtained U.S. developmental and 
research technology that, if taken to successful conclusion, could 
be used to attack U.S. satellites and submarines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``During the late 1990s, U.S. research and development work on  
electromagnetic weapons technology has been illegally obtained by 
the PRC as a result of successful espionage directed against the 
United States,'' the report adds.Such technology, once developed, 
can be used for space-based weapons to attack satellites and 
missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also says the Chinese have set up as many as 3,000  
front companies in the United States to assist its efforts and also 
gained valuable secrets about rocket components from two U.S. 
satellite manufacturers, Loral Corp. and Hughes Electronics, which 
remain under U.S. investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Loral and Hughes showed the PRC how to improve the design and  
reliability of the guidance system used in the PRC's newest Long 
March rocket,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report singled out Hughes for transfers of information in  
1993 and 1995 that the committee alleged might assist China's MIRV 
missile ``if the PRC decides to develop them'' and said the company 
acted without getting proper U.S. clearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hughes deliberately acted without seeking to obtain the  
legally required licenses,'' the report charged. 
</P>
<P>
	The 700-page report, about one-third of which remains  
classified, will characterize a voracious appetite by China for 
American know-how -- from nuclear secrets at U.S. weapons 
laboratories to satellite and computer technology it obtained 
through business and academic contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	The report describes a ``blurring of commerce and intelligence  
operations'' by China that poses an unprecedented challenge to U.S. 
efforts to keep China from getting America's military-related 
secrets, said congressional sources quoting from a portion of the 
document. 
</P>
<P>
	Former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who appointed the Cox  
committee, said during a speech to a political fund-raising group 
Monday that the report shows ``the Chinese have made a very 
successful effort to gather up our secrets. It is possible ... that 
this is the largest breach of secrecy since the Soviet spy ring in 
the 1940s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report was approved unanimously by the committee in late  
December, but its release was delayed for months because of 
disagreements over how much of it should be kept classified. About 
70 percent of the original report is being made public, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also describes problems with lax security at the  
weapons labs and says that despite recent improvements, 
counterintelligence programs will not be what they should be until 
sometime next year. 
</P>
<P>
	It contends that the espionage threat from China is much broader  
than the infiltration of the weapons labs, encompassing a broad 
array of technology-related businesses and academia. 
</P>
<P>
	There is evidence, the report concludes, that China has been  
using -- and continues to use -- an extensive network of both small 
and large businesses operated by Chinese nationals in the United 
States to penetrate civilian technology centers. 
</P>
<P>
	There may be more than 3,000 such American ``front companies'' --  
many concentrated in high-tech centers in California and New 
England -- with connections to the Chinese intelligence apparatus, 
the report says. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the congressional panel concluded, China requires  
as a normal practice that many of the thousands of students, 
tourists and other Chinese visitors to the United States to seek 
out bits of information that might be used for military purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	Though not providing specifics, Rep. Norman Dicks of Washington,  
the ranking Democrat on the committee, said it is clear that China 
uses an array of businesses and contacts at universities to gather 
technology information. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's touring groups or front companies or actual  
companies or scientific exchanges, they have a very diffuse system 
of collecting intelligence,'' Dicks said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the weekend, Cox, the committee's chairman, said Chinese  
espionage ``has been occurring for some decades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``More importantly,'' he continued, his committee's findings  
will say that ``it continues ... to this very day.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
