<HEADLINE> Mfume Won't Run for Baltimore Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- NAACP president Kweisi Mfume said Monday he  
won't run for mayor of Baltimore, ending months of speculation and 
cajoling by politicians, business leaders and activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said he left Congress to pursue the fight for civil rights  
and isn't ready to give up the cause. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that my job is to finish the work that I have begun, to  
create a more just and humane society for all people, regardless of 
race, religion, ethnicity or background,'' he said. ``I cannot walk 
away from that fight at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 250 politicians, business leaders and activists signed  
full-page ads urging Mfume to run for the office held by three-term 
Mayor Kurt Schmoke, who is not seeking re-election after 12 years 
of struggling to reverse the city's declining health and safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume, a 50-year-old Baltimore native and former city  
councilman, had been running out of time to decide. The deadline is 
July 6 to file for the September primary -- the real race to win in 
this predominantly Democratic city. 
</P>
<P>
	Former City Councilman Carl Stokes has already entered the race.  
And City Council President Lawrence Bell, who is Mfume's cousin, is 
expected to announce on Tuesday that he is running. Former Gov. 
William Donald Schaefer, who was mayor of Baltimore for nearly 16 
years, had endorsed Mfume but political observers said he may run 
himself now. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said he will not endorse any candidate until the filing  
deadline has passed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mfume said his decision was based on where he could do the  
greatest good for the greatest number of people. He made the 
announcement at NAACP headquarters, leading to speculation that he 
would remain with the nation's oldest civil rights organization. 
</P>
<P>
	As a nine-year member of the House, Mfume became head of the  
Congressional Black Caucus and gained a reputation as an eloquent 
and charismatic figure. He quit Congress in 1996 to take over the 
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
