<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: Thefts Let China Build Nuke  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China can build more advanced, mobile nuclear  
weapons ``on a par with our own'' as a result of two decades of 
stealing U.S. secrets, and it could begin testing one such weapon 
as early as this year, says a congressional report to be released 
tomorrow. ``These thefts of nuclear secrets from our national 
weapons laboratories enabled (China) to design, develop and 
successfully test modern strategic weapons sooner than would 
otherwise have been possible,'' according to a copy of the report 
obtained by The Associated Press. The report is by a select House 
committee on Chinese espionage. It reported China stole U.S. 
secrets about the seven major warheads in the current American 
nculear arsenal as well as the neutron bomb. The thefts from the 
late 1970s through the mid-1990s ``almost certainly continue to the 
present,'' the report said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Hits Yugoslavia Again  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO warplanes roared over Kosovo,  
Belgrade and elsewhere in Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia, 
as allied attacks entered their third month. Air raid sirens 
sounded after sundown in Yugoslavia's three largest cities -- 
Belgrade, Novi Sad and Nis -- and elsewhere. Ten strong explosions 
rocked Novi Sad near a refinery and power station and four missiles 
fired by NATO jets struck civilian targets around Glogovac, 15 
miles southwest of Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina, the 
state-run Tanjug news agency reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Plans To Live in N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton says she will  
definitely make her home in New York after leaving the White House, 
whether or not she runs for the Senate. She made the commitment 
during a CBS-TV ``60 Minutes II'' interview when asked which New 
York baseball team she would root for. ``The politic answer, since 
I do plan to live in New York no matter what I end up doing, is 
I'll root for both,'' Mrs. Clinton said. The interview, taped May 
20, will air Wednesday night. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Young Volunteers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saluting theirs as ``a better way to live,''  
President Clinton urged young volunteers today to preach their 
message of teamwork and service to youths who feel alienated from 
society. Clinton addressed the 10th anniversary celebration of the 
City Year service organization. He asked the 1,000 attendees to set 
examples for other young adults. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools May Be Liable in Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled 5-4 today that schools  
can be sued if officials fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing each other. It found that schools that accept federal 
money can be forced to pay victims of such harassment. The court 
also decided that police who let the news media accompany them into 
people's homes can be sued for violating the Constitution's 
protection against unreasonable searches. It also turned down an 
appeal by a Maine dentist who was sued for refusing to treat a 
woman because she has the virus that causes AIDS. 

</P>
<P>
	Accused Gunman's Mom Apologizes  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The mother of the teen accused of shooting  
six fellow students at his high school apologized to the victims 
and thanked the assistant principal who stopped her son from 
committing suicide. Mae Dean Daniele spoke in a tearful interview 
on CNN. Heritage High School students returned to class today for 
the first time since last week's shooting in suburban Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
	Attorney: NYC Cop To Plead Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of torturing a prisoner  
inside a Brooklyn stationhouse will change his plea to guilty, his 
lawyer told a federal judge. ``We would like to enter a plea,'' 
attorney Marvyn Kornberg, lawyer for Officer Justin Volpe, said 
today according to a transcript. The case against the four 
remaining officers was expected to proceed. A source connected with 
the prosecution who requested anonymity said there was no agreement 
with Volpe on a recommended sentence. The five officers were 
accused of mistreating a black Haitian immigrant. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Decline in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks dropped Tuesday on renewed concern  
about Japan's banking system. The Nikkei fell 153.41 points to 
16,237.08 in early trading. In New York, the Dow ended at 
10,654.67, down 174.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Mike Tyson Leaves Jail  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mike Tyson walked out of a suburban Maryland  
jail today after serving less than a quarter of his one-year 
sentence for assaulting two motorists after a fender-bender. The 
smiling ex-heavyweight champ left the Rockville, Md., jail where he 
spent the past 3 1/2 months. Tyson's release came hours after an 
Indiana judge announced her decision to end his probation for a 
1992 rape conviction. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
