<HEADLINE> Wash., Mass. Get Tobacco Deal Bonus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- Washington state will receive a $100  
million bonus from the nationwide tobacco settlement because 
Attorney General Christine Gregoire was the states' lead 
negotiator. 
</P>
<P>
	The $206 billion settlement, reached last fall, included an $8.6  
billion ``strategic contribution fund'' to reward states that 
played leadership roles in suing the industry or participating in 
the settlement talks. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a three-member panel of former attorneys general  
allocated $394.9 million from the fund to Washington state. Only 
New York and California were granted more money, because of their 
larger populations. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gregoire announced Monday that in a second round of  
allocations, the panel took into account her role as lead 
negotiator in the settlement. Her lawsuit, which was being tried 
when the settlement was reached, was the ninth filed by a state 
against the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, the panel boosted Washington's share to $494.9  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	That money comes on top of the $4 billion Washington is slated  
to receive over 25 years as part of the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states that played leading roles in the settlement were  
scheduled to receive bonuses too. Massachusetts announced it will 
receive $55.6 million on top of $358.6 million awarded to the 
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
