<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Rent Control Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge  
to California cities' power to limit rents without having to prove 
at trial that the controls are achieving their goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, let stand a California Supreme  
Court ruling that leaves it to the state Legislature to decide 
whether rent control laws need to be changed or repealed. 
</P>
<P>
	The state court ruling, reached by a 4-3 vote last January,  
upheld a voter-approved 1979 rent control ordinance in Santa 
Monica, one of the state's toughest. 
</P>
<P>
	``With rent control, as with most other such social and economic  
legislation, we leave to legislative bodies rather than the courts 
to evaluate whether the legislation has fallen so far short of its 
goals as to warrant repeal or amendment,'' the state court ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of a 12-unit apartment building in Santa Monica had  
challenged the city's rent controls ordinance as it applied to its 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	The landlord, Santa Monica Beach Ltd., sued in 1994 after  
requested rent hikes were denied in 1992 and 1993. A $3-per-month 
increase was allowed for each unit in 1993. The lawsuit contended 
that rather than helping, rent controls actually were hurting 
low-income residents by reducing the city's supply of affordable 
housing. 
</P>
<P>
	The city had adopted the rent controls to ensure a supply of  
affordable housing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not considering the question whether rent control is  
good policy but rather affirming the constitutional propriety of 
having the political process, through state and local legislative 
bodies, determine that policy,'' California's highest court ruled 
without reaching the merits of the landlord's argument. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower state courts had required a trial on the allegations made  
by Santa Monica Beach Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the landlord argued  
that the rent controls amounted to an unlawful ``regulatory 
taking'' because it hampered an owner's use of property without 
paying the ``just compensation'' the Constitution requires. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fifth Amendment says private property can be taken for  
public use only when such compensation is paid, and a series of 
Supreme Court rulings have established that compensation sometimes 
is due even when a landowner does not lose all use of the property. 
</P>
<P>
	That line of decisions, the California court said, does not  
apply to rent control laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Its ruling came on the heels of enactment of a California law  
entitling landlords to charge whatever the market will bear when an 
apartment becomes vacant. 
</P>
<P>
	Rent control laws in Santa Monica and the other four California  
cities with so-called vacancy control -- Berkeley, West Hollywood, 
Cotati and East Palo Alto -- were affected by that law. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Santa Monica Beach Ltd. vs. Superior Court of Los  
Angeles County, 98-1512. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0066 </DOCNO>
