<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Producers Say Ruling Not Pertinent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Despite the Supreme Court ruling barring  
police from bringing camera crews into private homes, the producer 
of ``COPS'' said Monday it will be ``business as usual'' for the 
show because it gets permission from those involved. 
</P>
<P>
	But police departments said the ruling has reinforced a move  
toward limits on filming and could lead to more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this may dampen officers' desire to take media with  
them. This is one more thing on the side of 'Is it worth it?''' 
said Penny Parrish, spokeswoman for the Minneapolis Police 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	John Langley, creator and executive producer of the Fox series  
``COPS,'' said in a statement he did ``not necessarily agree'' with 
the court's decision, which said officers could be sued for 
bringing the media onto private property during arrests or 
searches. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``we are obligated to point out, as a so-called  
ride-along show, 'COPS' routinely obtains permission when filming 
on private property and also obtains releases from everyone 
involved in the program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Langley said it will be ``business as usual'' for the show as it  
accompanies police on the beat. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before Monday's ruling, police departments were tightening  
up on camera crews. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the Los Angeles Police Department reaffirmed  
guidelines barring TV crews from entering homes or other private 
property without an owner's permission. And when it comes to 
ride-along requests, a news program would get priority over a 
reality show, a police spokesman said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're satisfied with the court's ruling,'' police Lt. Anthony  
Alba said. ``We're already engaged in a media ride-along policy 
that mirrors their ruling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	City officials had asked the department to clarify its policy  
following lawsuits involving the now-ended syndicated series 
``LAPD: Life on the Beat'' and the Spanish-language program 
``Placas'' (``Shields''). 
</P>
<P>
	TV crews can seek an owner's permission to film but officers  
will not assist them in doing so, Alba added. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Police Department decided several years ago to bar  
camera crews from accompanying its officers because of privacy 
concerns, said Marilyn Mode, deputy commissioner for public 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not aware of any lawsuits against the NYPD, but it  
certainly has been an issue in other jurisdictions,'' Ms. Mode 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shows that feature people in embarrassing or potentially  
criminal situations in which police are not involved won't be 
affected, said one producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Erik Nelson of Termite Art Productions, which makes such  
programs as ``Busted on the Job,'' said his company makes sure 
people sign release agreements. Other measures taken to protect 
privacy include blurring faces or omitting names. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court's unanimous decisions in cases from Montana and  
Maryland said police who carry out ``media ride-alongs'' violate 
privacy rights protected by the Constitution's Fourth Amendment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 13:32:22 </DATE_TIME>
