<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NLRB Rejects N.J. Doctors' Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	After a second legal setback in its attempt to organize the  
first union for doctors in private practice, a labor union says it 
may shift gears to focus on federal legislation to support its 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Labor Relations Board on Monday rejected a petition  
on behalf of the 650 New Jersey doctors, saying they were not 
employees of an HMO. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Food and Commercial Workers Local 56, which is  
seeking to represent the doctors in collective bargaining with 
AmeriHealth Inc., declared ``a moral victory'' despite the ruling 
and said it may try another tactic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that our efforts along with the other unions have  
brought this to a head,'' said Anthony Cinaglia, president of the 
Pennsauken, N.J.-based local. ``We understand that they're 
interpreting the law very narrowly. Perhaps we need to change the 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case has been watched around the country as a growing number  
of doctors, frustrated by increasing control over their practices 
by health maintenance organizations, have attempted to unionize. 
</P>
<P>
	While there are other physician unions, those involve doctors  
employed directly by hospitals or clinics. The doctors in this case 
all treat patients of AmeriHealth. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has never been a question of quality care,'' AmeriHealth  
chairman and chief executive G. Fred DiBona, Jr., said in a 
statement. ``This has been a costly and time-consuming effort for 
everyone, but clarifies a question of considerable importance to 
consumers, providers and insurers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Frederick Nahas, of Somers Point, a vascular surgeon who  
helped organize colleagues to join the union, disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, patients are still going to be denied care in  
lieu of profiteering that's going on by the HMOs,'' he said. 
``That's really the bottom line: HMOs are trading patient lives and 
limbs for profits,'' said Nahas. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if they are successful at unionizing, it may not be an  
answer to their problems, which revolve around stepped-up HMO 
control over their practices, said Uwe Reinhardt, a Princeton 
University health economist. 
</P>
<P>
	``They think they can, as a union, sit there and shove a  
unionized fee scale down the throat of the insurer,'' said 
Reinhardt. He added that it would never be effective because 
insurance carriers in turn would band together to negotiate with 
the doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just simply can't create a physician monopoly,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Monday's ruling by Dorothy L. Moore-Duncan, NLRB regional  
director in Philadelphia, said the doctors were independent 
contractors and not employees of AmeriHealth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Moore-Duncan had also ruled against the union last year but  
was ordered to hold a hearing after the doctors appealed. She heard 
14 days of testimony, the first hearings ever before the NLRB on 
the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has until June 7 to request a review from the  
five-member NLRB in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 38,000 to 45,000 doctors -- about 6 percent of the  
nation's doctors -- belong to unions, up from about 25,000 two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The union filed a petition in 1997 seeking to have family  
doctors and specialists in Atlantic and Cape May counties declared 
employees of the HMO. Initially, only AmeriHealth was targeted, but 
the union had planned to target other HMOs if the strategy proved 
successful. 
</P>
<P>
	HMOs have controlled skyrocketing health costs by preventing  
unneeded treatments and watching fees charged by doctors and 
hospitals. The doctors say forming a union would return their 
control over medical decisions and improve quality of care. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Medical Association, a trade group that represents  
about half of the nation's doctors, shares the doctors' complaints 
about HMOs but has long rejected traditional labor unions. AMA 
officials declined to comment on the ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	AmeriHealth insisted the doctors are independent medical  
practitioners because most of their income comes from other sources 
and the doctors provide their own facilities, equipment and support 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	AmeriHealth, a subsidiary of Independence Blue Cross of  
Philadelphia, covers 270,000 New Jersey residents. 
</P>
<P>
	In her ruling, Moore-Duncan said the doctors still exert  
substantial control how they provide services to the HMO, have 
their own practices independent of the health maintenance 
organization, and have proprietary interests in their practices. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. antitrust law prohibits independent contractors from  
banding together to set prices and terms for their work, but the 
NLRB has allowed unions for some whose work primarily is dictated 
by others, including entertainers, athletes, cab drivers and, most 
recently, couriers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
