<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 06:41:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Targets Yugoslav Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Much of Yugoslavia was blacked out  
and water supplies seriously threatened by NATO attacks, state 
media reported today. Serb authorities urged residents to be 
patient while they rectified this ``humanitarian disaster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's envoy to the Balkans, meanwhile, said today that he has  
persuaded his Western counterparts to allow Yugoslavia to leave 
some troops in Kosovo as part of any potential peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has taken two or three weeks to convince our counterparts --  
the United States and (other) NATO countries -- that while 
withdrawing the (Yugoslav) troops, it's necessary to leave some of 
them behind,'' Viktor Chernomyrdin said in Moscow. Russia has 
long-standing ties to the Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has considered allowing Serb troops to guard some  
historical sites in Kosovo, but continues to demand all forces 
leave the southern Serb province as a condition for ending 
airstrikes that began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott or Finnish  
President Martti Ahtisaari said anything about the alleged 
agreement after talks with Chernomyrdin last week. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his ongoing mediation efforts, Chernomyrdin said he  
will hold more talks with Talbott and Ahtisaari on Wednesday and 
travel to the Yugoslav capital on Thursday with Ahtisaari to meet 
with President Slobodan Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	During Chernomyrdin's trip to Belgrade last week, Milosevic said  
he was still against pulling all his troops out of Kosovo and 
allowing an international armed force with NATO at its core to 
control the province. 
</P>
<P>
	On the diplomatic front, German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer  
departed today for Washington where he is to meet with Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright to discuss ways to accelerate a possible 
political solution to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Diplomatic efforts are reaching a decisive point,'' said  
Ludger Volmer, a state secretary in the German Foreign Ministry. 
``The difficulty is that many actors must by in synch to take a 
courageous step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Western leaders expressed confidence that the air campaign  
was putting pressure on Milosevic to give up control of Kosovo, 
more than 20,000 ethnic Albanians fled over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials in neighboring Macedonia today spoke of what  
looked like a final drive to clear ethnic Albanians out of the 
province 
</P>
<P>
	``You could call it the last push,'' said Astrid Van Genderen  
Stort, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. 
``We don't know for certain how many people are left in Kosovo, but 
we've seen a massive influx.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tensions soared Sunday night when Macedonian authorities tried  
to divert hundreds of new arrivals from Kosovo into neighboring 
Albania by bus. U.N. officials protested and after an hours-long 
standoff, the refugees were allowed to stay. 
</P>
<P>
	In Albania, where an estimated 438,000 people from Kosovo have  
fled since airstrikes began, more than 1,000 Kosovo refugees had 
crossed the border by midday today, according to the UNHCR. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at NATO headquarters, meanwhile, said alliance  
aircraft flew 554 sorties overnight despite poor weather. Targets 
included power plants, ammunition dumps and broadcast relay 
stations. 
</P>
<P>
	In Serbia, 15 NATO bombs hit water pumps early today near the  
northwestern town of Sremska Mitrovica for the second night in a 
row. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgrade was down to its last 10 percent of water reserves  
because of damaged pumping stations and a power outage, which cut 
electricity to the few water pumps still working, media reported. 
Two ``destructive'' missiles hit the Kostolac power plant, 20 miles 
east of Belgrade, reports said. 
</P>
<P>
	The main outages began early Saturday after attacks on a power  
station near Belgrade. NATO continued to hit power stations, among 
other targets, Sunday and today, causing extensive outages in 
Yugoslavia's three main cities -- Belgrade, Novi Sad and Nis. 
</P>
<P>
	Some areas of Belgrade had electricity today, but the supply was  
erratic and authorities were trying to give priority to hospitals. 
This is not the first time the power supply has been hit, but it 
may be the most sustained and heavy attack on the electrical grid 
so far. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb media say NATO is using more destructive bombs against  
power stations instead of the so-called soft bombs that spread 
carbon-fiber filaments designed to short-out systems without doing 
extensive long-term damage. That makes it harder to restore power. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every effort is being made in this difficult situation to  
restore power supply to priority users -- hospitals, the water 
company, bakeries -- in order to alleviate the humanitarian disaster 
being caused by NATO,'' Serbia's power company told the state news 
agency Tanjug. 
</P>
<P>
	Blic, a Belgrade daily, published statistics today from Nis  
saying 32 civilians have died and 210 were wounded there from NATO 
attacks. In addition, it said 50,000 people -- one-fourth of the 
city's population -- were idled because factories were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides demanding that Milosevic withdraw his security forces  
from Kosovo, NATO is insisting he permit the return of more than 
800,000 ethnic Albanian refugees of the 2.1 million Kosovo prewar 
populace who have fled or been deported. 
</P>
<P>
	While many NATO members remain reluctant to add a ground  
invasion to the air campaign, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook 
said Sunday that NATO must prepare to deploy troops ``in a 
permissive or a non-permissive environment.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
