<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Prosecutors issued an arrest warrant  
Monday for feared paramilitary boss Carlos Castano in the 1990 
slaying of a charismatic leftist presidential candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief prosecutor Alfonso Gomez linked Castano and his brother  
Fidel to the April 1990 murder of Carlos Pizarro, a former 
guerrilla chief who had demobilized months before he was 
assassinated on the campaign trail. 
</P>
<P>
	The Castano brothers, charged with murder and conspiracy in the  
Pizarro killing, have already been indicted for a series of 
slayings, including the 1990 assassination of another ex-guerrilla 
presidential candidate, Bernardo Jaramillo of the Patriotic Union 
party. 
</P>
<P>
	The murdered candidates were among an estimated 3,000 leftist  
political activists assassinated by rightists since the early 
1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A sixth member of President Hugo  
Chavez's Cabinet has resigned to run for a constituent assembly 
that will rewrite Venezuela's constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez announced Agriculture Minister Alejandro Riera's  
resignation Sunday during a nationally broadcast radio talk show. 
He will be replaced by Juan Montilla, head of the national science 
and technology institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Riera joins Chavez's chief of staff and his interior,  
environment, labor and infrastructure ministers in becoming 
candidates for the July 25 election. 
</P>
<P>
	The resignations are part of an attempt by Chavez to keep the  
opposition from controlling the constituent assembly, which the 
president has made the centerpiece of his governing agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	He says a new constitution is needed to clean up political  
corruption, trim a bloated bureaucracy and reduce mass poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN CRISTOBAL, Mexico (AP) -- There have been new desertions from  
the Zapatista rebel army, Chiapas state officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	State prosecutor Eduardo Montoya Lievano said eight members of  
the Zapatista National Liberation Army surrendered their guns to 
authorities Sunday in the mountains near Ocosingo in exchange for 
aid for their communities. 
</P>
<P>
	It follows other cases publicized as Zapatista desertions. On  
March 29, 14 men turned in weapons to authorities at a river near 
Ocosingo. 
</P>
<P>
	But Zapatista leader Subcomandante Marcos said last week that  
masked men presented as Zapatistas had been used repeatedly in 
``desertions'' and had given false identities and hometowns to 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zapatista rebels are demanding that the government pay  
greater attention and give more autonomy to Chiapas' poor Indian 
communities. Peace talks have been stalled since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- At least 9,000 Peruvians fear detention  
because of arrest warrants for terrorism pending against them six 
years after political violence fell sharply, a human rights group 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government imprisoned thousands of suspected leftist Shining  
Path and Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement rebels and issued 
arrest warrants for thousands more during a bloody war that has 
left 30,000 dead since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the capture of rebel leaders in the early 1990s and the  
near end of the war, the arrest warrants remain on the books, 
forcing those accused to live in fear, said Jose Ramirez of Peru's 
Pro-Human Rights Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez said the government should review the warrants because  
most named are innocent and often cannot get jobs, travel freely or 
vote because of the warrants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
