<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally mixed  
Monday, with prices rising in Tokyo and Hong Kong, but slumping in 
Kuala Lumpur and Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 97.51  
points, or 0.60 percent, closing the day's trading at 16,390.49 
points. On Friday, the average closed up 92.99 points, or 0.57 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo market opened moderately weaker on futures-led  
profit-taking and hedge selling, but soon rebounded on the view 
that the downside remains solid. After modest fluctuations, the 
Nikkei average moved into positive territory toward the closing 
bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen despite  
profit-taking in reaction to last week's surge to seven-month 
highs. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 124.04 yen in late afternoon trading,  
up 0.28 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its level of 
124.01 yen late Friday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong rebounded after three straight  
sessions of declines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 164.72 points, or 1.3 percent, to 12,436.86. On 
Friday, the index had slumped 103.28 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said bargain-hunting pushed prices higher following  
recent declines that were triggered by worries over a possible rise 
in interest rates in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Any change in U.S. rates usually leads to a similar move in Hong  
Kong because the local currency is linked to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian shares closed sharply higher as foreign and local  
funds bought stocks in reaction to the smooth start of the 
country's election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Stock Exchange's Composite Index rose 3.7 percent,  
or 21.977, to close at a 22-month high of 613.641. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia will hold general elections on June 7.  
</P>
<P>
	Malaysian shares closed sharply lower as retailers took profit  
following spectacular gains last week, traders said. The benchmark 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, fell 26.45 
points, or 3.4 percent, to 743.34. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korean share prices closed sharply lower in reaction to  
the fall of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar. A weaker yen 
undermines the competitiveness of South Korean companies against 
Japanese rivals in key industries such as semiconductors, steel and 
shipbuilding. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 14.89 points, or 2.1  
percent, to 695.60. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher on bargain-hunting,  
triggered by a fresh cut in key central bank overnight rates. The 
30-company Philippine Stock Exchange rose 28.34 points, or 1.2 
percent, to 2,405.47. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mixed as institutional players  
took a cautious approach to the market. The Straits Times Index 
fell 1.1 percent, or 20.50 points, to 1,932.80. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower. The market's key Weighted  
Stock Price Index fell 18.46 points, or 0.3 percent, to 7,588.23. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly higher. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 8.14 points, or 0.3 percent, 
to 2,156.97. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed marginally lower on very  
thin volume, with most investors choosing to sit on the sidelines, 
dealers said. The All Ordinaries Index slipped 1.5 points to 
2,949.2. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stock prices closed mixed. The SET index fell 9.35  
points, or 2 percent, to 469.98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
