<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cherokee Nation Will Hold Runoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAHLEQUAH, Okla. (AP) -- The Cherokee Nation will hold a runoff  
election this summer to choose a chief, a vote considered a key 
step toward ending turmoil in the government of the nation's 
second-largest tribe. 
</P>
<P>
	Incumbent chief Joe Byrd finished first among nine candidates  
with 32 percent -- or 4,140 votes -- during Saturday's election. 
Challenger Chad Smith received 19 percent, or 2,535 votes, and 
candidate Pat Ragsdale placed third with 16 percent, or 2,162 
votes. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd and Smith will face each other in a July 24 runoff, when a  
deputy chief will also be selected. 
</P>
<P>
	Electronic voting devices were used for the first time Saturday  
by the Cherokee Nation, which has 200,000 members and is second in 
size only to the Navajo Nation. Half of its 26,000 registered 
voters cast ballots. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the outcome was unusual.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is in the Cherokee tradition to vote for the incumbent,''  
he said. ``But in other chief races, we didn't have to go through a 
runoff. This is a very big victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many candidates have been key figures in a government feud.  
</P>
<P>
	For instance, Ragsdale was tribal marshal until Byrd fired him  
in 1997 for serving a search warrant on Cherokee administrative 
offices, then alleging impropriety. And Smith, a lawyer, was 
arrested when he tried to stop Byrd's administration from closing 
the tribe's courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Interior Secretary attempted to negotiate a truce, but  
the conflicts continued with millions of federal dollars 
unaccounted for and boycotts of tribal meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
