<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement With DeLorean Trustee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A long-running lawsuit on behalf of DeLorean  
Motor Co.'s creditors has been settled, marking the end of the 
defunct automaker's financial battles. 
</P>
<P>
	Accounting firm Arthur Andersen has agreed to pay $27.8 million  
as part of a settlement on behalf of DeLorean's creditors, DeLorean 
trustee David W. Allard Jr. said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is an excellent settlement for the creditors,''  
Allard said. ``The creditors that I've spoken to are exceedingly 
pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the settlement, reached today, will take care of about  
90 percent of the roughly 260 creditors' bills. Except for a few 
loose ends, he said this marks the end of the litigation on behalf 
of the creditors that began more than a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLorean owed an estimated $86 million to creditors when  
litigation began. Through previous paybacks, that figure dropped to 
$78 million -- $60 million of which was owed to the company's two 
largest creditors, Allard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's settlement is subject to approval in bankruptcy court  
in Detroit, which is where the bankruptcy court filing was 
originally made, Arthur Andersen spokesman Robert Hubbell said. It 
is expected to take 30 to 60 days for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit -- first filed in federal court in 1985 -- stemmed  
from allegations that Andersen signed off on DeLorean's financial 
statements despite potential evidence of fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1998, a New York State Supreme Court jury found in  
favor of DeLorean's trustee, ordering Arthur Andersen to pay $46.2 
million. The accounting firm had filed a motion asking the court to 
set aside the verdict, but the two sides reached the settlement 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	John DeLorean's car manufacturing enterprise went bankrupt 17  
years ago, leaving a trail of unpaid bills. Plaintiff-creditors had 
suggested that DeLorean ripped off millions, and that Arthur 
Andersen auditors knew about it or should have. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLorean never has been convicted of fraud and Arthur Andersen  
has admitted no wrongdoing. In the settlement, the firm did not 
admit any liability. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate related lawsuit, the British government sued  
Arthur Andersen in 1985, alleging the accountants should have done 
more to warn the government about DeLorean's financial condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Economic Development, which is the successor  
to the Industrial Development Board of Northern Ireland received a 
settlement in that suit in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s, DeLorean Motor Co. formed a subsidiary in Belfast,  
Northern Ireland, and the British government poured $160 million 
into it via grants and loans based on the promise of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimates of the payout Andersen was to make to the government  
ranged from $31 million to $37 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 08:43:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Ride-Alongs Violate Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police can be sued for letting TV camera crews  
and other journalists accompany them into people's homes to observe 
arrests or searches, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous decisions in cases from Montana and Maryland said  
police who authorize and carry out such ``media ride-alongs'' 
violate privacy rights protected by the Constitution's Fourth 
Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a violation of the Fourth Amendment for police to bring  
members of the media or other third parties into a home during the 
execution of a warrant when the presence of the third parties in 
the home was not in aid of the execution of the warrant,'' Chief 
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a scene repeated countless times daily across America:  
Police officers burst into a house or some other private place and 
seek their quarry. A court-issued warrant or emergency 
circumstances give police that authority, but lower courts had 
disagreed whether police may take the news media with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardly new, such ride-alongs have been given higher visibility  
in recent years by true-life television programs focusing on police 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's decision means law enforcement officers can be forced to  
pay monetary damages for violating the Fourth Amendment's ban on 
unreasonable searches and seizures. 
</P>
<P>
	Still pending before the justices is an important related issue:  
Can the journalists be punished financially, too? 
</P>
<P>
	But the court, by an 8-1 vote, ruled also that allowing such  
news media access was not ``clearly established'' as 
unconstitutional back in 1992 and 1993, when the raids in Maryland 
and Montana occurred, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Therefore, the court said, the law enforcement officials  
involved in those incidents are immune from the ensuing lawsuits 
against them. 
</P>
<P>
	News media lawyers contend that reporters on such assignments  
provide a valuable public service by detailing police work, but 
critics call the ride-alongs nothing more than government publicity 
stunts producing fodder for tabloid television. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four news organizations, including The Associated Press,  
sided with law enforcement officers in the Maryland and Montana 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the cases were argued before the court in March, most  
of the justices seemed determined to stop police from continuing 
the practice. At one point, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor called one 
such raid ``an amazing invasion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Justice David H. Souter declared, ``I don't see why you have  
to take the news media people into someone's home. ... It sounds 
like fluff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision was more muted but hit on those same sentiments.  
</P>
<P>
	``Surely, the possibility of good public relations for the  
police is simply not enough, standing alone, to justify the 
ride-along intrusion into a private home,'' Rehnquist said. ``And 
even the need for accurate reporting on police issues in general 
bears no direct relation to the constitutional justification for 
the police intrusion into a home in order to execute a ... 
warrant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision comes at a time when some police departments are  
taking steps to restrict news media access during police raids. For 
example, Los Angeles Police Department guidelines issued in March 
bar TV camera crews from entering homes and other private property 
without owners' permission. 
</P>
<P>
	The court spelled out its constitutional rationale in deciding  
the Maryland case. In it, Montgomery County sheriff's deputies and 
deputy U.S. marshals took along a Washington Post reporter and 
photographer when they entered the Rockville home of Charles and 
Geraldine Wilson early one morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The photographs, one showing Wilson clad only in his undershorts  
with a police officer's gun to his head, never were published. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers had been wanting to arrest the Wilsons' fugitive  
adult son, who was not at their home. He turned himself in later 
that day at the urging of his parents. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the Wilsons'  
lawsuit against the county and federal officers. That dismissal was 
upheld today as the justices concluded that the constitutional 
mandate was unclear until today's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	A brief decision spelled the same fate for the Montana lawsuit,  
filed by a husband and wife against federal agents and a prosecutor 
who let a Cable News Network reporter and camera crew accompany 
them during a raid on the couple's ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul and Erma Berger sued after about 20 U.S. Fish and Wildlife  
Service agents rushed onto their sheep and cattle ranch searching 
for evidence of eagle poisoning. Berger was acquitted of all 
charges except improper use of a pesticide, a minor offense. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN eventually used footage of the raid as part of its coverage  
of government efforts to protect endangered species. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the Bergers  
could sue the government officials involved in the raid as well as 
CNN. The cable network's Supreme Court appeal has not yet been 
acted on. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Justice John Paul Stevens voted to let both lawsuits  
proceed to trial. He said the constitutional violations were clear 
back in 1992 and 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are Hanlon vs. Berger, 97-1927, and Wilson vs. Layne,  
98-83. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
