<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Belgian Film Wins Top Cannes Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- In a ceremony full of the surprises for  
which Cannes has become known, a small Belgian film about a young 
woman struggling to find a job and a place in the world took top 
honors at the 52nd annual film festival. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rosetta,'' awarded the Golden Palm on Sunday evening, was the  
fourth film by the brothers Jean-Pierre and Luc Dardenne. Their 
18-year-old star, Emilie Dequenne, won the best actress award for 
her very first screen role, sharing it with Severine Caneele of the 
French film ``Humanity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Best actor went to Caneele's co-star, Emmanuel Schotte. Neither  
were professional actors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Humanity,'' a slow-moving, sexually explicit tale of a  
small-town cop investigating a sordid murder, also won the Grand 
Prize, second place after the Golden Palm. It was directed by Bruno 
Dumont. 
</P>
<P>
	But by far, the most popular award of the night was the best  
director prize given to Spain's Pedro Almodovar for his ``All About 
My Mother.'' He was the only winner to receive a standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Almodovar's 13th film was a big favorite with critics at Cannes.  
It impressed audiences with its balance of tragedy and humor and 
its quartet of absorbing female characters: a resilient single 
mother, a transvestite, an impressionable young nun and a lesbian 
actress. 
</P>
<P>
	In his acceptance speech, Almodovar paid tribute to his  
actresses, and also to three directors whom many felt should have 
been among the winners: Americans David Lynch for ``The Straight 
Story,'' Jim Jarmusch for ``Ghost Dog: The Way of the Samurai;'' 
and Atom Egoyan, the Canadian director of ``Felicia's Journey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	None of the four American films in the competition were honored.  
Also shut out was a crowd favorite, ``Kikujiro,'' a lighthearted 
road movie by Japanese director Takeshi Kitano. 
</P>
<P>
	In a further surprise, the ceremony was marred by a rambling,  
disoriented speech by French actress Sophie Marceau, who presented 
the Golden Palm. She went on so long and incomprehensibly that the 
audience called for her to stop, and she was interrupted by the 
hostess of the ceremony, British actress Kristin Scott Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	In other awards, the jury prize went to ``The Letter,'' by  
veteran director Manoel de Oliveira of Portugal. And in a nod to a 
film that was widely panned, best screenplay went to ``Moloch,'' a 
German-Russian production about Adolf Hitler and Eva Braun. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's jury was headed by the Canadian director of  
``Crash,'' David Cronenberg, and included Jeff Goldblum and Holly 
Hunter; directors Andre Techine, George Miller, Maurizio Nichetti 
and Doris Dorrie; playwright Yasmina Reza; classical singer Barbara 
Hendricks and French actress Dominque Blanc. 
</P>
<P>
	Several notable films also premiered outside the main  
competition. One of them was Spike Lee's ``Summer of Sam,'' a 
powerful look at the summer of 1977 when New York was terrorized by 
the serial killer David Berkowitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Also notable was Kevin Smith's ``Dogma,'' a controversial  
religious satire featuring Ben Affleck and Matt Damon as two very 
un-angelic angels trying to make it back to heaven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0087 </DOCNO>
