<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Extends Jockey's Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The state Racing Commission voted  
unanimously Monday to uphold and extend the suspension of jockey 
Billy Patin, accused of using an electrical device to spur his 
horse to victory in the Arkansas Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing stewards at Oaklawn Park had suspended Patin for a year --  
the harshest penalty they were authorized to impose. But they 
recommended that the commission extend the suspension until May 5, 
2004, for a total of five years, and the commission voted 5-0 to 
follow that recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also upheld the stewards' decision to disqualify  
Valhol and redistribute the $300,000 winner's share of the purse in 
the April 10 race. 
</P>
<P>
	Patin had appealed his suspension and $2,500 fine to the  
commission, while Valhol owner James Jackson appealed the 
disqualification of his horse. He said he would appeal the 
commission's ruling to circuit court. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony before the commission Monday was largely a rerun of  
testimony to the stewards inquiry earlier this month. Racing 
investigator Paul Berube testified that static on an audiotape made 
from a microphone that Patin wore during the Derby matched what was 
produced in laboratory testing of an electrical device found on the 
Oaklawn Park track after the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Berube, president of the Thoroughbred Racing Protective Bureau,  
testified for more than two hours. He said he was sure the device 
found on the track after the race was carried illegally by Patin 
when he rode Valhol to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Patin ``possessed a device during the Arkansas Derby, he  
deposited it on the race track after the race,'' Oaklawn attorney 
Jim Simpson said. ``The evidence is consistent but not conclusive 
that he used it. (But) if he possessed it, that's a violation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson defended his horse's showing in the Derby.  
</P>
<P>
	``They can't see anything with that horse (to show) he ran  
anything other than the way he usually runs,'' Jackson said. ``The 
horse ran a good race, the horse won the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Berube, head of the investigative branch of the thoroughbred  
racing industry, testified that the microphone strapped inside 
Patin's jersey picked up static shortly before and after the 
three-eighths mile marker, as Valhol took the lead. That static, 
picked up on tape, matched what was obtained from lab tests on the 
electrical device that was found on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to operate the device at Monday's hearing eventually  
produced a loud hum, after several attempts produced no sound. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also watched a videotape showing a dark object  
falling from Patin's hand during Valhol's victory gallop after 
crossing the finish line. Berube said he was personally convinced 
that the device found on the track was what was seen on videotape 
falling from Patin's hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Under cross-examination by Patin's lawyer, J. Minos Simon of  
Lafayette, La., Berube said fingerprint tests on the device were 
inconclusive. 
</P>
<P>
	Grilled by lawyers for Patin and Jackson, Oaklawn general  
manager Eric Jackson said he had handled the device found on the 
track, and said others may also have done so, just after the race 
and before it was shipped to Berube's agency to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were serious about connecting this with Mr. Patin, you  
would certainly have exercised some caution to preserve that 
valuable piece of evidence,'' lawyer Sam Laser chided. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Jackson said he had no indication where the device came  
from until two days later when he said a videotape of the race. But 
he admitted to a misstep. 
</P>
<P>
	``I should have been more careful, but I wasn't,'' the racetrack  
manager said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
