<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Orders Retiree Miner Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to free the  
former operator of two Kentucky coal mines from having to finance 
health benefits for its retired employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away Robert Coal Co.'s  
argument that a 1992 federal law should not force it to pay for the 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Coal operated two mines in Pike County, Ky., between 1974  
and 1984. During that time, it signed several contracts with the 
United Mine Workers of America that promised health care benefits 
to its employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The mines were sold in 1984, and Robert Coal no longer operated  
them. But the coal miners' union sued the company, saying it still 
was obligated to provide health benefits to retirees. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1988 settlement, Robert Coal agreed to pay retirees'  
health benefits through January 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, Congress created the United Mine Workers Benefit Plan  
to provide lifetime health care benefits. The law requires the 
company that most recently employed a worker to pay for the 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	After Robert Coal refused to pay premiums, the benefit plan's  
trustees sued in federal court in the District of Columbia. The 
company, now a subsidiary of Cleveland-Cliffs Inc. in Cleveland, 
Ohio, estimated the premiums would cost it $8.6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge ruled against Robert Coal, saying the 1988 settlement  
did not free it of any future obligation to pay for retirees' 
benefits. A federal appeals court agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	While the appeal was pending, the Supreme Court ruled last year  
in an unrelated case that a Massachusetts-based company that left 
the coal business in 1965 could not be forced to pay for its 
retirees' lifetime health benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, Robert Coal's lawyers said last  
year's Supreme Court ruling should control its dispute. Forcing the 
company to pay for health benefits would unfairly nullify the 1988 
settlement and would amount to an unconstitutional taking of its 
property without payment, Robert Coal's lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyers said the Kentucky case differed from  
the Massachusetts case because Robert Coal had promised its 
employees health care benefits for life. The Massachusetts company 
had not. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Robert Coal Co. vs. Holland, 98-1311.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boat Qualifies on Indy Front Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- It's hard to tell which was more difficult  
for Billy Boat, crashing for the third time in a week or having to 
explain his misfortune to his boss, A.J. Foyt. 
</P>
<P>
	``A.J. chased me around the shop just a little bit. ... I still  
outran him, though,'' Boat said, joking. 
</P>
<P>
	His third crash was on Saturday as he took a warmup lap before  
Indianapolis 500 qualifications. Foyt, watching from trackside, 
slammed a green signal flag to the ground in disgust, then ran back 
to the garage to get his crew started repairing Boat's 
Dallara-Aurora. 
</P>
<P>
	Four-and-a-half hours later, with the rebuilt car, Boat  
completed four laps at an average 223.469 mph, putting him on the 
outside of the front row, next to Arie Luyendyk and Greg Ray for 
the May 30 race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Billy works hard and listens to me,'' said Foyt, a four-time  
Indy winner, who is known for his quick temper. ``Billy is a great 
race driver. It's been a tough week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are one big family. That's what makes a winning  
combination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boat won one race last year and set an Indy Racing League record  
with six poles, including the Indy 500. Teammate Kenny Brack had 
three victories and won the IRL season championship. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Boat first crashed on May 16, the second day of  
practice, causing heavy damage to the left side and rear of his 
car. The next day, he crashed again, this time damaging the right 
side. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, morning rain, a drop in temperature and high  
humidity produced slippery track conditions. Boat lost traction for 
just an instant, but that was enough to send his car spinning first 
to the left, then to the right and into the Turn 2-wall with heavy 
damage to the right side. 
</P>
<P>
	He was not injured, but had to go to the infield hospital for a  
mandatory checkup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told the doctor, `I hope I'm not back in a few minutes after  
I talk to A.J.,' but he was great,'' Boat said Sunday. ``It's times 
like that when things are down when you look at a guy like that to 
pick you up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boat called Saturday's crash ``a stupid incident.''  
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to look at yourself in the mirror and say, `What's  
going on?' They just said, `Don't worry about it.' I knew we had 
the race car, and I knew we had the setup, but it's been a long 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can appreciate qualifying for this race  
until you go through something like this. There's nothing given to 
anybody here, and my boss told me that better than anybody. ... 
Never once did he say anything negative to me. He's been there. I'm 
very fortunate he believes in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boat qualified on the pole last year at 223.503, and led the  
first 12 laps. He finished 23rd after a bad drive line knocked him 
out after 111 laps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
