<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Commits to Move to NY  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton says she will definitely  
make her home in New York after leaving the White House, whether or 
not she runs for the Senate. The first lady made the commitment 
during a CBS-TV ``60 Minutes II'' interview after being asked which 
New York baseball team she would root for. ``The politic answer, 
since I do plan to live in New York no matter what I end up doing, 
is I'll root for both,'' she said. The interview, which was taped 
May 20 and will air Wednesday night. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: China Has U.S. 'Front' Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China secretly controls several thousand  
American ``front companies'' to obtain U.S. technology for military 
purposes, a congressional report says. It's part of a 700-page 
document to be issued tomorrow by a special House committee 
investigating espionage and U.S. technology losses to China, 
officials familiar with the report said today. The report describes 
a ``blurring of commerce and intelligence operations'' by China 
that poses an unprecedented challenge to U.S. efforts to keep its 
military-related secrets, said congressional sources. Problems with 
lax security at U.S. weapons labs are also described in the report. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Vows To Keep Her Job  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno made clear today  
that she isn't resigning over the handling of allegations of 
Chinese nuclear espionage. ``I'm right here, going strong,'' she 
said. Her future was questioned by Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., 
who has been a vocal defender of President Clinton. Reno's ouster 
had been sought during the past two years by some Republicans in 
Congress angered by her refusal to turn her campaign finance 
investigation over to an independent counsel. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools May Be Liable in Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled 5-4 today that schools  
can be sued when officials fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing each other. Schools -- from elementary to college -- that 
accept federal money can be forced to pay victims of such 
harassment. The court also decided that police who let the news 
media accompany them into people's homes to observe arrests or 
searches can be sued for violating the Constitution's Fourth 
Amendment protection against unreasonable searches. It also turned 
down an appeal by a Maine dentist who was sued for refusing to 
treat a woman in his office because she has the virus that causes 
AIDS. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N.: Kosovo Plight Is 'Worse'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A U.N. team today said it found the  
humanitarian situation worse than expected in Kosovo. Visits to 
more than seven Kosovo towns over three days showed conditions in 
the province to be ``a lot worse than we feared,'' said Sergio de 
Mello, head of the U.N. fact-finding mission. ``Everything 
indicates that there is an attempt to displace, ethnically cleanse 
Kosovo,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	Accused Gunman's Mom Apologizes  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The mother of the teen accused of shooting  
six fellow students at his high school apologized to the victims 
and thanked the assistant principal who stopped her son from 
committing suicide. Mae Dean Daniele spoke in a tearful interview 
on CNN. Heritage High School students returned to class today for 
the first time since last week's shooting in suburban Atlanta. 

</P>
<P>
	Attorney: NYC Cop To Plead Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of torturing a prisoner  
inside a Brooklyn stationhouse will change his plea to guilty, his 
lawyer told a federal judge. ``We would like to enter a plea,'' 
attorney Marvyn Kornberg, lawyer for Officer Justin Volpe, said 
today according to a transcript. The specific charge to which Volpe 
would plead was not revealed. In the case, five officers were 
indicted on charges of violating the civil rights of a black 
Haitian immigrant. 

</P>
