<HEADLINE> Dollar Higher, Japan Stocks Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen today  
despite profit-taking in reaction to last week's surge to 
seven-month highs. Japanese stocks advanced moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 124.04 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.28  
yen from late Friday in Tokyo and also above its level of 124.01 
yen late Friday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 97.51 points,  
or 0.60 percent, closing the day's trading at 16,390.49 points. On 
Friday, the average closed up 92.99 points, or 0.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, strong buying from Japanese trust banks  
and U.S. funds pushed the dollar to an intraday high of 124.39 yen 
early in the session, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar shed some of its early gains after U.S. funds and  
Japanese banks later sold dollars to lock in profits, pushing the 
currency as low as 123.74 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign exchange market mostly shrugged off a morning  
announcement that Japan's trade surplus fell 12.6 percent in April 
to $8.62 billion from the same month of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was almost in line with consensus estimates of  
economists, who had forecast on average that the surplus would fall 
by 10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.22 yen, up from  
131.17 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Optimistic forecasts by companies for the current fiscal year  
through March 200 led to buying of selected issues on the Tokyo 
stock market, although overall profit results for the last fiscal 
year ended March have been poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies think things will be better this year, but  
historically what companies think is not a very reliable estimate 
of what will happen,'' said Richard Jerram, chief economist at ING 
Baring Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerram said there will likely be an improvement in the second  
quarter of this year from the previous quarter, although overall 
corporate profits could be lower this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The market opened moderately weaker on futures-led profit-taking  
and hedge selling, but stocks soon rebounded on the view that the 
downside remains solid. After modest fluctuations, the Nikkei 
average moved into positive territory toward the closing bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 410  
million shares, down from Friday's turnover of 565 million shares. 
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners 606 to 591, with 114 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 7.84 points, or 0.60 percent, to 
1,317.51. The TOPIX closed up 7.80 points, or 0.60 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.350 percent from Friday's finish of 1.325 percent, 
driving its price down to 101.32 yen from 101.55 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
