<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Revises Cadbury Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co. is moving to speed up its deal to  
acquire Cadbury Schweppes' soft drink brands overseas by excluding 
most of the European Union membership. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies said the deal still will cover more than 100  
countries and is valued at $1.1 billion. When announced in 
December, it covered 126 countries and was worth $1.85 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal had drawn criticism from the European Union, which  
raised antitrust questions. As revised, only three EU members -- 
Britain, Ireland, and Greece -- remain involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have modified the agreement to meet the specific concerns  
expressed, both by the EC and individual nations,'' Coke chairman 
M. Douglas Ivester said Monday. ``And we have decided to move 
quickly to make those modifications while maintaining a viable 
proposition for Cadbury Schweppes and us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The original agreement said Coke would buy Cadbury's soft  
drinks, such as Schweppes, Dr Pepper, Canada Dry and Crush brands, 
in Cadbury Schweppes markets excluding the United States, France 
and South Africa. The revised deal now excludes 12 European Union 
nations, including France, and other countries where the 
transaction was being slowed by regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	It still must clear regulatory hurdles in Britain, Australia,  
Mexico and other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Nations dropped from the deal are Andorra, Austria, Belgium,  
Denmark, Finland, Germany, Gibraltar, Iceland, Italy, 
Liechtenstein, Luxembourg, Malta, Monaco, The Netherlands, Norway, 
Portugal, San Marino, Spain, Sweden and Switzerland. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
