<DOCNO> APW19990524.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 00:11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Cheetah, Camel Bones Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELKO, Nev. (AP) -- Cheetah, camel and llama bones sealed in a  
Nevada cave for tens of thousands of years are giving scientists a 
glimpse at the ecosystem of the West before the last Ice Age. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusually well preserved cache from about 40,000 to 50,000  
years ago includes bones from a wide variety of creatures now 
extinct -- from the giant short-faced bear to huge deer and bison. 
</P>
<P>
	``This cave is kind of a Noah's Ark collection of species,''  
said Tom Stafford, a Boulder, Colo.-based specialist who has been 
testing the bones. 
</P>
<P>
	The conditions at the back of the cave are like those of a  
modern refrigerator. Perhaps most intriguing to the scientists are 
the twigs, leaves, seeds and animal hair from which they believe 
they'll be able to extract DNA to compare the genetic makeup of 
past and present species. 
</P>
<P>
	``We could see how much evolution there has been,'' said Bryan  
Hockett, the Bureau of Land Management archaeologist who is leading 
a new excavation at the site. 
</P>
<P>
	Hockett, 37, and fellow archaeologist Eric Dillingham, 37, have  
been dragging bones out of the cave for the past two summers and 
next month plan the largest expedition yet into the 700-foot 
cavern. 
</P>
<P>
	The bones are in the back of a cave where miners left their mark  
in the 1860s. Hockett suspects the cave some 300 miles east of Reno 
was a den for large carnivores that dragged prey back to feed their 
young. 
</P>
<P>
	The find is evidence of the wildly diverse ecosystem in the  
western United States before the last big Ice Age, 18,000 years 
ago. It was a vast grassland where predators stalked grazing 
animals well before man is believed to have arrived on the scene 
10,000 to 12,000 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the bones are from animals which originate from the end  
of the Pleistocene Age. There are horses, mountain sheep, pronghorn 
antelope, wolves, weasels, badgers, coyotes, lizards, bats and 
birds. 
</P>
<P>
	The giant short-faced bear had a short snout and longer legs  
than a typical bear. It was much larger than bears today and a fast 
runner. 
</P>
<P>
	The cheetah remains are only the second discovered in Nevada.  
Fewer than 10 have been recorded in North America and the remains 
may shed light on a question that has bothered scientists for 
decades: Why are pronghorn antelope so fast? 
</P>
<P>
	``There was always speculation that there must have been a  
faster-running predator during the Pleistocene than we know of 
today because the American pronghorn can run so much faster than 
anything living here now that might have been a predator,'' said 
Robert Emry, a paleo-biologist at the Smithsonian's Museum of 
Natural History in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 05:59:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opera Star Beverly Sills Turns 70 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Beverly Sills was, well, bubbling.  
</P>
<P>
	Just shy of her 70th birthday on May 25, her standout recording  
of Douglas Moore's ``The Ballad of Baby Doe'' was about to be 
released on compact disc for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a funny way it's like that career happened to somebody  
else,'' Miss Sills said during an interview last month. ``I feel 
like an observer at this point. In my family, my singing career is 
never discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sills, known as Bubbles Silverman when she had her radio  
debut on ``Uncle Bob's Rainbow House'' as a child, made her 
professional operatic debut in Philadelphia in 1947. 
</P>
<P>
	During more than three decades on stage, she sang dozens of  
coloratura roles, specializing in heroines such as Massanet's 
``Manon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She doesn't sing at all these days.  
</P>
<P>
	``Since I've retired, I sang `Happy Birthday' to Isaac Stern,''  
Miss Sills said lightly -- she last performed in 1980. ``The last 
time I sang I was 50. What could I sound like that would give me 
pleasure?'' 
</P>
<P>
	She doesn't even listen to her old recordings. Even in her  
singing days she avoided her records because she'd concentrate on 
mistakes rather than successes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ashamed to tell you, I don't listen to them. I go to the  
opera. I have my box -- it was once reported in New York Magazine 
that I left in the middle, so I always stay to the end. I thought I 
had solved that problem by getting a box instead of sitting in the 
orchestra.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sills has enough to fill her schedule without singing.  
She's the chairwoman of Lincoln Center, a director of the 
Metropolitan Opera and a director of Time Warner Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	She appears as a host before performances on Public  
Broadcasting, a role that has been lampooned by Ira Siff's La Gran 
Scena, an opera company of drag divas. Miss Sills even attended a 
Grand Scena performance, watching a man imitate her always 
ebullient personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hysterically funny,'' she said. ``He's got me down pat,  
that guy. He had me down so perfectly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sills has become something of an icon -- THE American opera  
singer. No matter how good they are, current stars like Renee 
Fleming, Deborah Voigt and Ruth Ann Swenson are known only by a 
small percentage of the general public. Bubbles, however, has name 
recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	Terrence McNally even poked fun at her in his 1989 play, ``The  
Lisbon Traviata,'' in which she is put down by fans of Maria 
Callas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stephen: Have you heard Sills' last `Thais?' ''  
</P>
<P>
	``Mendy: Unfortunately, I heard her first Thais.' ''  
</P>
<P>
	Miss Sills can be just as biting in her reviews. Even though  
she's a board member, she loathed the Met's new ``La Traviata'' 
that Franco Zeffirelli staged last fall. The singers, she said, 
were lost in all the grandeur. 
</P>
<P>
	``Franco, Franco, how could you?'' she told a group of  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	And she didn't think much of the negative reviews given to  
Carlisle Floyd's ``Susannah'' at the Met this spring. Some said the 
3,800-seat house was too large for the work. 
</P>
<P>
	``They shouldn't talk out of both sides of their mouth,'' she  
said of critics. ``They say, 'Why don't you do more contemporary 
work?' and when they do more contemporary work, they treat it with 
a condescending view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle Maria Silverman -- her given name -- knew she wanted to be a  
singer at an early age. She was voted ``Most Beautiful Baby of 
1932'' after singing ``The Wedding of Jack and Jill'' at a 
competition in Brooklyn, N.Y., and adored the singer Lily Pons -- 
memorizing arias from the record collection of her mother, Shirley. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father, Morris, was an insurance salesman from Romania and  
her mother was from Ukraine, and they encouraged her musical 
studies at the Professional Children's School as she went through 
New York City public schools. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1945, she had caught the attention of impresario J.J.  
Schubert, who used her in light opera and Broadway-type musicals. 
She made her debut in 1947 in Philadelphia in a bit role in 
``Carmen,'' and slowly made her way up to bigger companies. Her 
breakthrough came in 1966 at the New York City Opera, where her 
performance of Cleopatra in Handel's ``Giulio Cesare,'' made her a 
star. In Italy, the critics adored her, calling her ``La Fenomina'' 
after a first night at La Scala. 
</P>
<P>
	She didn't appear at the Metropolitan Opera until 1975, shortly  
before her retirement from singing -- which made it surprising when 
the Met asked her to sit on its board. 
</P>
<P>
	As an administrator who spent 10 years as general director of  
the New York City Opera, she understands the conflict between the 
different audiences. While some want rare operas, many prefer the 
warhorses. The choice is a painful one for her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Three performances of `Boheme' and have a 90 percent house? Or  
do three performances of `Susannah' or `Doe' and have a 72, 75 
percent house?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Doe,'' while not in the standard repertoire, is a work that  
has attracted fervid followers -- known as ``Doeites.'' The 
re-released recording also includes Walter Cassel as Horace Tabor 
and Frances Bible as Tabor's wife, Augusta, with Emerson Buckley 
conducting the New York City Opera Orchestra and Chorus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it will find its niche in history, if it hasn't  
already happened,'' Miss Sills said. ``It's too beautiful to go 
away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To get the opera recorded, Miss Sills received a fee of just  
$502, she recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We couldn't do any retakes,'' she said. ``It was, `Just keep  
singing, honey.' '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 11:51:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meth Dealers Eyed in Yosemite Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MODESTO, Calif. (AP) -- FBI agents investigating the slayings of  
three Yosemite National Park sightseers have zeroed in on a 
loose-knit group of methamphetamine users and are confident that 
some of those responsible are already behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Carole Sund, a member of a wealthy real estate family in Eureka,  
vanished Feb. 15 along with her 15-year-old daughter Juli and their 
Argentine friend Silvina Pelosso during a trip through the Sierra 
foothills. 
</P>
<P>
	They were found dead weeks later and hours away from where they  
were last seen. The burned bodies of Mrs. Sund, 42, and Ms. 
Pelosso, 16, were found in the trunk of their charred rental car. 
Juli's body was discovered more than 30 miles away on a hill. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been charged in the slayings.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators must resolve many questions: How did the  
sightseers encounter their assailants? How were they killed? And 
why? Was it for money, sex, thrills, something else? 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement sources and grand jury witnesses said the probe  
is centered on a group of ``cranksters'' -- methamphetamine is known 
as ``crank'' -- including Eugene ``Rufus'' Dykes and Michael 
``Mick'' Larwick, half-brothers with a long history of weapons, 
drug and sex offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Maria Ledbetter, Dykes' girlfriend, said she recovered one of  
his knives at the request of the FBI and has testified before the 
federal grand jury investigating the slayings. 
</P>
<P>
	The law enforcement sources, speaking to The Associated Press on  
condition of anonymity, said investigators are still trying to 
identify everyone who may have been involved in the slayings and 
figure out what their roles were. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI agent in charge, James Maddock, would not confirm the  
accounts of Ms. Ledbetter or other people interviewed by the AP. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said last week that his task force has collected hundreds  
of pieces of potential physical evidence and is making substantial 
progress in solving the mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents have been forced to return time and again for  
corroboration from witnesses whose memories may be clouded by 
drug-induced paranoia or hallucinations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're dealing with individuals in the crank trade or  
circles, one of the byproducts generally is these people are not as 
responsible or aware of details. We're not dealing with people who 
have regular jobs and regular lives,'' Maddock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Methamphetamine is a potent illegal drug that often causes  
delusions, paranoia and aggressive behavior. It a fast-growing drug 
problem in much of the Far West and Southwest. The drug is 
particularly popular with outlaw biker gangs. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-month-old investigation gained momentum shortly after the  
women's bodies were found. Agents shifted their attention from the 
rustic lodge in El Portal where the women were last seen to the 
seedy neighborhoods and trailer parks where the meth trade thrives 
in Modesto. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the bodies were found, Dykes and Larwick had been  
arrested during separate standoffs in Modesto. Larwick, 42, 
allegedly shot and wounded an officer who had pulled him over for a 
false license plate. Dykes, 32, was taken into custody on an 
undisclosed parole violation. 
</P>
<P>
	Larwick has roots in Long Barn, the tiny community where the  
victims' car was set on fire. One of his hangouts, friends said, is 
a home less than 10 blocks from the Modesto street corner where 
part of Mrs. Sund's wallet was found. Agents questioned him for 16 
hours straight. He has professed his innocence and said he provided 
a blood sample to clear his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Dykes, an ex-con with a record of meth possession, unlawful sex  
and weapons convictions, also remains in custody. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe my son had anything to do with it,'' said his  
father, Burel Dykes. ``He may know something, though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement sources said that others must have been involved  
in the slayings as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting people to talk has not been easy. This is one reason  
investigators convened the grand jury April 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to take our clique down,'' said Angelia Dale,  
24, a friend of Dykes and Larwick who has been arrested for meth 
possession and was subpoenaed to testify. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
