<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Wants Pressure on War Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate voted unanimously Monday to step up  
pressure for international prosecution of suspected Kosovo war 
criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	On a 90-to-0 vote, the Senate approved a nonbinding amendment by  
Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Mary Landrieu, D-La., that 
recommends ``vigorous investigation'' of war crimes by an 
international tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure authorizes $18 million to help an international  
tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, expand its investigation into 
other Balkan war crimes to include activities in Kosovo, a Serbian 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, an amendment to a $288.8 billion Pentagon spending  
bill, also recommends that amnesty for those who might be indicted 
as war criminals not be made part of any diplomatic settlement to 
the conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO should not accept any diplomatic solution that would bar  
indictment of war criminals,'' Specter said. To spare Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic ``or other high-ranking individuals 
should be rejected as part of any negotiated settlement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S 1059.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
