</P>
<P>
	First Talks Held in Shipyard Strike  
</P>
<P>
	HAMPTON, Va. (AP) -- Negotiators for Newport News Shipbuilding,  
the nation's only builder of aircraft carriers, and the United 
Steelworkers met today for the first time since before the union 
went on strike seven weeks ago. Spokesmen for both sides said they 
hoped the meeting arranged by federal mediators would lead to a 
contract agreement and the end of the strike. Shipyard spokesman 
Mike Hatfield would not say whether the yard was willing to budge 
from what it called its final contract offer, which it delivered 
during the last talks, on March 30. The strike began April 5, when 
the old contract expired. 

</P>
<P>
	Oil Cos. Lack National Y2K Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The oil and gas industry, with its dependence  
on computers, has too many question marks about its plans to deal 
with Year 2000 computer problems, a congressional report concludes. 
The General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress, 
said that while individual companies are confronting possible 
problems, no national-level approach has emerged to deal with 
shortages or disruptions in the nation's oil and gas supplies. 
Citing an industry survey taken in February, the GAO said more than 
a quarter of the industry does not expect to be Y2K ready until the 
second half of 1999, ``leaving little time for resolving unexpected 
problems.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Rogers &AMP; Wells, UK Law Firm To Merge  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The leaders of the New York-based law firm  
Rogers &AMP; Wells have decided to merge with one of Britain's biggest 
and most prestigious firms, Clifford Chance. The executive 
committees of the two firms voted separately late Friday to submit 
proposals for a merger to their partners, a senior attorney at one 
of the firms said today. If approved by the full partnerships it 
would be the first merger of major U.S. and British law firms. A 
spokeswoman for Rogers &AMP; Wells, Jolie Goldstein, declined to 
comment. 

</P>
<P>
	FTC Allowed To Regulate Nonprofits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said today tht the Federal  
Trade Commission has the authority to regulate at least some 
nonprofit professional groups, such as dental associations, in an 
effort to protect competition. But the justices ordered lower 
courts to take a closer look to determine whether the FTC properly 
invalidated the California Dental Association's limits on dentist 
advertising. The FTC said the association's rules would bar even 
truthful ads. All nine justices agreed that the FTC's authority to 
oversee for-profit corporations also extends to nonprofit 
professional groups that provide substantial economic benefits to 
their for-profit members. 

</P>
<P>
	New Site for Shockwave Technology  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Software maker Macromedia Inc. has formed a  
new unit to promote its Shockwave technology on a Web site it hopes 
will become an entertainment hub on the Internet. The unit, called 
shockwave.com, will operate a Web site by the same name. The site 
will guide users to games, puzzles and animation created by 
Macromedia's Shockwave and Flash technology, the company said 
today. On the Web site, users will be able to download two pieces 
of software that play Shockwave files. The free Shockwave Remote 
allows Internet users to search out and play back music, comics and 
games, and then save up to five pieces of content for use at 
anytime -- even when their computers are not connected to the 
Internet. 

</P>
<P>
	Some N.J. Doctors Rebuffed on Union  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A landmark attempt to unionize hundreds of  
doctors in southern New Jersey suffered another setback today after 
the National Labor Relations Board again rejected their union 
petition. An appeal was expected by the United Food and Commercial 
Workers Local 56, which has sought to represent more than 650 
private practice doctors in collective bargaining. The case is 
attracting attention around the country as increasing numbers of 
doctors try to unionize in frustration at the way HMOs control 
their practices. 

</P>
<P>
	News Banned for Shanghai Pagers  
</P>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Pager and computer information services  
in Shanghai have been ordered to stop carrying news reports, a 
newspaper reported today. The report by the Xinmin Evening News did 
not give a reason, but Chinese authorities are trying to muzzle 
potential sources of dissent ahead of the 10th anniversary of the 
June 4, 1989, crackdown on pro-democracy protests in Tiananmen 
Square. Shanghai telecommunications officials announced the order 
at a meeting with representatives of 131 pager and computer 
services, the newspaper said. All domestic news media in China are 
state-controlled. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysia Multimedia City Ready Early  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's high-tech multimedia  
city modeled after Silicon Valley is set to open a year ahead of 
schedule, despite economic and political turmoil in the Southeast 
Asian nation, officials said today. Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed 
is expected to declare the multibillion dollar cybercity, known as 
Cyberjaya, officially open on July 8. Cyberjaya is part of the 
country's Multimedia Super Corridor. The zone, roughly the size of 
neighboring Singapore, will be bound by fiber-optic wires linking 
new megaprojects with the international airport and a new federal 
capital called Putrajaya, where Mahathir will shift offices in 
June. 

</P>
<P>
	Settlement With DeLorean Trustee  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A long-running lawsuit on behalf of DeLorean  
Motor Co.'s creditors has been settled, marking the end of the 
defunct automaker's financial battles. Accounting firm Arthur 
Andersen has agreed to pay $27.8 million as part of a settlement on 
behalf of DeLorean's creditors, DeLorean trustee David W. Allard 
Jr. said today. He said the settlement, reached today, will take 
care of about 90 percent of the roughly 260 creditors' bills. 
Except for a few loose ends, he said this marks the end of the 
litigation on behalf of the creditors that began more than a decade 
ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
