<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Job Market Should Stay Strong  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The job market should remain strong through the  
summer, with the highest demand for workers expected in Western 
states, according to a survey released today. A quarterly survey of 
more than 15,000 companies by Manpower Inc. reported that 32 
percent planned to increase hiring in the third quarter. Just 6 
percent anticipated cutbacks, while 58 percent foresaw no change. 
The remaining 4 percent were unsure, the survey said. The figures 
were almost identical to the year-earlier tallies and up slightly 
from the April-June period. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Down 2.65  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed this morning as investors  
awaited the next indication of whether inflation is threatening the 
vibrant U.S. economy. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones 
industrial average was down 2.65 at 10,826.63. Broader stock 
indicators were mostly lower. The Nasdaq composite index was down 
31.93 at 2,488.21. Investors spent last week on the sidelines, 
weighing the Federal Reserve's decision to leave interest rates 
unchanged and its accompanying warning that it is ready to raise 
interest rates if inflation is rekindled. Today, it appeared that 
investors are continuing their own watch. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:  
Dow Industrials:        10826.63  -  2.65
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1397  Declines 1009  Unchgd  653
NYSE Volume:         147,307,980
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online 120 1/4   - 6 3/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1326.94  - 3.35
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          798.81  + 3.44
Nasdaq Composite Index:       2488.21  - 31.93
Gold(final) -    $272.70    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Court Rejects Rent Control Challenge  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected a challenge  
to California cities' power to limit rents without having to prove 
at trial that the controls are achieving their goals. The justices, 
without comment, let stand a California Supreme Court ruling that 
leaves it to the state Legislature to decide whether rent control 
laws need to be changed or repealed. The state court ruling, 
reached by a 4-3 vote last January, upheld a voter-approved 1979 
rent control ordinance in Santa Monica, one of the state's 
toughest. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Trade Surplus Falls in April  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus with the world slipped 12.6  
percent in April from the same month last year in an indication 
that growth in the imbalance may be slowing, the government said 
today. The merchandise trade surplus, the measure of all goods 
exported by Japan minus those imported, decreased to 1.069 trillion 
yen, or $8.62 billion, the Finance Ministry said. The April surplus 
was slightly lower than the average forecast of 1.099 trillion yen 
by Tokyo-based economists. 

</P>
<P>
	Toyota Profits Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Toyota Motor Corp.'s profit fell 22 percent in the  
latest fiscal year as weak sales at home and in Asia by Japan's 
biggest carmaker more than offset an increase in exports to North 
America. Toyota's group net income reported today totaled 356.1 
billion yen, or $2.9 billion, for the fiscal year ended March 31 
versus 454.3 billion yen a year earlier. Toyota attributed the 
decline to falling sales in Japan where consumer demand has 
weakened amid the country's deepest postwar recession. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally mixed  
today, with prices rising in Tokyo and Hong Kong, but slumping in 
Kuala Lumpur and Seoul. The Japanese 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 
rose 97.51 points, or 0.60 percent, closing the day's trading at 
16,390.49 points. On Friday, the average closed up 92.99 points, or 
0.57 percent. The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key 
indicator of blue chips, rose 164.72 points, or 1.3 percent, to 
12,436.86. Malaysian shares closed sharply lower as retailers took 
profit following spectacular gains last week, traders said. The 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 blue-chip stocks, fell 26.45 
points, or 3.4 percent, to 743.34. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Revises Cadbury Deal  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola Co. has revised a deal to acquire  
Cadbury Schweppes soft drink brands overseas to exclude most of the 
member nations of the European Union, where it has faced antitrust 
challenges. Britain, Ireland and Greece remain part of the revised 
deal announced today. It still covers more than 100 countries and 
is now valued at $1.1 billion. The deal announced in December had 
covered 126 countries and was worth $1.85 billion. Coca Cola stock 
was down 5/16 at 67 11/16 this morning. Cadbury's ADR is down 1/2 to 
55 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Settlement With DeLorean Trustee  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The accounting firm Arthur Andersen has agreed to  
pay $27.75 million as part of a settlement with the bankruptcy 
trustee for DeLorean Motor Co., the trustee said today. The lawsuit 
stemmed from allegations that Arthur Andersen signed off on 
DeLorean's financial statements despite potential evidence of 
fraud. In March 1998, a jury in New York State Supreme Court found 
in favor of DeLorean's trustee, ordering Arthur Anderson to pay 
$46.2 million. The accounting firm had filed a motion asking the 
court to set aside the verdict, but the two sides reached the 
settlement Friday, trustee David W. Allard Jr. said today. ``I 
think this is an excellent settlement for the creditors,'' Allard 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Gas Prices Finally Drop  
</P>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- The 2 1/2-month climb in gasoline prices  
has reversed itself, dropping 1.57 cents per gallon nationwide 
since May 7, and likely to keep falling, according to an industry 
analyst. The high prices had been blamed on the oil refining 
industry's decision to increase supplies of fuel for early summer 
driving, said Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the Lundberg Survey of 
10,000 gasoline stations. By Friday, the national weighted average, 
including all grades with taxes, was $1.218 per gallon, Ms. 
Lundberg said Sunday. 

</P>
