<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Decided that police who let the news media accompany them into  
people's homes to observe arrests or searches can be sued for 
violating the Constitution's Fourth Amendment protection against 
unreasonable searches. The court ruled unanimously in a pair of 
cases from Maryland and Montana. ``The possibility of good public 
relations for the police is simply not enough, standing alone, to 
justify the ride-along intrusion into a private home,'' Chief 
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote in the Maryland case. 
</P>
<P>
	--Turned down an appeal by a Maine dentist who was sued for  
refusing to treat a woman in his office because she has the virus 
that causes AIDS. Dentist Randon Bragdon argued that the Americans 
with Disabilities Act allowed him to conclude that filling the 
woman's cavity would pose a ``direct threat'' to his health and 
safety. The same case was the subject of a major Supreme Court 
decision last June, when the justices said people infected with HIV 
can sue under the ADA. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled 5-4 in a California case that people at least sometimes  
can get a jury trial when they invoke a much-used civil rights law 
and sue in federal court over local governmental land-use 
regulations. The justices upheld a $1.45 million award against the 
city of Monterey, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled unanimously that the Federal Trade Commission has the  
authority to regulate at least some nonprofit professional groups, 
such as dental associations, in an effort to protect competition. 
But the justices, voting 5-4, ordered lower courts to take a closer 
look to determine whether the FTC properly invalidated the 
California Dental Association's limits on dentist advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	--Made it easier for disabled workers to sue their employers over  
alleged discrimination after they seek Social Security disability 
benefits. Voting unanimously in a Texas case, the justices said 
courts cannot presume that people who apply for such benefits are 
admitting they are unqualified to hold a job. Someone must be 
qualified for a job to file a discrimination lawsuit under the 
Americans with Disabilities Act. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowed Georgia to require a runoff election when no political  
candidate gets more than 50 percent of the vote in a primary 
election. The justices let stand lower rulings that said the 
majority-vote requirement does not discriminate against black 
voters and candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
