<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Won't Force Noncommercial Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to force the  
city of Phoenix to accept noncommercial advertisements, such as 
religious and political messages, for display on the outside of 
city buses. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away arguments by a religious  
group and the Arizona Civil Liberties Union that the city violates 
free-speech rights by renting space on public transit buses only 
for commercial advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices had been asked to reconsider the court's 1974  
ruling that allowed an Ohio city to bar political advertising on 
public transit vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Children of the Rosary, a religious group, successfully sued  
Phoenix in 1995 over its policy of excluding political and 
religious messages from city buses. 
</P>
<P>
	In November 1996, a new city policy took effect that limited bus  
advertising to ``speech which proposes a commercial transaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon afterward, the city rejected an advertisement from Children  
of the Rosary that contained a quote from the Bible, the phrase 
``choose life,'' and stated, ``Purchase this message as a 
bumpersticker for your vehicle.'' City officials said the ad was 
primarily noncommercial. 
</P>
<P>
	The city also rejected an ACLU ad that said, ``The ACLU supports  
free speech for everyone'' and gave a phone number to buy a bumper 
sticker with that message. 
</P>
<P>
	Children of the Rosary and the ACLU sued in 1997, saying the  
advertising standard violated the Constitution's First Amendment, 
which protects freedom of speech. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge ruled against the challengers. Phoenix's bus  
advertising is a nonpublic forum, the judge said, adding that the 
policy was a reasonable way to protect a city revenue source and 
maintain neutrality on political and religious issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed in an opinion  
written by retired Supreme Court Justice Byron R. White, a visiting 
member of that court. The city can exclude such speech from a 
nonpublic forum as long as it does not discriminate against 
particular viewpoints, White wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the religious group  
and the ACLU suggested commercial speech should not be given 
greater protection than noncommercial speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Children of the Rosary vs. Phoenix, 98-1433.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
