<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Hollywood Plan for the NFL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Leave it to Hollywood to bedazzle NFL owners.  
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ovitz, the show business agent who heads one of two  
groups bidding for the new Los Angeles franchise, has a plan for 
the Los Angeles Coliseum that includes everything from a parking 
garage covered with trees, grass in front of luxury suites and even 
a cooling system that would spray mist on fans in hot weather. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan, first reported Sunday in the Los Angeles Times, will  
be presented to the owners at their spring meetings Tuesday and 
Wednesday. League officials confirmed the newspaper report that the 
plan had impressed most of the owners who had seen it. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day meeting will be involved primarily with settling  
some of the NFL's franchise issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The owners are expected to approve the sale of the Washington  
Redskins to Edward Snyder for $800 million. Snyder was a member of 
the group headed by Howard Milstein that withdrew after it became 
apparent the owners wouldn't approve it. 
</P>
<P>
	They also are expected to discuss the New England Patriots'  
decision to stay in the Boston area after withdrawing a commitment 
they had made to Hartford, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	But Los Angeles may be the most pressing issue.  
</P>
<P>
	At the March meetings, the league tentatively awarded Los  
Angeles the 32nd franchise over Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	But the NFL told the California city that it needed to come up  
with a viable plan by September. And there still are two groups 
vying for the franchise -- one headed by Ovitz and the other by real 
estate moguls Eli Broad and Ed Roski. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL already has chosen the Coliseum, the Roski-Broad site,  
as the setting for the new stadium. But Ovitz's plan may give his 
group the edge in getting the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal, designed by architect David Rockwell, is called  
``The Coliseum at Exposition Park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking Central Park here and a unique recreation  
environment with the stadium standing as a monument in the 
middle,'' the Times quoted an unidentified NFL official as saying. 
``It just blew everyone away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't guarantee Ovitz will get the franchise, which would  
replace the Rams and Raiders, who defected to St. Louis and Oakland 
after the 1995 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Broad-Roski group claims to hold a special right to bring  
the NFL back to the Coliseum. If the owners decide on Ovitz's plan, 
their claim could hurt Los Angeles' chance of meeting the Sept. 15 
deadline set to the owners. 
</P>
<P>
	League officials also have said if Los Angeles seemed close to a  
new plan, it might be considered to have met the deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
