<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Volunteers to Mentor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saluting theirs as ``a better way to live,''  
President Clinton urged a sea of enthusiastic young volunteers 
Monday to preach their message of teamwork and service to youths 
who feel alienated from society. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton addressed the 10th anniversary celebration of the City  
Year service organization and asked the 1,000 attendees to set 
examples for other young adults. He cited the recent wave of school 
violence and said he was struck by the descriptions of 
disengagement and anger experienced by the youths accused of 
carrying them out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that community service can have a profound impact in  
diminishing, even erasing, the sense of alienation and isolation so 
many of our young people feel,'' Clinton said at the rally at 
Howard University. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said many of the volunteers might also have felt  
upset or resentful at times, but they managed to keep going and 
become a part of something larger than themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	He called on the group to mentor and speak to other children and  
encourage them to participate in activities that give them a sense 
of purpose like community service. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can tell them that no matter what has happened, no matter  
what's bugging them, no matter who is dissing them, no matter what 
they have to have a beef about, real or imagined, what you're doing 
is a better way to live, and they ought to join you and live that 
way, too,'' Clinton said to resounding cheers. 
</P>
<P>
	City Year, which works alongside AmeriCorps, is a one-year  
service program for young people age 17 to 24 in 11 cities across 
the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Spaloss of New Hampshire welcomed the president and  
described the impact of his first meeting with Clinton in 1991. A 
presidential candidate at the time, Clinton visited the group's 
convention in Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	``He challenged me to commit myself to a lifetime of service,''  
said Spaloss, who went on to serve with the program in founding 
branches in other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also used Monday's event to push for expansion of  
AmeriCorps. He has proposed an additional $113 million for the 
program next year, with the goal of supporting 100,000 members a 
year by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation has ``both the unique obligation, and because of our  
prosperity and security, a unique opportunity to galvanize people 
as never before in the cause of citizen service,'' the president 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
