<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota Profits Fall 22 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Weak auto sales both domestically and  
internationally pushed Toyota Motor Corp.'s profit down 22 percent 
in the latest fiscal year, despite an increase in exports to North 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's group net income reported Monday totaled 356.1 billion  
yen, or $2.9 billion, for the fiscal year ended March 31 vs. 454.3 
billion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota attributed the decline to falling sales in Japan where  
consumer demand has weakened amid the country's deepest postwar 
recession. At the same time, Toyota's exports to Asia fell by 
nearly half as demand crumbled in countries struck by the nearly 
two-year-old economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Group sales rose from last year, but the increase was due  
largely to Daihatsu Motor Co. and IDO Corp. joining the Toyota 
group. Daihatsu makes small-cars and trucks and IDO is a 
cellular-phone service provider. Toyota acquired majority stakes in 
the companies last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota said group sales rose 9 percent to 12.7 trillion yen, or  
$102 billion, from 11.7 trillion yen a year earlier. The number of 
vehicles sold rose 1.2 percent to 1.93 million in Japan and rose 
8.5 percent to 2.8 million overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	But excluding the effect of adding Daihatsu to the group,  
vehicle sales figures were more bleak. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports of Toyota and Lexus cars from Japan fell 5.8 percent to  
1.4 million vehicles as exports to Asia dropped 47 percent to 
78,109 vehicles. That drop more than offset a rise in exports to 
North America of 7.8 percent to 573,756 cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Toyota vehicles in Japan -- excluding the addition of  
Daihatsu -- fell 13 percent to 1.7 million vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	The bleak economic environment is expected to continue this  
year, Okijima said, though the company is hoping the economy will 
pick up in the second half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Toyota said it would move the listing of its stock to the New  
York Stock Exchange from the Nasdaq Stock Market this year and to 
list its shares in London. The moves are aimed at making the shares 
more accessible for foreign investors, said Okijima. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Toyota closed down 12 1/2 cents to $53.87 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Toyota said the top management at Toyota Motor Sales USA would  
change. Among other shifts, Yoshio Ishizaka, president and CEO of 
the division since mid-1996, was promoted to senior managing 
director of Toyota Motor Corp. He will be succeeded by Yoshimi 
Inaba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
