<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 05:05:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Dome Rises and a Feud Boils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Capitol dome is, purely and simply, a  
paramount symbol of the United States, an image engraved on the 
national mind like the Statue of Liberty and the faces on Mount 
Rushmore. 
</P>
<P>
	The dome's image is everywhere and has been since it was topped  
off with the 19 1/2-foot statue of Armed Freedom in the midst of the 
Civil War, the cannons in 12 forts surrounding Washington booming 
salutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Everywhere, as in its floodlit image glowing from millions of  
television screens in the moments before a president's State of the 
Union address, the light in the lantern near its top a signal that 
Congress is in session. 
</P>
<P>
	Advertisements, book jackets, patriotic prints and hundreds of  
thousands of political cartoons have employed the image of the 
white-painted Capitol dome. 
</P>
<P>
	At its western base, where presidents since Ronald Reagan have  
been inaugurated, the dome faces the Mall, the storehouse of 
national history, the White House, the city of power, lawyers and 
lobbyists. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dome didn't rise to its place on the skyline without the  
familiar accompaniment of a first-class Washington power struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	Intervention by Congress led to a wounding personal feud between  
the dome's architect and the ``reckless egotism'' of the ambitious 
Army engineer employed to supervise construction. The battle played 
out against the backdrop of the nation's widening sectional gulf 
and the fast-approaching Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	The story of the building of the dome is told by William C.  
Allen, chief architectural historian in the office of the Architect 
of the Capitol, in ``The Dome of the United States Capitol,'' 
published as a Senate document in 1992. Allen now is writing a 
full-scale history of the Capitol's architecture. 
</P>
<P>
	The two principal actors were Thomas U. Walter, one of the  
leading architects of his time, and Montgomery C. Meigs, an Army 
captain and talented engineer determined to stamp the dome with his 
personality and name. 
</P>
<P>
	In the near background was Meigs' sponsor, U.S. Secretary of War  
Jefferson Davis, soon to be president of the Confederate States of 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	A dome had been on the national wish list since the 1790s, when  
America's leaders saw architecture as a way to express the pride 
and permanence of both the new Capitol and the fledgling nation. 
</P>
<P>
	But no dome rose until the 1830s, and it was a modest effort at  
best. By the time the capital was ready for expansion in the early 
1850s the existing dome was widely scorned as a ``washbowl turned 
upside down,'' hardly the transcendent symbol Thomas Jefferson had 
envisioned. 
</P>
<P>
	The new vision came from the drawing board of Walter, a  
Philadelphia architect who had impressed Congress with his design 
for a new Capitol library, made entirely of molded iron. 
</P>
<P>
	While Walter would use marble for the new House and Senate  
wings, the central dome resting on the old stone walls would also 
be made of industrial-age iron from top to bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	But Congress inserted a stinging irritant into the mix, asking  
the War Department to assign an officer to supervise construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Meigs, Davis' choice for the job, immediately overstepped his  
mandate of managing contracts and supervising construction. He 
demanded a premier role in design and decoration of the dome, down 
to his name stamped on its iron parts. 
</P>
<P>
	Meigs saw the dome as his chance for immortality. Walter saw an  
attack on the professional stature of architecture itself. 
</P>
<P>
	In a long series of events, Meigs demanded all of Walter's  
drawings be turned over to him, refused to authorize pay for his 
draftsmen, quarreled openly with him in the press, tried to 
undermine his reputation, ordered him fired and, when all else 
failed, posted a sentry on his office door to keep him out. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter described the situation as ``open war'' against ``the  
despotism of a military upstart who happens to have the power to 
annoy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``During the two-year battle between Meigs and Walter,  
construction of the dome slowed to a crawl. The drafting room 
continued to produce elegant drawings, but these were not sent to 
Meigs for fear of alteration or mutilation,'' Allen writes. 
</P>
<P>
	But time for petty quarrels was running out. Southern states  
seceded from the Union. Davis went with them to head the rebel 
government. Promoted to major general, Meigs ran the supply effort 
for federal forces and, spitefully, buried Union dead on the 
grounds of Robert E. Lee's Virginia mansion, the beginnings of 
Arlington National Cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederate pickets across the Potomac could see the dome  
continue to rise to its overall height of 287 feet, six inches. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter's wife called it ``that magnificent dome.'' No one  
contradicted her. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
