<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Down in T-Bill Sale / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities declined in Monday's auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.5 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.495 percent, down from 4.570 percent last 
week. An additional $7.5 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.570 percent, down from 4.630 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the lowest since May 10, when the bills  
sold for 4.480 percent. The six-month rate was the lowest since May 
10, when the rate was 4.510 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.621 percent for three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,886.40, and 4.756 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,767.70. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 4.89 
percent last week from 4.79 percent the previous week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
