<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 15:31:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fine Line Between Harassing, Teasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Schools in North Carolina and New York City  
were accused of going too far when they suspended small boys -- a 
first-grader and a second-grader -- for kissing female classmates. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, school officials say the Supreme Court's ruling Monday in a  
Georgia case means they will face new difficulties in 
distinguishing illegal harassment from rambunctious teasing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next year kids will be suspended for behavior nobody's ever  
been suspended for, and parents will ask why,'' said Bruce Hunter 
of the American Association of School Administrators. ``But I don't 
see any way of avoiding that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schools -- from elementary to colleges -- that accept federal  
money can be sued by victims of such harassment, the court said in 
its 5-4 ruling. The case stems from a fifth-grade girl suing the 
Monroe County, Ga., school board, saying a classmate harassed her 
despite complaints to officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Some districts had policies taking a student's age, prior  
conduct, and intent into account, but the Supreme Court decision 
made it clear they need stronger harassment policies to back up 
their actions, Hunter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Dumas, superintendent of the Monroe County schools, said  
that in the four years since the case began, the district has made 
some changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a program now that talks about the difference between  
a good touch and bad touch,'' he said. ``We're starting even in 
primary school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What officials don't see is schools backing off the issue.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is rare to find a school or college that does not  
respond,'' said Norma Cantu, the Education Department's civil 
rights chief. ``We want common sense. Cases should not be 
exaggerated or ignored. The Supreme Court decision is urging common 
sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schools have had their share of problems in trying to determine  
what is common sense in addressing peer harassment: 
</P>
<P>
	--Last year, officials in a Peterborough, N.H., high school were  
criticized for not immediately expelling a 17-year-old boy charged 
with sexually assaulting a 15-year-old girl. The boy, who served a 
20-day suspension, was allowed back into school because the school 
board's investigation didn't support other disciplinary action 
against him. 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1997, prosecutors in Arlington, Va., abruptly dropped a sex  
charge against a 9-year-old fourth-grade boy who was accused of 
rubbing against a 9-year-old girl in a sexual manner in a school 
lunch line. The boy's family said he accidentally brushed against 
the girl. 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1996, a state court held an Antioch, Calif., school district  
liable for violating a state harassment law and gave $500,000 to 
the family of a 6th-grade girl who said a boy in her class 
repeatedly called her ``slut'' and other vulgarities and threatened 
her physically. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents, who are often the source of the official complaints,  
should have a role in deciding those local policies, said Patty 
Yoxall, spokeswoman of the National Parent Teacher Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a double-edged sword,'' said Arizona State Board of  
Education spokeswoman Patricia Likens. ``You may see more lawsuits 
that are more justified, or you may see parents jumping to 
conclusions. But the onus is on the districts. They are going to 
have to tread lightly on this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Julie Underwood, general counsel for the National Association of  
School Boards, believes the court's ruling could actually prevent 
schools from overreacting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The standard is pervasive sexual harassment. If the court had  
left it at all sexual harassment, schools would be in a position 
where they would have to respond to even the slightest blush,'' 
said Underwood. ``Hopefully, the standard is high enough that we 
won't get the frivolous suspensions for holding hands or for 
kissing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Children are children,'' she said. ``They are going to  
misbehave.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
