<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Target Reno in Spy Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers, including a normally staunch  
Democratic defender of the Clinton White House, say Attorney 
General Janet Reno should resign, or at least consider doing so, 
because of what they call the administration's tepid response to 
alleged nuclear spying by China. 
</P>
<P>
	The comments, made on the Sunday television talk shows, came as  
a special House committee prepares to release a report detailing 
China's quest for American military secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the Justice Department is adrift,'' said Sen.  
Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Intelligence 
Committee. ``I believe that the attorney general ought to resign 
and she ought to take her top lieutenants with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In response, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said today  
``the president has confidence in the attorney general'' and noted 
that she had directed an internal investigation into the FBI's and 
Justice's handling of the case involving a Los Alamos scientist, 
dating back to 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be inappropriate to prejudge that review,'' Lockhart  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey, appearing with  
Shelby on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' also said President Clinton 
should talk with Reno about possibly stepping down. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is something wrong when the United States Congress on a  
bipartisan basis has so little confidence in the chief law 
enforcement officer of the United States,'' said Torricelli, who 
customarily supports administration policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's time for President Clinton to have a conversation  
with the attorney general about her ability to perform her duties 
and whether or not it is in the national interest for her to 
continue,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno has long been under fire from GOP lawmakers for her refusal  
to have an independent counsel investigate charges the Chinese 
funneled illegal contributions to Clinton's 1996 presidential 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the issue is the Justice Department's refusal to  
approve FBI requests for a wiretap of Wen Ho Lee, a scientist at 
the Los Alamos, N.M., nuclear weapons laboratory who is suspected 
of passing secrets to Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said Reno had reviewed  
the decision and fully supported it. ``The Justice Department 
cannot and must not authorize intrusion by the government into the 
lives of its citizens when the evidence presented as in this case 
fails to meet the standards established by the Constitution and the 
Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act,'' Marlin said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, a special House panel chaired by Rep. Christopher  
Cox, R-Calif., is to make public its report detailing how Chinese 
stole or otherwise obtained satellite and nuclear secrets over the 
past two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox, interviewed on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said the  
revelations in the report ``were so stark, so grave and so 
important,'' and the espionage ``continues to this very day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said satellite and  
radar technology, supercomputers, nuclear warhead designs and 
advanced rocket technology have entered Chinese hands. ``I do agree 
with others that some heads should roll,'' he said on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who was credited by  
Republicans for taking forceful steps in recent months to bolster 
security at the national labs, urged lawmakers not to politicize 
the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	While Shelby and others declared this could be the worst case of  
espionage in U.S. history, Richardson told on ABC's ``This Week,'' 
that the content and extent of the Chinese spying is still unclear. 
``We cannot overdramatize conclusions that are not conclusive 
yet,'' he said, adding that the United States has 6,000 strategic 
warheads to 23 for the Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cox said there were serious lapses in the U.S. response to  
the Los Alamos affair, which was first uncovered in 1995 but didn't 
surface until this year when Lee was fired from his job. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a great deal of time the appropriate people in our  
government were not told of these things,'' Cox said, noting that 
one person out of the loop until this year was the secretary of 
commerce, who is responsible for approving high-tech sales to 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told CBS she also did not  
learn of the investigation until earlier this year. ``I was not 
briefed, that was wrong, and I made that clear and that has been 
rectified,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said he would meet with key Senate committee chairmen today  
to discuss future action, including the possibilities of appointing 
a special investigative committee and passing laws tightening 
export laws and security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
