<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Rules Out '47 Palestine Partition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, poised to work  
with a new government in Israel, today ruled out a 1947 U.N. 
resolution calling for the partition of Palestine into Jewish and 
Arab states as a basis for peacemaking. 
</P>
<P>
	While reminding Israel the United States would insist it  
relinquish land for peace with the Arabs, senior American mediator 
Dennis Ross said the resolution, which has strong Arab and European 
support, ``is not relevant'' to current peacemaking efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not appropriate, and we will say so,'' Ross said,  
prompting applause from delegates to the annual meeting of the 
American-Israel Public Affairs Committee, the main pro-Israel 
lobbying group. 
</P>
<P>
	Resolution 181, adopted by the U.N. General Assembly, would  
transfer large parts of what is now Israel to an Arab state, as 
well as all the land that the Arabs subsequently lost to Israel in 
the 1967 Mideast war, 
</P>
<P>
	Saeb Erekat, Yasser Arafat's top negotiator, said in the region  
today that U.N. resolutions 242 and 338 -- calling on Israel to 
concede territory captured in the war in exchange for secure 
borders -- still applies, but ``this should not undermine 181, 
especially in provisions calling for a two-state solution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ross said resolutions 242 and 338, which were approved in  
1967 and 1973 by the U.N. Security Council, were the only bases for 
negotiations. ``Any other basis is not relevant,'' he said, clearly 
referring to resolution 181. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat, Erekat and other officials of the Palestinian Authority  
are viewed by the Clinton administration as bent on peace with 
Israel if they can only take over more territory. 
</P>
<P>
	With Ehud Barak elected as prime minister, and far more inclined  
than his predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, to give up land for 
promises of peace, Ross and others in the administration are 
gearing up for a new try. 
</P>
<P>
	In an apparent reference to Netanyahu's government, Ross said  
``accusations'' by either side and ``steps on the ground'' tend to 
hurt the good will needed for agreements. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu's government had accused Arafat of not rooting out  
terrorist cells on land already under Palestinian control, and 
supported settlers who have staked claims to part of the territory 
on which Arafat intends to establish a state. 
</P>
<P>
	Officially, the Clinton administration is neutral on statehood  
and on whether the Palestinians should have part of Jerusalem as a 
capital. But President Clinton, in a speech in Gaza and in a letter 
to Arafat, has offered strong support to what he called 
``Palestinian aspirations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is confident Barak can help advance the Middle  
East peace process, Vice President Al Gore said in a speech Sunday 
night to the lobby group. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore called Barak, who defeated the more hawkish Benjamin  
Netanyahu on Monday, ``an immensely credible voice in support of 
peace.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
