<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Little Changed As Stocks Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds were little changed Monday as stocks fell  
sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dipped 3/32  
point, or 94 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, edged up to 5.76 percent from late 
Friday's 5.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The smooth sailing in bonds came as some investors sought the  
safety of government securities while stock prices were stumbling 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was down 174.61, or by 1.6  
percent, at 10,654.67. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices of short-term Treasuries ranged from unchanged to 1/32  
point higher, and intermediate maturities ranged from 1/32 point to 
1/8 point higher, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.61 percent from  
Friday's 4.59 percent, while the discount rose 0.02 percentage 
point to 4.49 percent. Six-month yields were unchanged at 4.75 
percent as the discount held steady at 4.57 percent. One-year 
yields rose to 4.82 percent from late Friday, while the discount 
rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, remained unchanged at 4.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1/32 point to 122 1/4. The average yield 
to maturity was unchanged at 5.35 percent from late Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
