<HEADLINE> University Names Don King Trustee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- The university which last year gave boxing  
promoter Don King an honorary doctorate and received a $200,000 
donation has appointed him to its board of trustees. 
</P>
<P>
	King joined Shaw University's 40-member board earlier this  
month, university spokeswoman Regina Boone said Monday. Also 
joining the board were former North Carolina State chancellor Larry 
Monteith and Garrett Briggs, the former president of Peace College 
in Raleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	WBA and IBF heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield also is a  
board member. 
</P>
<P>
	Trustees and alumni acknowledged King's controversial past but  
applauded his humanitarian efforts, university president Talbert O. 
Shaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it weren't for redemption, none of us would have a  
chance,'' Shaw said in a statement. ``King has a good heart, 
believe it or not, and he really wants to help young people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King said in a prepared statement that he was honored by the  
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	He was convicted of murder, a charge later reduced to  
manslaughter; faced numerous lawsuits from boxers and their 
handlers; was acquitted on tax evasion charges in 1985; and was 
acquitted last year of insurance fraud in the second of two trials. 
</P>
<P>
	King has been the subject of at least three grand jury  
investigations and at least one FBI sting operation. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, King received an honorary doctorate from the  
historically black private college and quipped that he ought to 
donate millions of dollars for a campus arena and fitness center. 
He recently donated $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAACP honored King in 1997 for his ``significant support of  
social causes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
