<DOCNO> APW19990524.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  New IRL Car Devices To Protect Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indy Racing League is using space-age  
cable in its cars to save lives in the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL, following the lead of rival Championship Auto Racing  
Teams and Formula One, said Monday it will have a ``wheel energy 
restraint system'' on its cars for Sunday's Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes almost a month after an accident in  
Concord, N.C., in which debris killed three spectators and injured 
eight others in the grandstand. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL and a vice president of  
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, said the system is designed to 
keep suspension parts from flying off open-wheel cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes will be made before Thursday's two-hour  
``Carburetion Day'' practice. That is the only time between the end 
of qualifications and the start of the 500 that the 33 starters 
will drive on the 2 1/2-mile oval. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators also were killed and several others injured  
last July in Brooklyn, Mich., by a wheel and other debris from a 
crash during a CART event. The North Carolina and Michigan tracks 
are high-speed, high-banked ovals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that this is definitely a step in the right  
direction,'' Mehl said. ``We're not done with taking more steps to 
make us more confident on the high banks. We have some more things 
that we will do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``I think we're doing everything possible to make it  
as safe for the fans as it can be. I mean, there isn't a 100 
percent guarantee that we're going to walk out there and not get 
run over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A.J. Foyt, a four-time Indy 500 winner and now an IRL team  
owner, appreciates the changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anything they can do to make racing safer is fine with me,''  
he said. ``It's like the car makers putting in seat belts and air 
bags. Even if it only works 50 percent of the time, it's great. It 
can save lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eliseo Salazar, who has finished fourth and sixth at Indy and  
will be starting 18th on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's absolutely necessary we try something,'' he said.  
``Nobody can say if this will be 100 percent efficient, but it's 
crucial we never put the spectators in that position again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the three companies building cars for IRL competition --  
Dallara in Italy, G Force in England and Riley &AMP; Scott in 
Indianapolis -- have worked with the league in developing a 
restraint system. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately, nobody knows more about their race cars than the  
manufacturers themselves,'' Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	CART's new system -- which will anchor the front suspensions --  
will make its debut in Saturday's Motorola 300 in Madison, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL announcement said all four suspensions on its cars will  
be attached to the chassis with cables of Zylon -- a high-tech fiber 
Mehl said is two times stronger than Kevlar. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has a breaking strength of five tons,'' said Mehl, who  
added that it's the same material used by Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	He also pointed out that there is no way to test the  
effectiveness of the new system under the actual stresses except in 
the cars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody can test at 200 mph and our cars spend a great deal of  
their racing life over 200.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Formula One began requiring its teams to use tether systems at  
the start of the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	One worry is the possibility that tethered suspension pieces or  
wheels could rebound into the open cockpit, hitting the driver. But 
Mehl said the IRL thinks its system will actually make the drivers 
safer. 
</P>
<P>
	The cables will connect the rear hubs and the front hubs and  
will also be attached to the farthest points from the driver on the 
frame. Mehl said they should not be able to reach the driver's 
compartment in a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	But, even if they could reach the cockpit, most of the drivers  
have said they'd rather be at more risk than put spectators in 
danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``We live for this, and we know what can happen,'' Salazar said.  
``You never want to put other people in the way of harm.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
