<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:06:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cipollini Wins Italy Tour Stage 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANSEPOLCRO, Italy (AP) -- Mario Cipollini outsprinted a large  
pack of riders Monday to win the 10th stage of the Tour of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his second stage win of the Tour and the 27th of his  
career. 
</P>
<P>
	France's Laurent Jalabert finished in the main group, right  
behind Cipollini, and retained the overall lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Marco Pantani finished close to Jalabert, and  
remained virtually tied for the overall lead. Jalabert leads by the 
.02 seconds he gained in winning Sunday's time trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Cipollini, who also won the second stage, pulled away from the  
lead group over the closing 100 yards and finished in 4 hours, 28 
minutes, 24 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you do not win for a while, they think you're finished.  
Well, I'm still here,'' Cipollini said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Italians, Ivan Quaranta and Massimo Strazzer, were  
second and third, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowded finish was set up when the main group caught three  
riders who had broken away early in the 118-mile route from Ancona 
west into Tuscany. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's 11th stage of 78 miles takes the riders east to  
Cesenatico on the Adriatic coast. It is the shortest of the race's 
22 stages, except for the two time trials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
