<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cigarette Blamed in Michigan Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CRYSTAL TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- A couple and four boys sleeping  
over as guests of their son were killed in a fast-moving fire 
blamed on a cigarette. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17-year-old son, Christopher Simmons, escaped early Sunday  
and ran to a neighbor's house for help. When firefighters arrived, 
the house in the community 40 miles northeast of Grand Rapids was 
engulfed in flames, Fire Chief Bob Brundage said. 
</P>
<P>
	The state fire marshal's office ruled today that the fire was  
accidental and likely started when a cigarette fell into a couch on 
the porch. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said the boy smelled the smoke and heard a smoke  
alarm, but the smoke was too thick for him to reach his friends or 
family. He made a vain effort to put out the flames with a garden 
hose before going for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonnie Woodruff, who lives next door, said she and her husband  
were awakened when their dog barked after Simmons knocked on their 
door. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just said, `Help me, help me, the house is on fire,''' she  
said. ``He was in shock, screaming and crying. He had to sit here 
and watch.'' She said he told her he accidentally started the fire 
with a cigarette. 
</P>
<P>
	All six victims apparently died of smoke inhalation, Brundage  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons' mother, Linda Christophersen, 42, and his stepfather,  
Richard Christophersen, 35, were killed. Also killed were Simmons' 
friends Lee Geselman, 16, Blakely Sailor, 17, and twin 15-year-old 
brothers, Matthew and Stephen Long. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmons was treated for burns at a hospital and released.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
