<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rosie Nixes Annie 'Gun' Song </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rosie O'Donnell reportedly asked the cast of  
Broadway's ``Annie Get Your Gun'' to change a lyric in one of the 
show's hit songs before taping her talk show because it clashed 
with her views on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Donnell wanted the line ``I can shoot a partridge with a  
single cartridge'' removed from one of the show's hit songs, 
``Anything You Can Do,'' the New York Post reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post said the musical's stars, led by star Bernadette  
Peters, refused the request and shot down a planned taping of ``The 
Rosie O'Donnell Show,'' set for Tuesday. The show is a revival of 
the classic Irving Berlin musical about Wild West sharpshooter 
Annie Oakley. 
</P>
<P>
	The appearance was revived when co-star Tom Wopat and other cast  
members agreed to perform ``My Defenses Are Down,'' a song from the 
musical that does not mention guns. The Post said Peters will not 
appear. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Donnell spokeswoman Lois Smith said the song was changed  
because Peters could not attend the taping. ``Anything You Can Do'' 
is a duet; ``My Defenses Are Down'' is sung by Wopat. 
</P>
<P>
	The report follows last week's heated on-air debate between  
O'Donnell and actor Tom Selleck. The actor has taped a commercial 
for the National Rifle Association, while O'Donnell has been a 
frequent critic of the NRA since the Columbine High School 
massacre. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
