<DOCNO> APW19990524.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 16:11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre Mulls Yankee Lineup Switches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Joe Torre fills out the lineup card at  
Yankee Stadium for the first time in more than seven months, there 
probably will be a few changes. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Yankees game against the Boston Red Sox was rained out  
Monday night, Torre said it might be time to shake up New York's 
struggling lineup a bit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could do it tomorrow,'' said Torre, who missed the first six  
weeks of the season recovering from prostate cancer surgery. ``But 
before I do anything involving the middle of the lineup, the guys 
will hear from me. I won't just post it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of those struggling Yankees -- Tino Martinez and Paul O'Neill  
-- did talk with Torre before leaving the ballpark Monday. They went 
into Torre's office for separate meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neill, the Yankees most consistent hitter since coming to New  
York in 1993, is batting .195 with no homers and four RBIs this 
month and the frustration is evident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never been through a stretch like this since coming to  
New York,'' O'Neill said. ``I told him it wouldn't bother me. We're 
not scoring runs. I am coming up in big at-bats and not delivering. 
We'll see if a change helps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre acknowledged that any changes would probably be minor. And  
even if he skakes up the lineup a little Tuesday, it could change 
back by next week. All he's looking for is a little spark to get 
this team going again. 
</P>
<P>
	New York has lost eight of its last 12 and trails Boston by 1 1/2  
games in the AL East. That's not cause for panic, but it does raise 
concerns -- especially on a team that rolled through last year with 
114 wins and barely even a hint of a slump. 
</P>
<P>
	``Paul is fighting something awful right now,'' Torre said. ``It  
makes it much tougher when you are losing games because you start 
blaming yourself. Last year, whenever someone went in a slump other 
people picked it up and the team still won so it was easier to 
handle. 
</P>
<P>
	``No club is as good as what we did last year,'' Torre said.  
``We played above our heads and got the breaks. We are better than 
we are playing right now. We're probably somewhere in between.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre is hoping the dramatic come-from-behind win Sunday against  
the Chicago White Sox will start a hot streak for New York. The 
Yankees trailed 7-3 in the ninth before tying the game on a balk 
and winning it in the 10th on Chad Curtis' homer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully it is the start of not being hesitant, not being  
tentative and not being all the things we're not used to being,'' 
Torre said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees' struggles run much deeper than O'Neill. Scott  
Brosius is batting .167 (7-for-42) with no RBIs in his last 13 
games; the Yankees have gotten almost no production from a left 
field platoon of Curtis, Shane Spencer and Ricky Ledee or the 
catching tandem of Jorge Posada and Joe Girardi; and leadoff hitter 
Chuck Knoblauch is hitting .136 this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``This game is a game of numbers, wins, losses and average.  
Period,'' O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	And because the Yankees numbers have not been up to  
expectations, Torre appears ready to make a change.. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The game will be made up Thursday at 7:05 p.m. EDT. ... The  
pitching matchups for the series will stay the same: Brian Rose 
(1-0) vs. Hideki Irabu (1-2) on Tuesday; Mark Portugal (3-2) vs. 
Orlando Hernandez (4-4) on Wednesday; and Pat Rapp (2-2) vs. Roger 
Clemens (3-0) on Thursday. ... Yankees minor league catcher Jaime 
Torres began three days of radiation Monday as part of his planned 
treatment for thyroid cancer. ... The Red Sox have won 14 of their 
last 17 games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 21:41:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Banks Have $171B in Bad Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's 17 biggest banks are saddled with a total  
of $171.7 billion in bad debts under newly introduced accounting 
standards, a leading Japanese economic newspaper said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined problem loans were up $9.84 billion from the  
previously disclosed amount under the old accounting method, the 
Nihon Keizai daily said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's banks have been struggling to deal with loans which have  
soured amid the nation's worst recession in 50 years. Many of these 
loans were extended in the late 1980s to finance highly speculative 
land deals before a burst in real estate prices at the outset of 
this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators in Japan revamped disclosure standards last year for  
domestic banks as part of a scheme implemented in October to inject 
new capital into banks to cover bad loan write-offs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new disclosure standards, applied for last fiscal year  
ended March 31, problem loans include those extended to bankrupt 
borrowers, companies in danger of failing and loan guarantees or 
loaned securities which have gone bad. 
</P>
<P>
	The average ratio of bad debt to total outstanding credit,  
including debt guarantees, was 5.9 percent among the 17 banks, the 
report said. Nippon Trust Bank Ltd. had a 23.6 percent ratio, the 
highest among them. 
</P>
<P>
	Top-ranked Tokyo-Mitsubishi Bank Ltd., the only major commercial  
bank which did not receive public funds in a taxpayer-financed bank 
industry bailout, had a 4.6 percent ratio of bad debt to its total 
lending, the Nihon Keizai said. 
</P>
<P>
	Total write-offs at the 17 major Japanese banks amounted to  
$88.52 billion at the end of March 31, the report said. All but 
Daiwa Bank Ltd. have recently announced their earnings results, and 
all have reported losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said write-offs of bad debt held by Daiwa Bank, which  
is to announce its earnings on Thursday, were calculated based on 
the bank's previously announced restructuring plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Four banks, which had become insolvent due largely to problem  
loans, have been put under state control since late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 12:23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lopez Releasing 'Latin Soul' Album </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jennifer Lopez has already played a singing  
sensation in the movies. Now she hopes to be one. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Selena'' actress releases her first album, ``On the 6,''  
on June 1. She sings in English and says the sound is ``Latin 
soul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``English is my first language. I grew up here. I was born here.  
I didn't have a career in Spanish first,'' Ms. Lopez says. ``I 
think it appeals definitely to my generation of people, who grew up 
in America but had Latin parents or parents of a different 
ethnicity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The album includes a duet with popular Puerto Rican salsa singer  
Marc Anthony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
