<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Indy 500 Field Set </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Arie Luyendyk will have the best seat in the  
house for the start of his last ride in the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	The 45-year-old Flying Dutchman, a two-time winner who already  
holds virtually every speed record at the Brickyard, is retiring 
after Sunday's race. Fittingly, he will start from the pole 
position, on the inside of the front row. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm ecstatic about being on the pole, but I would have been  
very satisfied with being on the front row,'' Luyendyk said. ``Even 
before qualifying, I did think that we were going to be competitive 
in the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Ray had the fastest speeds most of last week in practice  
and was a favorite to win the pole. Luyendyk turned a four-lap 
average of 225.179 mph on Saturday, then waited to see if Ray, or 
anyone, could oust him from the pole. 
</P>
<P>
	Just over an hour later, Ray came close at 225.073, but when  
Pole Day was over, Luyendyk was still at the top of the lineup. 
Five other drivers were bumped by faster qualifiers on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The track will be closed until race day, except for a final  
two-hour practice session on Thursday, known as Carburetion Day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a lot more nervous watching him than driving the race  
car myself, I can tell you that,'' Luyendyk said of the late 
challenge by Ray, who will start from the middle of the front row. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before my qualifying run, I pretty much had run through my  
qualifying, what I was going to do, how I was going to take the 
turns, what line to go, so I was pretty calm about my own run,'' 
Luyendyk said. ``But when I saw him run, I was really nervous 
because he was my main competitor. It was very close. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we're here to win, so I'm glad he came up short.''  
</P>
<P>
	It will be the third start from the pole for Luyendyk, who also  
is the Indy career money leader with $5.2 million from his first 14 
races. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thrill is the same,'' he said of winning the pole again.  
``I would say this was, maybe at this stage of my career, more of a 
thrill just because of the way the fans reacted coming on down back 
into the pits, and people waving in the pits and thumbs up and 
things like that. ... So it was a very special moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A tentative lineup of 33 cars -- a record for first-day  
qualifiers -- was set on Saturday, putting hard-luck Billy Boat on 
the outside of the front row, a rushed Tony Stewart far back in the 
pack in Row 8, and a nervous Lyn St. James on the bubble with the 
slowest speed. 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipating she would be bumped from the lineup by a faster  
qualifier, St. James took a backup car out to practice Sunday 
morning but blew an engine and slid into the wall in the fourth 
turn. 
</P>
<P>
	She wasn't hurt, but it didn't matter. When Raul Boesel  
qualified on Sunday, St. James became the first of the five drivers 
bumped from the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Unser then bumped rookie Jaques Lazier, younger brother  
of former winner Buddy Lazier; Jack Miller knocked Stephan Gregoire 
out of the starting field, Mike Groff bumped Scott Harrington, and 
Robbie Buhl, who took over an A.J. Foyt backup after his own car 
blew an engine, bumped Groff. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we took the car back and started busting it apart, we  
figured, `This isn't gonna work,''' Buhl said. ``Somebody talked to 
A.J., so I went to see him. ... A.J. was kind enough to say, `Hey, 
I've got two (backup) cars. See which one works best for you.' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our two teams pulled together and made a couple calls that  
were right. I think we timed it just right,'' Buhl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes after Buhl qualified, the track was closed by rain,  
leaving rookie Wim Eyckmans of Belgium, driving for owner-teammate 
Eddie Cheever, as the slowest in the field at 220.092 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Boat, who crashed three times in the past week -- including once  
on a warmup lap before qualifications Saturday -- earned his 
front-row start with an average of 223.469 mph. Robby Gordon, who 
took over a Team Menard backup car at almost the last minute, 
qualified on the inside of the second row at 223.066, next to Mark 
Dismore and Scott Sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk's Treadway Racing teammate, Sam Schmidt, is on the  
inside of the third row, next to Kenny Brack and Scott Goodyear. 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever, the defending Indy winner, will start from the inside  
of the sixth row. Buddy Lazier, the only other former winner 
besides Luyendyk and Cheever, will be on the inside of Row 8, next 
to Roberto Moreno and Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, one of the fastest in practice last week, had to rush  
through qualifications in order to get to Concord, N.C., in time 
for practice for Saturday night's Winston Open, an all-star NASCAR 
race. He'll also leave right after Sunday's race to compete in the 
Coca-Cola 600 at Concord that night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to go quicker, obviously, but we were flat-out the  
whole way around. That's all the car had,'' Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	His 220.653 mph run was some 6 mph slower than his top speed in  
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The field average is 221.558, up from last year's 218.305 but  
well below the record 227.807 set in 1996, before the Indy Racing 
League adopted its current engine and chassis formula. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
