<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sonia Gandhi To Rescind Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sonia Gandhi withdrew her resignation as  
president of India's Congress Party today, ending a leadership 
crisis in the main opposition ahead of fall elections, party 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi agreed to preside over a meeting Tuesday of 1,200  
Congress party representatives from across the country, senior 
party leader ' Mukherjee said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has reconsidered her decision and agreed to continue as  
Congress president,'' Mukherjee said after a meeting of the 
Congress Working Committee, the party's highest decision-making 
body. 
</P>
<P>
	As word reached hundreds of party members waiting outside the  
Congress Party headquarters, people hugged each other in joy. 
Slogans hailing Mrs. Gandhi echoed across the avenue, not far from 
her residence. 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting of the All India Congress Committee was called in New  
Delhi to plead with Mrs. Gandhi to rescind her resignation as 
president of India's oldest political group. But Mrs. Gandhi acted 
before the meeting in response to a plea from the working 
committee, Mukherjee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi resigned last week after three top party officials  
asked her to step down from the prime minister's race because her 
Italian ancestry was turning into an election issue and many 
Indians resented the thought of a foreign-born citizen running for 
the highest elected office. 
</P>
<P>
	They also said she lacks political experience -- unlike her slain  
husband, Rajiv Gandhi; her mother-in-law, Indira Gandhi; or her 
mother-in-law's father, Jawaharlal Nehru, who served as lawmakers 
before they became prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	After Mrs. Gandhi resigned, hundreds of party workers besieged  
her fortress-like house in New Delhi for days to pressure her to 
reconsider. Four chief ministers offered to quit their jobs; dozens 
of officials quit their party posts; supporters threatened to 
immolate themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The three top officials who criticized her were thrown out of  
the party without discussion on the issues they had raised. Their 
expulsion could hurt the prospects of the Congress in the September 
general elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials include Sharad Pawar, formerly the Congress  
powerhouse in the western state of Maharashtra, whose capital, 
Bombay, is the country's financial capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Pawar and the other two -- former house speaker Purno Sangma and  
lawmaker Tariq Anwar -- plan to form another party that will focus 
on issues such as women's empowerment and reduction of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
