<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Most Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against most major currencies  
Monday as it followed tumbling U.S. stocks in the absence of 
guidance from economic data or other news. 
</P>
<P>
	``The life of the dollar is highly correlated right now with the  
stock market,'' said Hillel Waxman, chief foreign exchange dealer 
at Bank Leumi USA. ``There was nothing else to look at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0594, rising from $1.0568 Friday. The  
dollar fell to 123.21 yen from 124.01 yen Friday, The dollar also 
was quoted at 1.5122 Swiss francs, down from 1.5166; and 1.4546 
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4610. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors had nothing fresh to guide their trading, so they  
played along with U.S. stocks. The broader market indicators fell 
as the Dow Jones industrial averages plummeted 203 points before 
ending the day down 174.61, or by 1.6 percent, at 10,654.67. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's fall, however, was far less grave.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's been some solace that (the dollar) hasn't fallen apart  
on the selloff in the marketplace,'' Waxman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar has been drawing its strength lately from the U.S.  
economy, not only the strongest in the world but in a league where 
the No. 2 economy, Japan, is in severe recession, and No. 3, 
Germany, is holding down Europe, which is engaged in expensive 
combat with Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. currency is holding its own against the yen also  
because traders and analysts consider economic recovery in Asia as 
poorly undergirded, Waxman said. Some countries have started 
regaining their foothold after the widespread collapse that began 
nearly two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tenuous recovery. If someone like Japan sneezes, then  
the rest of Asia will need a massive dose of antibiotics,'' Waxman 
said. ``The market is very uncomfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As far as the new European currency is concerned, Waxman said,  
``The only thing that can make the euro bounce 3 or 4 cents is the 
immediate cessation of hostilities in Europe.'' NATO has been 
bombing Yugoslavia since the end of March. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the British pound fell to $1.5964 from  
$1.6013. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8460 German marks, down from 1.8508; 6.1920 French francs, down 
from 6.2073; and 1,828.15 Italian lire, down from 1,831.50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
