<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Talks Held in Shipyard Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMPTON, Va. (AP) -- Negotiators for Newport News Shipbuilding,  
the nation's only builder of aircraft carriers, and the United 
Steelworkers met today for the first time since before the union 
went on strike seven weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for both sides said they hoped the meeting arranged by  
federal mediators would lead to a contract agreement and the end of 
the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very optimistic,'' Arnold Outlaw, president of  
Steelworkers Local 8888, said as he and about a half dozen other 
union representatives headed into the closed meeting at a Hampton 
hotel. Local 8888 represents 9,200 hourly workers at the yard. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipyard spokesman Mike Hatfield would not say whether the yard  
was willing to budge from what it called its final contract offer, 
which it delivered during the last talks, on March 30. The strike 
began April 5, when the old contract expired. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatfield said shipyard officials are hopeful about ending the  
strike now that talks have resumed. But he added that the union 
must be realistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot pay more than what the industry standard is or we  
will not be competitive,'' Hatfield said. ``We made the best offer 
in the industry and we were really surprised they didn't take 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company offered an overall increase of $2.49 an hour over 47  
months for the average worker, who makes $13.50. The union wanted 
an across-the-board increase of $3.95 an hour over 36 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides also have been unable to agree on pension and  
health care benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
