<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 21:31:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Talks Held in Shipyard Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAMPTON, Va. (AP) -- The union representing Newport News  
Shipbuilding workers has given the shipyard a modified contract 
proposal, but the company did not indicate the proposal marked a 
breakthrough in the seven-week strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks Monday were the first since the walkout began April 5.  
</P>
<P>
	The union offered to settle the wage dispute for an  
across-the-board increase of $3.70 an hour over 36 months, United 
Steelworkers spokesman John Duray said. That's a 25-cent drop from 
the union's previous demand of $3.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipyard spokeswoman Jerri Fuller Dickseski said the company,  
the nation's only builder of aircraft carriers, would review the 
union's proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, we're disappointed because on first glance it doesn't  
appear that they've modified their position anywhere close to the 
competitive framework we've outlined,'' Ms. Dickseski said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, in an offer made March 30, said it would boost the  
average employee's wage of $13.50 an hour by $2.49 an hour over 47 
months. The shipyard had said that was its final offer, which it 
called the best in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials said the optimism they felt before Monday's  
talks waned by the time the meeting ended in late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the company has any intention of trying to  
bargain in good faith,'' said Arnold Outlaw, president of 
Steelworkers Local 8888, which represents 9,200 hourly workers at 
the shipyard. ``I think they are trying to break the spirit of the 
union.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Outlaw said both sides met separately with mediators and then,  
``We got back together for some chit-chat. We gave the company a 
counter proposal. Shortly after we gave it to them, they walked 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting was convened under an order of the Federal Mediation  
and Conciliation Service. Union representatives were scheduled to 
meet with federal mediators again today, Outlaw said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Dickseski said company negotiators will be available to meet  
again as well ``if we receive a call to return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides also have been unable to agree on pension and  
health care benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, shipyard spokesman Mike Hatfield said more employees  
return to work every day and that the yard is operating at 
``something approaching 60 percent productivity.'' He declined to 
say how many workers had crossed the picket line. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers walking the picket line at the shipyard Monday said they  
were resolved to stay off the job for as long as necessary to get a 
better contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheila Harrison, 35, of Surry County, said she doubted the talks  
would lead to a quick resolution, unless shipyard officials eased 
their position. ``They're stubborn,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Still, anything's better than nothing,'' added Ms. Harrison, a  
ship painter who has worked at the yard eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Laverne Kenon, 39, of Chesapeake, said she wanted the union to  
remain firm and not give a lot of concessions just to end the 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers ``have given up a lot in the past,'' said Ms. Kenon,  
an insulator and ship cleaner with 11 years at the yard. ``It's 
time that they (shipyard officials) give us something.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
