<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *James Blades    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- James Blades, a symphonic percussionist whose most  
widely heard work was banging out ``V for victory'' for the BBC's 
wartime broadcasts, died Wednesday at age 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Blades also recorded the sound of the gong that was featured in  
the opening credits of films by the J. Arthur Rank studios. 
</P>
<P>
	His recording of the Morse code for ``V'' was played up to 150  
times a day at the start of British Broadcasting Corp. broadcasts 
to occupied Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Blades began drumming with a circus, then in cinemas. In 1982,  
he joined the London Film Society Orchestra. During the war he 
began playing with the London Philharmonic Orchestra, and later 
with the English Opera Group, the Aldeburgh Festival and the 
English Chamber Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote ``Percussion Instruments and Their History,'' published  
in 1970, and two volumes of autobiography. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Vanessa Brown    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Vanessa Brown, who made her Broadway debut at  
13 and played ingenue roles in films of the 1940s and '50s before 
becoming a journalist, died Friday of cancer. She was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	She made her first movie at 16, 1944's ``Youth Runs Wild.''  
Other films included ``Margie,'' ``The Ghost and Mrs. Muir'' and 
``The Bad and the Beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Born Smylla Brind in 1928 in Vienna, her family fled the Nazis  
when she was 9, moving first to France and then America. She heard 
that the producer of the play ``Watch on the Rhine'' was looking 
for a girl with a German accent. She went to the play's author, 
Lillian Hellman, got an understudy part and by the end of the 
Broadway run was a regular cast member. 
</P>
<P>
	At 14, Ms. Brown joined ``The Quiz Kids'' radio show, a popular  
program with a panel of children answering listeners' questions. 
She also did stage work, appearing on Broadway in 1952 in ``The 
Seven Year Itch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She left acting in 1959, but returned to the screen in the 1967  
film ``Rosie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1980s and 1990s she appeared on such television shows as  
``General Hospital,'' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and ``Homicide: Life on 
the Street.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brown also was a playwright, novelist and a journalist,  
publishing in many newspapers and magazines and freelancing for the 
Voice of America. 

</P>
<P>
                      *John T. ``Chick'' Hayward    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTIC BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Retired Vice Adm. John T. ``Chick''  
Hayward, who helped develop the atomic bomb dropped over Nagasaki, 
died Sunday of cancer. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayward also developed systems for ground and air-launched  
rockets and became a pioneer in the development of weapons used to 
fight submarines. 
</P>
<P>
	He lied about his age to get into the Navy as a 15-year-old in  
1925. He graduated from the Naval Academy in 1930 and flew dozens 
of bombing missions over the South Pacific in the early part of 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Hayward joined the Manhattan Project at the China Lake Naval  
Ordinance Test Station in California in 1944. He helped develop the 
implosion components of the bomb dropped over Nagasaki on Aug. 9, 
1945. He was not involved in the development of the atomic bomb 
dropped on Hiroshima three days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	He also commanded the first nuclear-powered task force in naval  
history, leading the USS Enterprise. In 1966, as a vice admiral, he 
was named president of the Naval War College in Newport, R.I., and 
remained there until his retirement from the Navy in 1968. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Chester Migden    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former labor lawyer Chester ``Chet'' Migden,  
whose 30 years of work for the Screen Actors Guild remains the 
cornerstone for numerous entertainment work contracts, died Sunday 
of cardiac arrest. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Migden also worked for the National Labor Relations Board from  
1947 to 1951. 
</P>
<P>
	When Migden joined SAG in 1952 as national executive director,  
the union had 9,600 members and offices in three cities. On the eve 
of his retirement 30 years later, SAG had more than 50,000 members 
and branches in 15 cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Migden helped devise the principle of paying actors residuals  
for television reruns. He negotiated all agency franchise 
agreements between 1952 and 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	After SAG, Migden worked for more than a decade as executive  
director of the Association of Talent Agents until he retired in 
1996. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Dr. Harry Prystowsky    	
</P>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Dr. Harry Prystowsky, the former dean  
of Penn State's College of Medicine and senior vice president for 
health affairs at Hershey Medical Center, died Thursday at age 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Prystowsky's tenure beginning in 1973, the College of  
Medicine expanded from 400 to 3,000 employees and expanded its 
operating budget from $20 million to $200 million. He served as 
dean for 13 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, he was appointed to the then-new position of senior  
vice president for health affairs at Penn State's Hershey Medical 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to Penn State, Prystowsky had been a professor and  
chairman of the Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology at the 
University of Florida in Gainesville. An endowed chair in 
reproductive medicine was established there in his name. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Robert Rhodes James    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Robert Rhodes James, a prolific historian  
whose books included biographies of kings and prime ministers, died 
Thursday. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not released.  
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes James knew politics from the inside, serving as a clerk  
in the House of Commons for a decade and spending three years as a 
senior aide to U.N. Secretary-General Kurt Waldheim. He was elected 
to the House of Commons as a Conservative Party candidate in 1976, 
representing his Cambridge district until retiring in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes James published his first work in 1959, a biography of  
Lord Randolph Churchill, the father of Winston Churchill. He won 
acclaim with his next book, a life of Lord Rosebery, who became 
prime minister in 1894. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, he published ``Gallipoli,'' becoming the first  
historian to use unpublished papers from the official inquiry into 
the disastrous Dardanelles Campaign in 1915. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, Rhodes James published ``Churchill, a Study in Failure:  
1900-1939,'' examined the frustrations and failures of Winston 
Churchill before he became Britain's wartime prime minister. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Alvin John Rockwell    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Alvin John Rockwell, an attorney who helped  
shape West Germany's democratic government after World War II, died 
Wednesday of coronary artery disease. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell moved to Berlin in 1945 to serve as legal adviser to  
the commander of American forces occupying part of Germany. He was 
assigned to rebuild the German legal system, blending German 
tradition and Western democratic principles. 
</P>
<P>
	He became involved in relations between the U.S. and the Soviet  
Union when, in 1959, Nikita Khrushchev toured San Francisco as part 
of a controversial visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell was president of the World Affairs Council of Northern  
California, and Khrushchev had just been denied permission to visit 
Los Angeles and Disneyland. 
</P>
<P>
	At a dinner in his honor, a speech by Rockwell was credited with  
helping to defuse the tension that had built up around Khrushchev's 
U.S. tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockwell practiced law in Boston, then moved to Washington for a  
stint in the solicitor general's office as special assistant to the 
U.S. attorney general and as attorney for the National Labor 
Relations Board. Rockwell later came to San Francisco to join 
Brobeck, Phleger and Harrison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 14:23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Stymies Deutsche Telekom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Olivetti's stunning acquisition of a majority  
stake in Telecom Italia has dealt a severe blow to Germany's 
Deutsche Telekom and its ambition of creating a pan-European 
telecommunications leader and world-class competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti SpA's hostile action has stymied Deutsche Telekom AG's  
plan to merge with Telecom Italia SpA and left it struggling to 
mend tattered ties with France Telecom, its partner in other 
ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Deutsche Telekom's biggest German competitor,  
Mannesmann AG, has gained strength and a firm foothold in Italy by 
buying out Olivetti's stake in two telephone subsidiaries. 
Mannesmann's $8 billion purchase of the cellular unit Omnitel and 
fixed-line operator Infostrada helped Olivetti finance its highly 
leveraged bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom's chief executive Ron Sommer gamely insists  
that he hopes to salvage a merger with Telecom Italia under its new 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sommer's bargaining position in any future deal may suffer  
as a result of the Italian setback. 
</P>
<P>
	``He gambled on this one. It's now fallen flat. He's upset  
France Telecom. Where does he go from here?'' said Mark Horn, an 
industry analyst at London-based brokerage T. Hoare Canaccord. 
</P>
<P>
	By grabbing nearly 52 percent of its larger rival's shares in a  
$64 billion bid, Olivetti has forced a competitive realignment in 
Europe's telecommunications industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom had spoken publicly just weeks ago about its  
desire to acquire a U.S. company and compete on a global scale with 
the likes of AT&AMP;T Corp. Now, shorn of its chosen partner, it must 
drastically alter its expansion strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our objective remains that of becoming a global player,''  
spokesman Juergen Kindervater was quoted as saying by Italy's Ansa 
news agency. ``Telecom Italia is an option, but there are others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Calls seeking further details from Deutsche Telekom's  
headquarters in Bonn were not immediately returned on Monday, which 
was a holiday in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	In Rome, Telecom Italia chief executive Franco Bernabe met  
Monday with his Olivetti counterpart Roberto Colaninno to discuss 
the transfer of corporate control. It was the pair's first meeting 
since Olivetti garnered its slim majority of support from Telecom 
shareholders on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno has not ruled out merging with Deutsche Telekom,  
albeit on different terms than the ones Bernabe agreed to. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have always said that I'm not against discussing all  
opportunities,'' he said this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading in Milan, Italy, Olivetti stock rose 1.8 percent  
Monday to the equivalent of $3.65 a share, while Telecom Italia 
fell 2.1 percent to $9.94 a share. On the New York Stock Exchange, 
the U.S. shares of Telecom Italia fell 9 percent, or by $9.81 1/4, to 
close at $99.18 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia executives were expected to  
meet as early as Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the German-Italian merger plans collapse, as many  
analysts predict, Deutsche Telekom may need to rebuild politically 
sensitive relations with France Telecom. The French phone company 
was outraged when Deutsche Telekom unveiled it merger plans with 
Telecom Italia and has threatened to sue for billions of dollars, 
citing breach of contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom have reciprocal 2 percent  
shareholdings, and together with Sprint Corp. of the United States, 
they own the Global One joint venture. They also hold minority 
stakes in the Italian telephone consortium Wind. 
</P>
<P>
	Exacerbating Deutsche Telekom's problems is the rise of domestic  
competitors like Mannesmann, a former engineering firm. Mannesmann 
teamed up with Olivetti and expanded its ownership of Omnitel, 
taking an even bigger position in Italy, Europe's biggest mobile 
phone market. 
</P>
<P>
	Uncertain of his prospects with either Telecom Italia or France  
Telecom, Deutsche Telekom's Sommer may seek other alliances. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts point to Britain's No. 2 phone company, Cable &AMP;  
Wireless PLC, as a possible target -- speculation that the British 
company has denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutsche Telekom plans to raise some $10.6 billion by issuing  
new shares next month, greatly enhancing its ability to finance a 
merger or acquisition. It plans also to bring in additional cash by 
spinning off much of its domestic cable business. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
