<HEADLINE> Reds' Neagle Placed on 15-day DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Denny Neagle, who is 0-3 with an 8.17 ERA in  
six starts, was placed on the 15-day disabled list by the 
Cincinnati Reds Monday, retroactive to May 20. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Jim Bowden said Neagle has tendinitis in his  
left shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``The medical information we have been provided is not  
consistent with our baseball evaluation,'' Bowden said. 
``Therefore, we have asked for additional medical opinions and 
evaluations of Denny's left shoulder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle, who was obtained from the Atlanta Braves during the  
off-season, was diagnosed with weakness in the rotator cuff in 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	That diagnosis was affirmed in an examination Friday by Dr.  
Ralph Gambardella at the Kerlan-Jobe Clinic in Los Angeles. 
However, surgery was not recommended. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our present plan for treatment is not working,'' Bowden said.  
``There is no point continuing along a path that has not allowed 
the strength in Denny's left shoulder to improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``If surgery is not recommended by the physicians, then we must  
find a better way to strengthen the rotator cuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Post reported that the MRI performed in Los  
Angeles showed that Neagle likely has a slight tear in the 
underside of his rotator cuff, and minor fraying of the labrum 
cartilage in the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said a copy of the MRI would be sent to Dr. Steve  
Pomeranz of Pro-Scan in Cincinnati for analysis. Copies also have 
been sent to Dr. Stanley Ho at Stanford University, and to Dr. 
James Meranus of Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle also is scheduled to be examined Wednesday by Dr. James  
Andrews in Birmingham, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Neagle had won at least 16 games in each of the past three  
seasons and was expected to be the Reds' ace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
