<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aguilera Hopes To Save Cubs' Pen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Finding Wrigley Field was no problem for Rick  
Aguilera. In fact, he had more trouble locating the bathroom in his 
new home clubhouse than he did driving to work. All part of a 
fitting-in process Monday for the Chicago Cubs' new closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera had a rough night in his home debut with his new team,  
giving up four runs in the ninth inning to suffer the loss as the 
Florida Marlins beat the Cubs 7-5. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the way I was hoping to start off. It's a long season  
and I didn't expect not to have a bad day. But I certainly wasn't 
expecting one this soon,'' Aguilera said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera wanted to stay with the Minnesota Twins and finish his  
career as a closer. But when trade rumors began before spring 
training, he did some checking and after talking with Chicago 
starter Kevin Tapani, one of his best friends, he eventually 
designated the Cubs as a team he'd join. 
</P>
<P>
	``He asked what the team was like and I said it was like the  
team we had in Minnesota in the early 90s,'' Tapani said. ``Guys 
who play hard, get along and are winners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera's reasons for choosing Chicago, he said, were numerous:  
Some of his former teammates included Tapani, Gary Gaetti, reliever 
Dan Serafini and even team GM Ed Lynch from his days with the New 
York Mets. He also called Wrigley Field his favorite park in the 
majors. And he and Tapani's family are extremely close. 
</P>
<P>
	After earlier waiving a no-trade clause, Aguilera was dealt to  
Chicago last week along with Scott Downs for minor league pitchers 
Jason Ryan and Kyle Lohse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not coming here to replace Rod and I'm not coming here  
saying I have to close,'' Aguilera said. ``I told Riggs I came here 
to do whatever I can to help. I hope I'm not expected to come here 
and save every game because I'm not. I'm going to have bad days 
like everybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera, 37, is 19 saves shy of 300 and had a 1.27 ERA with a  
3-1 record and six saves when he left the Twins. He's pitched one 
inning so far with the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	A closer's life can change in a hurry. With one pitch.  
</P>
<P>
	After saving 51 games last season, Beck blew four saves in 11  
chances, had a 10.54 ERA and was 2-4, bringing out the boos birds. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife mentioned that, that they've really been getting on  
Rod Beck after the kind of season he had last year,'' Aguilera 
said. ``I played in New York where there are serious fans and it's 
something I can't control. I hope to pitch well and contribute. If 
that doesn't seem to materialize and I'm booed, we'll have to get 
through that. We'll see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera is also well aware that Beck, who underwent  
arthroscopic surgery, is expected to return before the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally I hope nothing is going to create a conflict  
personally between him and me,'' Aguilera said. ``I hope he is back 
as quickly as he can be and we can work together out of the 
bullpen, however Jim wants to work the bullpen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
