<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: China Nukes Near U.S. Par  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After two decades of stealing U.S. secrets,  
China can build advanced, mobile nuclear weapons ``on a par with 
our own'' and it could begin testing one such weapon as early as 
this year, a congressional report finds. ``These thefts of nuclear 
secrets from our national weapons laboratories enabled (China) to 
... successfully test modern strategic weapons sooner than would 
otherwise have been possible,'' according to a copy of the report 
obtained by The Associated Press. The report, to be released 
tomorrow, is by a House committee on Chinese espionage. It says 
China stole secrets about the seven major U.S. nuclear warheads and 
the neutron bomb. The thefts ``almost certainly continue to the 
present,'' the House report concluded. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton: I'll Live in N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton says she will  
live in New York after leaving the White House, whether or not she 
runs for the Senate. She made the pledge during a CBS-TV interview 
for ``60 Minutes II.'' Asked which New York baseball team she would 
root for, she said: ``The politic answer, since I do plan to live 
in New York no matter what I end up doing, is I'll root for both.'' 
The interview will air Wednesday night. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Pounds Yugoslavia Again  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As allied air attacks entered their  
third month, NATO warplanes pounded Yugoslavia again. Air raid 
sirens sounded after sundown in Belgrade, Novi Sad, Nis and 
elsewhere. Ten explosions rocked Novi Sad near a refinery and power 
station and four NATO missiles hit civilian targets 15 miles 
southwest of Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina, the state-run 
Tanjug news agency reported. Belgrade was down to its last 10 
percent of water reserves because of damaged pumping stations and a 
power outage, media reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools Can Be Sued on Sex Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled 5-4 today that schools  
can be sued if they fail to stop students from sexually harassing 
each other. It found that schools that accept federal money can be 
made to pay victims. The court also decided that police who let the 
news media accompany them into people's homes can be sued for 
violating the Constitution's protection against unreasonable 
searches. It also turned down an appeal by a Maine dentist who was 
sued for refusing to treat a woman because she has the virus that 
causes AIDS. 

</P>
<P>
	Attorney: NYC Cop To Plead Guilty  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A police officer accused of torturing a prisoner  
inside a Brooklyn stationhouse will change his plea to guilty, his 
lawyer told a federal judge. ``We would like to enter a plea,'' 
attorney Marvyn Kornberg, lawyer for Officer Justin Volpe, said 
according to a transcript. A source connected with the prosecution 
who requested anonymity said there was no agreement with Volpe on a 
recommended sentence. The case against four remaining officers was 
expected to proceed. The five were accused of mistreating a black 
Haitian immigrant. 

</P>
<P>
	Gandhi Withdraws Party Resignation  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Ending a leadership crisis for India's  
main opposition party, Sonia Gandhi announced she would remain at 
the helm of the Congress Party. Mrs. Gandhi had quit after three 
party leaders asked her to step down from the prime ministerial 
race because her Italian ancestry was turning into an issue. Many 
Indians opposed the candidacy of a foreign-born citizen in the race 
for the highest elected office. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Decline in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks dropped Tuesday on renewed concern  
about Japan's banking system. The Nikkei fell 153.41 points to 
16,237.08 in early trading. In New York, the Dow ended at 
10,654.67, down 174.61. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Sweep Hawks  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks completed a 4-0 sweep of the  
Atlanta Hawks with a 79-66 victory tonight, advancing to the NBA 
East finals against the Indiana Pacers. For New York, Allan Houston 
scored 19 points, Patrick Ewing had 17 and Latrell Sprewell added 
11. 

</P>
<P>
	Mike Tyson Gets Out of Jail  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mike Tyson walked out of a suburban Maryland  
jail today after serving less than a quarter of his one-year 
sentence for assaulting after a traffic accident. The 
ex-heavyweight champ was freed after an Indiana judge ended his 
probation for a 1992 rape conviction. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
</P>
</TEXT>
