<DOCNO> APW19990524.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 22:21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Campaigning Against Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Campaigning to overtake Vice President Al Gore  
in ``a brand new game,'' Democratic challenger Bill Bradley isn't 
ready to argue about their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not at a contrast stage right now,'' he said. ``This is  
not where things are. This is the defining stage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His is a careful, cautious game plan, in which, for example, he  
says trust is essential to a president and describes that as 
something in need of repair -- but he won't blame President 
Clinton's misconduct and impeachment for the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, fill in the blanks,'' is as far as he'll venture.  
</P>
<P>
	A candidate tackling a vice president with presidential  
political sponsorship, along with most of the party establishment, 
would ordinarily take the offensive from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	Not Bradley. He passes up open targets. He'll go only so far as  
to describe his record in the Senate -- he was there from New Jersey 
while Gore was senator from Tennessee -- as one of more risk-taking 
to deal with complex issues such as tax reform, trade and race, 
despite the risks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a risk of leadership, and I think the vice president has  
been more cautious,'' Bradley said in an interview with The 
Associated Press. ``And I think there is a difference. I think it 
implies a different kind of presidency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he's not addressing Gore's sometimes embarrassing  
involvement in 1996 campaign finance excesses. Bradley said that 
``to be a credible advocate for campaign finance reform as 
president,'' he has to do his own fund raising for 2000 on a 
standard higher than the existing law requires. No loopholes, he 
promised. 
</P>
<P>
	So, will Gore's past problems affect his future franchise on  
that issue? 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't know that until after you see the way a campaign is  
conducted,'' Bradley fenced. ``I think a campaign defines a 
candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As to the question of trust, in a president, in political  
institutions, and of a president in the people, Bradley said he 
wants to repair it, although Gore could, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know why not. I think he's been an honorable man, as  
far as I know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans criticize Gore as a cheerleader for Clinton. Bradley  
does not. ``I'm not going to get into criticizing the vice 
president, how he's conducted himself,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	What about Gore's description of Clinton as one of the great  
presidents? 
</P>
<P>
	``I actually thought Lincoln was better.''  
</P>
<P>
	On the current agenda, Bradley is considering an aggressive gun  
control proposal that may include a ban on the sale of handguns, 
along with a national handgun card with a photo ID, registration of 
gun resales as is done with automobiles, higher license fees for 
dealers and a stiff federal tax on handguns and ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	He laid out much of that program, but not the outright ban, as a  
senator. ``I'm considering all the alternatives,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But for later in the campaign, not now.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore just got a boost on the gun control issue by casting the  
tie-breaking Senate vote to pass a measure requiring background 
checks of all firearms purchasers at gun shows and pawn shops. ``I 
applaud it,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Bradley, his task at this point is to tell people  
who he is, not how he differs with his opponent. A new poll shows 
97 percent of voters have heard of Gore, to Bradley's 60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But he is going to have to tell people where he disagrees with  
Gore or he won't have much of an argument for a change by 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you should do that in the fall,'' said Bradley,  
describing that as the ``beginning of the engagement of the 
campaign not only with the Democratic opponent but also with 
potential Republican opponents on the most thorough level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That cautious schedule defies conventional wisdom as the  
strategy of a candidate trying to catch up, but Bradley said this 
is different. 
</P>
<P>
	``As it has evolved, it's a brand new game,'' he said. ``There's  
never been a one-on-one, 11-month primary before. ... This is a 
totally different pace and a different rhythm. It's a different 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also is an expensive one, and Bradley got off to a  
respectable, to some surprising, start raising funds for 2000, 
reporting that he took in $4.3 million in the first three months of 
1999. Gore raised more than twice as much, toward a campaign target 
of $55 million. Bradley said he can be competitive with a 
$20-to-$25 million campaign budget. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
