<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore told Florida  
supporters Monday that he celebrated his 29th wedding anniversary 
with a visit to the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic presidential contender said he had made  
reservations to celebrate with his wife, Tipper, at a cozy country 
inn outside Washington. But that was before the Senate began debate 
last week on an administration-supported amendment to tighten 
restrictions on gun show sales. 
</P>
<P>
	As he and Mrs. Gore headed out on their romantic escape, Gore  
said he checked in with the office on how the Senate vote was 
going. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tipper so strongly supported the amendment that was pending  
... that I celebrated our anniversary by going to the Senate and 
casting the tie-breaking vote,'' Gore said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 250 supporters of ``Gore 2000'' paid $1,000 apiece to share  
mixed greens, grilled chicken and New York cheesecake with the vice 
president. Gore apologized for shaking just a few hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're on a schedule here and they told me that I had to try to  
eat quickly and then talk,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential aspirant Gary Bauer  
urged President Clinton on Monday to be ``morally courageous'' and 
reverse an advisory panel's recommendations for government funding 
of limited forms of human embryo research. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Bioethics Advisory Commission recommended in a  
draft report to Congress that the four-year ban on spending federal 
money for embryonic research be rescinded in part. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can never be acceptable to take an innocent human life and  
that includes the embryonic stage,'' said Bauer, who opposes 
abortion. ``This president should be morally courageous enough to 
step in and reverse his own panel's recommendation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer said that despite arguments that embryonic research has  
potentially enormous medical benefits, it actually has the opposite 
effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``Snuffing out life in its earliest stage can never be to the  
greater good,'' Bauer said. ``It sends the signal that some life is 
expendable depending on the circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is sharply  
criticizing a parody of his presidential campaign's Internet web 
site, calling it ``garbage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The parody site, gwbush.com, is nearly identical to the  
legitimate Bush site, except on close inspection, its ``news'' 
items about the Republican governor are obviously satirical. 
</P>
<P>
	One item, for example, says Bush has ``a bold new policy  
initiative to free all `grown ups' from federal prisons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference last week, Bush was asked about the parody,  
and he had some harsh words for the site's designer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There ought to be limits to freedom,'' Bush said. ``We're  
aware of the site, and this guy is just a garbage man, that's all 
he is. Of course I don't appreciate it. And you wouldn't, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray Thomas, one of the site's operators, said in a telephone  
interview the Bush campaign is overreacting to humorous satire. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are opinions and there are facts,'' Thomas said. ``What  
we're doing is satire. He keeps saying this goes beyond humor. In 
fact, good humor often has a point. We're talking about Bush, we're 
talking about politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The address for the official Bush web site is  
www.georgewbush.com. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press reporters Sandra Sobieraj,  
Douglas Kiker and Michael Holmes contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
