<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Governor Backs Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Gov. George Pataki, flanked Monday by  
the most of the state's Republican leadership, endorsed George W. 
Bush's bid for the GOP presidential nomination. ``I'm going to 
count on you for the state of New York,'' the Texas governor told 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	That is no easy task. The state, with a 5-3 Democratic  
enrollment advantage, hasn't backed the Republican presidential 
candidate since Ronald Reagan carried it twice, in 1980 and 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki is the 16th Republican governor to endorse Bush, who has  
said he won't start campaigning until the conclusion of the Texas 
legislative session at the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Using a satellite hookup, Pataki told Bush, ``This is the team  
that in November of 2000 is going to shock the world by electing 
George W. Bush and carrying New York state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While more than 20 television cameras recorded the event, Pataki  
cooled speculation that he might run for the Senate. He said that 
while he had learned in politics that ``you never say never ... let 
me make it very plain, at this point, I have no intention of 
running for the Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A possible Pataki Senate run had drawn interest because of his  
chilly relations with New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who has 
formed an exploratory committee to prepare for a possible bid for 
the GOP nomination. Also eyeing the race on the Republican side is 
Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island, who joined Pataki for Monday's 
announcement. Giuliani wasn't invited. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the team that was with the governor in 1994,'' Pataki  
spokeswoman Zenia Mucha said when asked about the absence of 
Giuliani, who had crossed party lines that year to endorse 
then-Gov. Mario Cuomo in the governor's race won by Pataki. ``This 
is the team he wanted together, standing there with him when he 
chose to endorse the next president of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hillary Rodham Clinton is considering a run for the Democratic  
Senate nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki's endorsement of Bush also put an end, at least for the  
moment, on the New York governor's personal presidential ambition. 
He had been traveling the country in recent months seeking to boost 
his national profile. He is still considered a potential GOP vice 
presidential candidate next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush told Pataki, ``I intend to listen to you about more than  
just New York politics. ... The goal is much bigger than the two 
Georges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki assured Bush that ``New Yorkers are never shy or at a  
loss for ideas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Pataki and the rest of the New York Republican  
establishment came out early for Bob Dole and delivered all of the 
state's 93 national convention delegates to him. But they were 
unable to do the same for him in the general election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 15:51:45 </DATE_TIME>
