<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 14:32:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reaction to Police Privacy Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Reaction to the Supreme Court's unanimous decision Monday that  
said police violate people's privacy rights when they bring the 
news media into homes while they make arrests or conduct searches: 
</P>
<P>
	Richard K. Willard, attorney representing Charles and Geraldine  
Wilson in the Maryland case: ``I'm certainly pleased with the 
constitutional ruling. It establishes a clear constitutional 
decision here that the police cannot bring the news media'' into 
private homes without the residents' consent. ``This kind of thing 
can't happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henry H. Rossbacher, lawyer for Paul and Erma Berger in the  
Montana case: ``I'm delighted that the court affirmed the Fourth 
Amendment violation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joshua L. Dratel of the National Association of Criminal Defense  
Lawyers, which supported the Bergers: ``It's clear and there's no 
mistake anymore. ... It's a violation of the Fourth Amendment. ... 
The government is not allowed to make a display of you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Spitzer of the American Civil Liberties Union, which  
helped represent the Wilsons: ``This ruling says law enforcement 
officers must be guided by the Fourth Amendment and not by the 
demands of the `infotainment' industry. ... Today the court said 
the Constitution is more important than getting good publicity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Cordray, lawyer for the law enforcement officers in both  
cases: ``They were very sensible and fair rulings. ... The court 
didn't say all media ride-alongs are impermissible.'' The media can 
go along with police so long as they remain in public places, he 
said, adding, ``They just won't be able to go into the home 
themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Levine, attorney representing The Associated Press, ABC and  
other media which supported the police officers: ``I can't say I'm 
surprised the court's erected this kind of protective cloak around 
the home. ... This is going to cause law enforcement officers to be 
very cautious about allowing the media to ride along in all sorts 
of circumstances. ... It's bad for the public in the sense that the 
public won't get to see through the press' eyes that important 
aspect of the government's work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Kirtley of the Reporters' Committee for Freedom of the  
Press: ``There are going to be situations where it would be 
valuable for members of the press to be present. ... Given the 
pressure on law enforcement ... it's a given that there are going 
to be some people overzealous in carrying out their duties and I 
think it's important that the public see that. ... It's 
unconscionable for the court to say it's always a violation of 
Fourth Amendment rights'' for the media to accompany police into 
private homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
