<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Pounds Yugoslavia's Power Grids  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO hammered at Serbian power  
plants today as the bombing campaign entered its third month. Much 
of the capital remains without electricity, and the water supply is 
said to be dangerously low. Ten strong explosions rocked 
Yugoslavia's second-biggest city Novi Sad in the area of a refinery 
and power station, and Serb media also reported attacks on other 
targets. Meanwhile, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said there 
is evidence that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic is 
``cracking'' under the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools May Be Liable in Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today ruled that school  
districts can be sued if they fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing each other. The decision sprung from the case of a 
fifth-grade girl who complained about a classmate. The court ruled 
that a Georgia school district can be held financially responsible 
if officials with the authority to help the girl knew about the 
harassment but were ``deliberately indifferent'' to it. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Allowed To Regulate Nonprofits  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today ruled that the Federal  
Trade Commission has the authority to regulate at least some 
nonprofit professional groups in an effort to protect competition. 
But the justices ordered lower courts to take a closer look to 
determine whether the FTC properly invalidated the California 
Dental Association's limits on dentist advertising. Federal law 
gives the FTC authority over any company or association ``organized 
to carry on business for its own profit or that of its members.'' 
The FTC said that includes the nonprofit dental association because 
its goal is to ensure that its members make money. 

</P>
<P>
	Wrestler Killed During WWF Event  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Investigators are trying to figure out  
what went wrong when a popular wrestler was killed last night in an 
accident prior to a match. Owen Hart, also known as the ``Blue 
Blazer,'' plunged 50 feet into the ring as he was being lowered in 
a pre-fight stunt. Some witnesses say his cable snapped during the 
stunt, others think Hart became disconnected from the cable. ``From 
the information we have so far, it had something to do with the 
harness system,'' police said. ``Everyone's talking about something 
happening with the rigging, but it's still under investigation.'' 
An autopsy was planned. 

</P>
<P>
	Malaysia Oil Slick Spreads  
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Workers battled today to get an  
oil spill from a sunken luxury liner under control, dousing the 
35-mile long slick off Malaysia's west coast with chemicals to help 
dissolve it. Environmental officials say the slick, caused by fuel 
seeping from the cruise ship that sank Friday, is 12 miles long and 
growing. The Sun Vista was sailing through the Straits of Malacca 
from the Thai island of Phuket to Singapore when a fire broke out. 
The vessel, with 1,093 passengers and crew aboard, was evacuated 
and later sank. There were no casualties. 

</P>
<P>
	81-Year-Old Climbs El Capitan  
</P>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Eighty-one year-old Gerry  
Bloch became the oldest climber to scale Yosemite National Park's 
famed El Capitan rockface -- for the second time. Bloch, a retired 
chemical engineer from New Jersey, set out on his quest May 12 with 
two other men. The climb was only supposed to take a week, but the 
group was slowed by cold weather and the weight of the food and 
water they carried. He last scaled El Capitan, one of the most 
popular challenges for serious rock climbers, in 1986, when he was 
age 68. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 122  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 122.99 to 10,706.29. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,757-1,093. The Nasdaq was down 51.89 to 
2,468.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Daly Quits As Magic Coach  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Chuck Daly quit as coach of the Orlando  
Magic today and said he won't coach again. Orlando was upset by 
Philadelphia in the first round of the playoffs and Daly had 
several disagreements with star Penny Hardway, but he said neither 
played a role in his decision. Daly had one year remaining on a 
three-year, $5 million contract. ``The mind is willing but the 
flesh is weak,'' the 68-year-old said. 

</P>
<P>
	Kafelnikov, Hingis Win  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- World No. 1 Yevgeny Kafelnikov overcame a  
determined Michael Chang today to win his opening-round match at 
the French Open 6-2, 5-7, 6-0, 7-6 (10-8). Defending champion 
Carlos Moya also had a battle, surviving a five-set threat from 
Markus Hipfl of Austria 3-6, 1-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-4. Other winners on 
the men's side include Andre Agassi. Three top women, Martina 
Hingis and the Williams sisters, Venus and Serena, cruised to 
victories. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
