<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:20 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Schools May Be Liable in Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today ruled that school  
districts can be sued if they fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing each other. The decision sprung from the case of a 
fifth-grade girl who complained about a classmate. The court ruled 
that a Georgia school district can be held financially responsible 
if officials with the authority to help the girl knew about the 
harassment but were ``deliberately indifferent'' to it. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Calls Kosovo Situation `Worse'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The head of a U.N. fact-finding  
mission in Yugoslavia said the humanitarian situation in Kosovo is 
``a lot worse than we feared.'' The team members spent three days 
in Kosovo, and one said ``everything indicates that there is an 
attempt to displace, ethnically cleanse, Kosovo.'' More than 20,000 
ethnic Albanians fled to neighboring Macedonia over the weekend. In 
Albania, where an estimated 438,000 people from Kosovo have fled 
since airstrikes began, more than 1,000 Kosovo refugees had crossed 
the border by midday today, the U.N. group said. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Pounds Yugoslavia's Power Grids  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO hammered at Serbian power  
plants today as the bombing campaign entered its third month. Much 
of the capital remains without electricity, and the water supply is 
said to be dangerously low. Ten strong explosions rocked 
Yugoslavia's second-biggest city, Novi Sad, in the area of a 
refinery and power station, and Serb media also reported attacks on 
other targets. 

</P>
