<DOCNO> APW19990524.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 01:21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forsberg, Lemieux Playing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Peter Forsberg and Claude Lemieux were playing  
pretty well without Valeri Kamensky. With him, they've been 
unbeatable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colorado Avalanche are 5-0 since Kamensky's return from a  
two-month layoff caused by a broken arm. It's no coincidence, 
either, as Kamensky has provided six points and linemates Forsberg 
and Lemieux have stepped up their production. 
</P>
<P>
	Kamensky continued his strong play Saturday night, assisting on  
one goal and scoring the winner as the Avalanche opened the Western 
Conference finals with a 2-1 victory over the Dallas Stars. He also 
had a possible goal nullified on replay. 
</P>
<P>
	Game 2 of the best-of-7 series is tonight.  
</P>
<P>
	``Val's a great skater,'' Lemieux said. ``When he uses his feet,  
he's a force out there. I knew it wouldn't take any time for him to 
jump in and help out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without Kamensky, Colorado eliminated San Jose 4-2 in the first  
round and was down 0-2 to Detroit in the second round. Over those 
eight games, Forsberg had nine points and Lemieux had five. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 33-year-old Russian rejoined the Avalanche's top line,  
they won four straight from Detroit to knock out the two-time 
defending champion Red Wings and got the early jump on the 
top-ranked Stars in the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	In that five-game stretch, Colorado has outscored opponents  
21-8. Kamensky has two goals and four assists, Forsberg has 10 
points, two in each game, and Lemieux has seven. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's bringing a new dimension to our offense,'' coach Bob  
Hartley said. ``He generates a lot defensively with his speed and 
his skill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After missing 23 games because of the injury, Kamensky had an  
assist in his first game back and scored a goal the next game. He 
had two assists in the series finale against Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Kamensky appeared to have jump-started the Avalanche again  
midway through the second period Saturday night by redirecting a 
shot by Lemieux under Dallas goaltender Ed Belfour. 
</P>
<P>
	The red light didn't go on, but Kamensky and teammates began  
celebrating what they thought was a tying goal. 
</P>
<P>
	On-ice officials weren't sure whether the pole stopped the puck  
or if it was prevented from crossing the goal line by a pad at the 
base of the net that went too close to the post. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe the puck never crossed the line,'' Lemieux said, ``but  
it couldn't because of that padding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would've been a goal if the stuffing was in the way. Judges  
decided replays were inconclusive, so they couldn't award Colorado 
the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw the puck go in,'' Kamensky said. ``I think it's a  
goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten minutes later, Colorado made it 1-1 on Forsberg's  
playoff-leading seventh goal. He flicked in the rebound of a shot 
by Kamensky that Belfour had blocked. 
</P>
<P>
	The roles were reversed on the winning goal, with Kamensky  
knocking in his own rebound of Forsberg's miss with 5:58 left in 
regulation. Unlike the waved-off goal, Kamensky had no idea what 
happened on this play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw lots of sticks,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The victory was Colorado's seventh straight on the road in the  
playoffs. Dallas had won its first five home playoff games and nine 
straight at Reunion Arena counting the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-seeded Stars are down in a series for the first time  
since Detroit took a 2-1 lead in last year's Western Conference 
finals. The Red Wings won in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	Five of the Stars' eight victories this postseason have come  
when they were down in the third period and they made quite a run 
at it after Kamensky's goal. But Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy was 
at his best in the final minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to get in front of the net and then we've got to  
keep firing away,'' Dallas defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``We had 
chances at the end, but we didn't get second and third whacks at 
it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
