<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Police Torture Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Key developments in alleged police torture case:  
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 9, 1997: Police from Brooklyn's 70th Precinct are called to  
quell pre-dawn melee outside a club. In a scuffle, officers arrest 
Abner Louima. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers Thomas Wiese and Charles Schwarz handcuff Louima and  
put him in squad car. Officers Justin Volpe and Thomas Bruder 
follow in another car. 
</P>
<P>
	At the station, officers pull Louima's trousers down to ``search  
for contraband.'' Authorities say Schwarz takes him to a bathroom 
and Volpe follows. The two beat Louima, warning him not to tell 
anyone before Volpe sodomizes Louima with a stick, prosecutors 
allege. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors find that Louima has colon and bladder injuries from a  
blunt instrument. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 13: Volpe arrested on state charges of sex abuse and  
assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 15: Schwarz arrested on sex abuse and first-degree assault  
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 16: An estimated 4,000 protesters march on the 70th  
Precinct, shouting insults at officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 18: Wiese and Bruder arrested as alleged participants.  
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 28: Johnnie Cochran, lead defense lawyer in the O.J.  
Simpson case, joins legal team representing Louima in a 
multimillion-dollar civil suit against police and the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Feb. 26, 1998: Federal authorities take over case, charging the  
four officers in a civil rights indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	May 6, 1999: Louima testifies that police officers took turns  
beating him before one rammed a stick up his rectum. 
</P>
<P>
	May 17, 1999: Officer Mark Schofield testifies that he heard  
Volpe say ``I broke a man down'' and that Volpe borrowed a pair of 
gloves from Schofield before the attack and returned them covered 
with blood. 
</P>
<P>
	May 24, 1999: Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, tells judge Volpe  
will plead guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 12:13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Schedules 64 Exhibition Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The return of the Cleveland Browns and the  
return of instant replay will mark the opening weekend of the NFL 
64-game exhibition season, beginning Aug. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns, now an expansion team but wearing their old brown,  
orange and white colors, will mark their return against the Dallas 
Cowboys Monday night, Aug. 9, in the nationally televised Hall of 
Fame game at Canton, Ohio. It is the first time the Hall of Fame 
game to be played on a Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Browns were the home team for the first Monday night game  
ever in 1970, beating the New York Jets 31-21. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibition season begins with the two-time Super Bowl  
champions, the Denver Broncos, meeting the San Diego Chargers in 
the American Bowl at Sydney, Australia, plus Indianapolis at 
Chicago and Oakland at St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver also will face the Green Bay Packers, their opponents in  
the 1998 Super Bowl, at Madison, Wis., Aug. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	Two stadiums will debut this summer. The Browns will open the  
new 69,000-seat Cleveland Stadium Aug. 21 against the Minnesota 
Vikings, and on Aug. 27, the Tennessee Titans will debut in their 
67,000-seat stadium in Nashville against the Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	Instant replay will be used in 63 of the exhibition games, the  
exception being the game in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, 11 exhibition games will be nationally televised,  
capped by the Aug. 30 game between San Francisco and Oakland -- the 
first preseason meeting between the Bay Area rivals in six years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
