<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aguilera Hopes To Save Cubs' Pen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Finding Wrigley Field was no problem for Rick  
Aguilera. In fact, he had more trouble locating the bathroom in his 
new home clubhouse than he did driving to work. All part of a 
fitting-in process Monday for the Chicago Cubs' new closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Just the sight of the tall, goateed Aguilera is a relief for a  
team whose bullpen has blown 11 of 22 save chances this season and 
whose intended closer, Rod Beck, struggled greatly before 
undergoing elbow surgery last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sends a surge of energy though our clubhouse,'' Cubs  
manager Jim Riggleman said before Monday's game with Florida. 
``It's been uplifting for the club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera wanted to stay with the Minnesota Twins and finish his  
career as a closer. But when trade rumors began before spring 
training, he did some checking and after talking with Chicago 
starter Kevin Tapani, one of his best friends, he eventually 
designated the Cubs as a team he'd join. 
</P>
<P>
	``He asked what the team was like and I said it was like the  
team we had in Minnesota in the early 90s,'' Tapani said. ``Guys 
who play hard, get along and are winners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera's reasons for choosing Chicago, he said, were numerous:  
Some of his former teammates included Tapani, Gary Gaetti, reliever 
Dan Serafini and even team GM Ed Lynch from his days with the New 
York Mets. He also called Wrigley Field his favorite park in the 
majors. And he and Tapani's family are extremely close. 
</P>
<P>
	After earlier waiving a no-trade clause, Aguilera was dealt to  
Chicago last week along with Scott Downs for minor league pitchers 
Jason Ryan and Kyle Lohse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not coming here to replace Rod and I'm not coming here  
saying I have to close,'' Aguilera said. ``I told Riggs I came here 
to do whatever I can to help. I hope I'm not expected to come here 
and save every game because I'm not. I'm going to have bad days 
like everybody else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera, 37, is 19 saves shy of 300 and had a 1.27 ERA with a  
3-1 record and six saves when he left the Twins. He's pitched one 
inning so far with the Cubs. 
</P>
<P>
	A closer's life can change in a hurry. With one pitch.  
</P>
<P>
	After saving 51 games last season, Beck blew four saves in 11  
chances, had a 10.54 ERA and was 2-4, bringing out the boos birds. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife mentioned that, that they've really been getting on  
Rod Beck after the kind of season he had last year,'' Aguilera 
said. ``I played in New York where there are serious fans and it's 
something I can't control. I hope to pitch well and contribute. If 
that doesn't seem to materialize and I'm booed, we'll have to get 
through that. We'll see what happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera is also well aware that Beck, who underwent  
arthroscopic surgery, is expected to return before the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally I hope nothing is going to create a conflict  
personally between him and me,'' Aguilera said. ``I hope he is back 
as quickly as he can be and we can work together out of the 
bullpen, however Jim wants to work the bullpen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:51:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers' Sign Leetch to Big Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Brian Leetch is staying with the New York  
Rangers with a new, beefed up contract that reportedly will make 
him the highest paid defenseman in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers made the announcement at a news conference Monday,  
but declined to discuss terms of the deal in which Leetch's 
reported annual salary of $8.75 million would make him best paid 
player in team history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can tell you, and it may not show outwardly, I'm very  
excited to stay in New York,'' Leetch said at the news conference. 
``My family and friends are excited. They love coming to the 
Garden, they love everything about New York, they love rooting for 
the Rangers. This is a great day for me and my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been reports for weeks that Leetch will get $35  
million over four years. 
</P>
<P>
	It was either that or lose him to free agency.  
</P>
<P>
	Several teams were interested in Leetch, who has won the Norris  
Trophy as the NHL's top defenseman two times and generally regarded 
as one of the best players in the game for 12 years. Had he decided 
to test the free-agent market, there was speculation he could 
become hockey's first $10 million-a-year player. 
</P>
<P>
	With the retirement of Wayne Gretzky, and the Rangers having  
missed the playoffs for a second year in a row, it became critical 
for the team to sign Leetch, their captain and highest profile 
player along with goaltender Mike Richter. Richter is currently 
under a long-term contract signed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud to say we've signed the guy who is the foundation of  
the franchise,'' Madison Square Garden president Dave Checketts 
said. ``The first item on the agenda was to sign Brian Leetch. We 
made this a priority and now it's done and congratulations to 
(Rangers general manager) Neil (Smith) and to Brian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Re-signing Leetch will go a long way toward restoring the  
Rangers' credibility in the NHL and perhaps help in their search 
for some fresh free-agent talent to get them back in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those expected to be available when the free-agent market  
opens on July 1 are Colorado's Theo Fleury and San Jose's Vincent 
Damphousse. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch is third on the Rangers' career scoring list with 177  
goals and 578 assists for 755 points -- leading all defensemen in 
the team's history. This past season, Leetch totaled 55 points -- 
fifth among NHL defensemen. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch had said all along that he wanted to continue playing in  
New York. He has been one of the Rangers' top players since joining 
them after the 1988 Olympics, and played a starring role when the 
Rangers won the Stanley Cup in 1994. That year, Leetch won the Conn 
Smythe Trophy as the MVP of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch has been a star in the NHL since beginning his career in  
New York 12 seasons ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``To stay in one place for your career is something to take  
pride in,'' Leetch said. ``I've got enough money to last myself and 
my family a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He won the Calder Trophy as the league's rookie of the year in  
1988-89 and then two Norris Trophies as the league's top 
defenseman, in 1992 and 1997. It was also in 1992 and 1997 that 
Leetch was voted onto the NHL's first all-star team. In addition, 
Leetch at the age of 31 has already played in seven All-Star Games. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1991-92 season, he pulled off a rarity for a defenseman  
when he reached the 100-point mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 16:11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Report: China has US 'Front' Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- China secretly controls several thousand  
American ``front companies'' to obtain U.S. technology for military 
purposes, a congressional report says. It's part of a 700-page 
document to be issued tomorrow by a special House committee 
investigating espionage and U.S. technology losses to China, 
officials familiar with the report said today. The report describes 
a ``blurring of commerce and intelligence operations'' by China 
that poses an unprecedented challenge to U.S. efforts to keep its 
military-related secrets, said congressional sources. Problems with 
lax security at U.S. weapons labs are also described in the report. 

</P>
<P>
	Reno Vows To Stay  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Attorney General Janet Reno made clear today  
that she isn't resigning over the handling of allegations of 
Chinese nuclear espionage. ``I'm right here, going strong,'' she 
said. Her future was questioned by Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., 
who has been a vocal defender of President Clinton. Reno ouster had 
been sought during the past two years by some Republicans in 
Congress angered by her refusal to turn her campaign finance 
investigation over to an independent counsel. 

</P>
<P>
	Schools May Be Liable in Harassment  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court ruled 5-4 today that schools  
can be sued when officials fail to stop students from sexually 
harassing each other. Schools -- from elementary to college -- that 
accept federal money can be forced to pay victims of such 
harassment. The court also decided that police who let the news 
media accompany them into people's homes to observe arrests or 
searches can be sued for violating the Constitution's Fourth 
Amendment protection against unreasonable searches. It also turned 
down an appeal by a Maine dentist who was sued for refusing to 
treat a woman in his office because she has the virus that causes 
AIDS. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Says Kosovo Plight Is 'Worse'  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Hitting power plants and airfields  
again, NATO said today there were signs Yugoslav strongman Slobodan 
Milosevic was ``cracking'' after two months of airstrikes. A U.N. 
team, meanwhile, found the humanitarian situation worse than 
expected in Kosovo. Visits to more than seven Kosovo towns over 
three days showed conditions in the province to be ``a lot worse 
than we feared,'' said Sergio de Mello, head of the U.N. 
fact-finding mission. ``Everything indicates that there is an 
attempt to displace, ethnically cleanse Kosovo,'' he said, calling 
the scale of the refugee crisis ``gigantic.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Accused Gunman's Mom Apologizes  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The mother of the teen accused of shooting  
six fellow students at his high school apologized to the victims 
today and thanked the assistant principal who stopped her son from 
committing suicide. In a tearful interview on CNN, Mae Dean Daniele 
said: ``We grieve for each one of you and we pray for a full 
recovery.... We thank God that all the children are alive.'' 
Heritage High School students returned to class for the first time 
since last week's shooting in suburban Atlanta. 

</P>
