<HEADLINE> Today's Supreme Court Rulings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court today:  
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled that educators who fail to stop students from sexually  
harassing other students may be violating a federal anti-bias law 
and could be forced to pay the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	--Held that police can be sued for letting TV camera crews and  
other journalists accompany them into private homes to observe 
arrests or searches. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled that the Federal Trade Commission has authority to  
regulate at least some nonprofit professional groups, such as 
dental associations, in an effort to protect competition. 
</P>
<P>
	--Decided, 5-4, that people who invoke a much-used civil rights  
law and sue in federal court over local governmental land-use 
regulations can get a jury trial. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rejected the appeal of a Maine dentist who had lost a lawsuit  
filed by a woman he refused to treat in his office because she was 
infected with the AIDS virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
