<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 19:41:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Ride-Alongs Violate Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police violate people's privacy rights when  
they bring TV camera crews or other journalists into homes during 
arrests or searches, the Supreme Court ruled Monday in a pair of 
decisions that could put a crimp in popular true-life TV shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Police who carry out such media ``ride-alongs'' can be sued for  
violating the Constitution's Fourth Amendment ban on unreasonable 
searches and seizures, the court said in the two unanimous rulings. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, writing for the court in  
cases from Maryland and Montana, cited the ``centuries-old 
principle of respect for the privacy of the home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Surely the possibility of good public relations for the police  
is simply not enough, standing alone, to justify the ride-along 
intrusion into a private home,'' Rehnquist wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even the need for accurate reporting on police issues in  
general'' does not justify allowing journalists to accompany police 
onto private property, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union said the ruling means police  
must be guided by the Fourth Amendment, not by the demands of the 
``infotainment'' industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government is not allowed to make a display of you,''  
added Joshua Dratel of the National Association of Criminal Defense 
Lawyers. The group supported a Montana couple who sued after 
government agents brought along a CNN camera crew while conducting 
a raid on their ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	The rulings still will allow media to accompany police officers  
as long as the journalists stay outside when officers enter private 
homes, said attorney Richard Cordray, who represented the police 
officers in both cases. 
</P>
<P>
	But attorney Lee Levine, representing The Associated Press and  
other news organizations who sided with law enforcement officers, 
said the rulings may discourage police from allowing the media to 
accompany them even for permissible purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's bad for the public in the sense that the public won't get  
to see, through the press' eyes, that important aspect of the 
government's work,'' Levine said. 
</P>
<P>
	Milton Coleman, deputy managing editor of The Washington Post,  
stressed that the ruling concerns people's homes and does not 
restrict reporters' right to join police officers at work, or 
photographers' right to shoot pictures in public places. The Post 
was involved in one of the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Up until now the law in the area has not been clearly  
established,'' he said. ``We are encouraged that the court 
recognizes the important purpose that is served by the media role 
in providing the public accurate coverage of police activities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A CNN spokeswoman, Sue Binford, said, ``We are studying how the  
ruling might apply to our case, which is still pending. We will 
reserve any comment until the appropriate time in our litigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Langley, producer of the Fox television show ``COPS'' said  
Monday it will be ``business as usual'' for the program because it 
``routinely obtains permission when filming on private property and 
also obtains releases from everyone involved in the program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But police departments said the ruling has reinforced a move  
toward limits on filming and could lead to more. 
</P>
<P>
	The scene is repeated countless times daily across America:  
Police officers burst into a house or some other private place in 
search of a quarry. A court-issued warrant or emergency 
circumstances give police that authority, but the justices said 
bringing along outsiders is another matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite that holding, the justices ruled 8-1 that the police  
officers in the two cases cannot be sued because it was not 
``clearly established'' in 1992 and 1993 -- when the raids occurred 
-- that such access was unlawful. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Maryland case, Montgomery County sheriff's deputies and  
deputy U.S. marshals took along a Washington Post reporter and 
photographer when they entered Charles and Geraldine Wilson's home 
in Rockville early one morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers wanted to arrest the Wilsons' fugitive adult son,  
who was not at their home but turned himself in later at his 
parents' urging. The photographs, one showing Wilson wearing only 
his undershorts with a police officer's gun at his head, were not 
published. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the Wilsons'  
lawsuit against the officers, and the Supreme Court upheld that 
dismissal. However, the Wilsons also are pursuing a separate 
lawsuit against the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montana case was filed by Paul and Erma Berger against  
federal agents and a prosecutor who let a CNN reporter and camera 
crew accompany them to the couple's ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	Government agents were seeking evidence of eagle poisoning, but  
Paul Berger was convicted only of improper use of a pesticide, a 
minor offense. CNN later aired footage of the raid. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled the Bergers could  
sue the government officials involved in the raid as well as CNN. 
The Supreme Court ruled the Bergers could not sue the officials, 
but it has not yet acted on CNN's separate appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Justice John Paul Stevens voted to let both lawsuits  
proceed to trial. He said the constitutional violations were clear 
in 1992 and 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
