<HEADLINE> Gloria Estefan Releasing Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Gloria Estefan might not have had a career in  
music if it wasn't for the influence of her maternal grandmother. 
</P>
<P>
	``I studied psychology, communications, and languages, but she  
repeatedly told me that I would be happiest doing something I 
loved,'' Ms. Estefan writes of Consuelo Garcia in a new book, ``The 
Person Who Changed My Life: Prominent Americans Recall Their 
Mentors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book was to be released today at a party in New York. First  
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, who wrote the introduction, was to 
attend, along with Tony Bennett, Helen Gurley Brown, Joy Behar and 
Stanley Tucci. 
</P>
<P>
	Proceeds from the book, compiled by Matilda Cuomo, wife of  
former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, are to benefit Mrs. Cuomo's 
organization, Mentoring USA, which matches adult volunteers with 
at-risk children. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Estefan writes that she joined a band as a hobby, but her  
grandmother knew otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandmother told me after I had been accepted,'' she  
recalled, ``that I had probably taken the most important step of my 
life.'' 
</P>
