<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kmart Could Get Stuck With Leases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Kmart Corp. unloaded its Builders Square home  
improvement stores two years ago, but could be burdened with $761 
million in store leases if the new owners fail to keep up with its 
payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger Co. is struggling with widening losses and a cutback  
in credit from some of its vendors. In addition, the Largo, 
Md.-based company recently missed a large payment on its debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Such problems may cause Hechinger to miss its lease payments.  
That would leave Troy, Mich.-based Kmart with the brunt of the 
financial obligation. 
</P>
<P>
	Builders Square was one of four subsidiaries that Kmart sold or  
spun off in recent years as it moved to focus on its discount 
stores. Under the deals, Kmart guaranteed leases now worth $1.2 
billion, of which $761 million is for Builders Square, according to 
a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither company returned calls for comment placed Monday by The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	After closely held Hechinger bought Builders Square in 1997, it  
merged its stores with two other chains to create the third-largest 
home-improvement retailer behind Home Depot and Lowe's. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Home Depot and Lowe's have added stores and boosted  
profits, while Hechinger has struggled. The company has been 
remodeling stores and shedding others, ending April with 206 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	In filings with the SEC earlier this month, Hechinger said it  
lost $208 million before one-time expenses on $509 million in 
revenue in the three months ending in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's outlook worsened Friday, when Standard &AMP; Poor's  
downgraded much of Hechinger's debt after it put off a $4.7 million 
interest payment. Standard &AMP; Poor's said in a news release that it 
thought Hechinger would miss other debt payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart, in an April SEC filing, said it had helped finance a new  
$50 million credit line for Hechinger. The company, however, said 
it had not set aside any money for lease guarantees, but would do 
so ``at the time the obligation was determined to be probable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the problem has the potential to hurt Kmart's bottom line,  
analysts said it was not an immediate threat to the company. If 
Kmart did have to cover the lease payments, it could threaten the 
retailer's recent turnaround, with its profits and sales steadily 
rising over the past few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors need to be aware there would be a chain of events or  
several circumstances before there would be an ultimate liability 
at Kmart,'' said Roney &AMP; Co. analyst Scott Campbell. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said if Hechinger failed, Kmart could take several  
steps to cover its costs, such as subleasing. Meanwhile, he said, 
the outlook for Hechinger was dim. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look to Home Depot and Lowe's. They're thought to be the  
two consolidators going forward,'' Campbell said. ``They're just 
dominating the segment.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 05:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Targets Unbuckled Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 5,700 law enforcement agencies  
nationwide are cooperating in a renewed campaign to ensure that 
children are properly up buckled up when riding in automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	From today through the Memorial Day weekend, officers will make  
a special effort to ticket motorists if children are not restrained 
in safety seats or seat belts, said the Air Bag and Seat Belt 
Safety Campaign, sponsor of the semiannual crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the possibility of being in a crash does not motivate  
people to buckle up their children, the probability of receiving a 
ticket has proven to be a powerful motivator,'' Govs. John Engler 
of Michigan and Howard Dean of Vermont said in a recent letter 
asking colleagues for their support. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of 10 children killed in crashes were riding unrestrained,  
according to federal figures. About half of those children would be 
alive if they were restrained properly, the National Highway 
Traffic Safety Administration estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	Car crashes are the leading cause of death for children under  
15. In 1997, more than 2,000 children were killed and 320,000 
injured in traffic crashes, according to federal statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	All states have laws requiring that children younger than 4 be  
restrained while riding in a car, and many states also require that 
children younger than 16 wear seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	But 27 states with seat belt laws for those older children do  
not cover all youngsters under 16 when they ride in the back seat. 
</P>
<P>
	All states allow police to stop and ticket motorists solely  
because the youngest children are not wearing a seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 15 states and the District of Columbia have primary seat  
belt laws for adults and older children. Other states have 
secondary seat belt laws that require police to first pull 
motorists over for some other traffic offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The safety campaign also seeks to persuade adults to buckle up  
because research has shown a belted driver is three times more 
likely to restrain a child. Between 60 percent and 70 percent of 
Americans wear seat belts, according to federal and state 
statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators credited the campaign with helping to buckle  
up 19 million more Americans last year, the largest single-year 
increase in seat belt use in years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990524.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 17:11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NLRB Rejects N.J. Doctors' Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	An attempt by hundreds of physicians to form the nation's first  
union for doctors in private practice was rejected Monday for a 
second time by a federal labor regulator. 
</P>
<P>
	Dorothy L. Moore-Duncan, the National Labor Relations Board's  
regional director in Philadelphia, said the doctors couldn't 
unionize because they were independent contractors, not employees 
of the HMO, AmeriHealth Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Food and Commercial Workers Local 56, which is  
seeking to represent the doctors, was considering an appeal of the 
decision. The union also said it may try to pass federal 
legislation that would give physicians the right to organize. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that our efforts along with the other unions have  
brought this to a head,'' said Anthony Cinaglia, president of the 
Pennsauken, N.J.-based union. ``We believe there's been a moral 
victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While physician unions do exist, they involve doctors employed  
directly by hospitals or clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the New Jersey doctors are eventually successful,  
unionization may not be an answer to their problems, said Uwe 
Reinhardt, a Princeton University health economist. 
</P>
<P>
	``They think they can as a union sit there and shove a unionized  
fee scale down the throat of the insurer,'' said Reinhardt. He 
added that it would never be effective because insurance carriers 
in turn would band together to negotiate with the doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just simply can't create a physician monopoly,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Moore-Duncan had also ruled against the union last year but  
was ordered to hold a hearing after the doctors appealed. She heard 
14 days of testimony, the first hearings ever before the NLRB on 
the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're disappointed. We feel it should have gone the  
other way,'' Cinaglia said. ``We understand that they're 
interpreting the law very narrowly. Perhaps we need to change the 
law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union filed a petition in 1997 seeking to have family  
doctors and specialists in Atlantic and Cape May counties declared 
employees of the HMO. Initially, only AmeriHealth was targeted, but 
the union had planned to target other HMOs if the strategy proved 
successful. 
</P>
<P>
	AmeriHealth insisted the doctors are independent medical  
practitioners because most of their income comes from other sources 
and the doctors provide their own facilities, equipment and support 
staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are, of course, pleased with the decision,'' AmeriHealth  
chairman and chief executive G. Fred DiBona, Jr., said in a 
statement. ``This has been a costly and time-consuming effort for 
everyone, but clarifies a question of considerable importance to 
consumers, providers and insurers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AmeriHealth, a subsidiary of Independence Blue Cross of  
Philadelphia, covers 270,000 New Jersey residents. 
</P>
<P>
	HMOs have controlled skyrocketing health costs by preventing  
unneeded treatments and watching fees charged by doctors and 
hospitals. The doctors say forming a union would return their 
control over medical decisions and improve quality of care. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has never been a question of quality care,'' DiBona said.  
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Frederick Nahas, of Somers Point, a vascular surgeon who  
helped organize colleagues to join the union, disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, patients are still going to be denied care in  
lieu of profiteering that's going on by the HMOs,'' he said. 
``That's really the bottom line: HMOs are trading patient lives and 
limbs for profits,'' said Nahas. 
</P>
<P>
	In her ruling, Moore-Duncan said the doctors still exert  
substantial control how they provide services to the HMO, have 
their own practices independent of the health maintenance 
organization, and have proprietary interests in their practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The union has until June 7 to request a review from the  
five-member NLRB in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. antitrust law prohibits independent contractors from  
banding together to set prices and terms for their work, but the 
NLRB has allowed unions for some whose work primarily is dictated 
by others, including entertainers, athletes, cab drivers and, most 
recently, couriers. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 38,000 to 45,000 doctors -- about 6 percent of the  
nation's doctors -- belong to unions, up from about 25,000 two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Medical Association, a trade group that represents  
about half of the nation's doctors, shares the doctors' complaints 
about HMOs but has long rejected traditional labor unions. AMA 
officials declined to comment on the ruling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
